{"title_page": "Scott Hall", "text_new": "{{short description|American professional wrestler}}\n{{about|the professional wrestler}}\n{{Redirect|Razor Ramon|other uses|Razor Ramon (disambiguation)}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox professional wrestler\n|name        = Scott Hall\n|image       = Scott Hall with Paul Billets (cropped).jpg\n|image_size  = \n|alt         =\n|caption     = Hall in 1998\n|birthname   = Scott Oliver Hall<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://windsorstar.com/arts-2/scott-hall-wrestled-with-life-as-razor-ramon|title=Scott Hall wrestled with life as Razor Ramon &#124; Windsor Star|date=October 17, 2013}}</ref>\n|spouse      = {{Plainlist|Dana Burgio ({{abbr|m.|married}} 1990\u2013{{abbr|div.|divorced}} 1998; {{abbr|m.|married}} 1999\u2013{{abbr|div.|divorced}} 2001)<br>{{marriage|Jessica Hart|2006|2007|reason=divorced}}}}\n|children    = 2, including [[Cody Hall]]\n|names       = The Diamond Studd<ref name=\"OWOW\"/><br>Razor Ramon<ref name=\"OWOW\"/><br>'''Scott Hall'''<ref name=\"OWOW\"/><br>Starship Coyote<ref name=\"OWOW\"/><br>Texas Scott<ref name=\"OWOW\"/>\n|height      = 6 ft 7 in<ref name=\"WWE\"/>\n|weight      = 287 lb<ref name=\"WWE\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/superstars/razor-ramon|title=Razor Ramon bio|publisher=[[WWE]]|accessdate=April 30, 2018}}</ref>\n|birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|1958|10|20|mf=y}}<ref name=\"OWOW\"/>\n|birth_place = [[St. Mary's County, Maryland]], U.S.\n|resides     = [[Duluth, Georgia]], U.S.<ref>[http://podcastone.com/Steve-Austin-Show?showAllEpisodes=true Steve Austin Show podcast, \"SAS-EP#32 \u2013 Razor Ramon\" (21:50)]. Podcastone.com. Retrieved on November 29, 2013.</ref>\n|billed      = '''[[Chuluota, Florida]]'''<br>[[Miami]], [[Florida]]<ref name=\"WWE\"/>\n|trainer     = [[Hiro Matsuda]] \n|debut       = 1984<ref>[http://www.wrestlingdata.com/index.php?befehl=bios&wrestler=44 Scott Hall's profile at]. Wrestlingdata.com. Retrieved on November 29, 2013.</ref>\n|retired     = 2010<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.grunge.com/90291/retired-wrestlers-completely-unrecognizable-today/|title=Retired wrestlers who are completely unrecognizable today|first=Jason|last=Iannone|website=Grunge.com|date=October 10, 2017 |accessdate=April 5, 2020}}</ref>\n}}\n'''Scott Oliver Hall''' (born October 20, 1958) is an American retired [[Professional wrestling|professional wrestler]]. He is best known for his work with the World Wrestling Federation (WWF, now [[WWE]]) as '''Razor Ramon''' and with World Championship Wrestling ([[World Championship Wrestling|WCW]]) under his real name.\n\nBeginning with his time in the [[American Wrestling Association]] (AWA), Hall maintained a perennially high profile as a wrestler, as he became a [[List of WWE Intercontinental Champions|four time]] [[WWE Intercontinental Championship|WWF Intercontinental Champion]] (a record from 1995 to 1999), a [[List of WWE United States Champions|two-time]] [[WWE United States Championship|WCW United States Heavyweight Champion]], a [[List of WCW World Television Champions|one-time]] [[WCW World Television Championship|WCW World Television Champion]], and a nine-time [[World tag team championship|world tag team champion]] ([[List of WCW World Tag Team Champions|seven times in WCW]], [[List of TNA World Tag Team Champions|once in TNA]], and [[AWA World Tag Team Championship|once in the AWA]]). In addition, Hall is a two-time [[world champion]], having won the [[WWC Universal Heavyweight Championship]] and the [[USWA Unified World Heavyweight Championship]]. He is also notable for being a founding member of the [[New World Order (professional wrestling)|New World Order (nWo)]]. On April 5, 2014, Hall was inducted individually into the [[WWE Hall of Fame]] as Razor Ramon, and he will be inducted a second time (this time under his real name) in 2020 as a member of nWo, together with fellow former stablemates [[Hulk Hogan]], [[Kevin Nash]] and [[Sean Waltman]].\n\n== Early life ==\nHall was born in St. Mary's County, Maryland. He grew up as an [[army brat]] and moved once every year before he was fifteen.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://slam.canoe.com/Slam/Wrestling/2016/06/24/22646003.html|title=Scott Hall once again the Bad Guy|author=Murphy, Jan|work=Slam! Wrestling|publisher=[[Canadian Online Explorer]]|date=April 3, 2016|accessdate=September 12, 2016}}</ref> He attended [[high school]] in [[Munich]], [[West Germany]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=SHJsJPpIXWg|title=Scott Hall reveals he'd eat out Paige + Talks Sexcapades & Ring Rats|last=Controversial Wrestling Shoots|date=November 14, 2016|publisher=|via=YouTube}}</ref>\n\n== Professional wrestling career ==\n\n=== National Wrestling Alliance (1984) ===\nHall began his career in 1984 in the [[National Wrestling Alliance]]'s (NWA) Florida territory [[Championship Wrestling from Florida]] (CWF) and soon began a [[Feud (professional wrestling)|feud]] with [[Dusty Rhodes (wrestler)|Dusty Rhodes]].<ref name=\"scottbio\">{{cite web|url=http://www.thescotthall.com/about.html|title=Biography|work=Scott Hall's Official Website|accessdate=June 18, 2008}}</ref> He and [[Dan Spivey]] trained together in Florida (mainly under Rhodes, but also under [[Mike Rotunda]] and [[Barry Windham]]). When it was time for the two to debut as a tag team, Rhodes sent them to work in [[Jim Crockett]]'s [[Charlotte, North Carolina]] based territory. They debuted as American Starship, Hall under the ring name Starship Coyote and Spivey under the ring name Starship Eagle.<ref name=\"OWOW\">{{cite web|url=http://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/profiles/s/scott-hall.html|title=Scott Hall Profile|publisher=Online World of Wrestling|accessdate=June 18, 2008}}</ref><ref name=\"earlycareer\">{{cite web|url=http://www.accelerator3359.com/Wrestling/bios/hall.html#beginning|title=Scott Hall's Early Career|work=Accelerator's Wrestling Rollercoaster|accessdate=June 18, 2008}}</ref>\n\nAt first, American Starship were booked to wrestle infrequently; so much so that the two were given ground crew jobs for the Charlotte Orioles (which Jim Crockett owned at the time). When they did get in the ring, it was with little success. The highlight of their stay in Crockett's [[Jim Crockett Promotions|Mid Atlantic Championship Wrestling]] was a losing challenge to [[Arn Anderson|Arn]] and [[Ole Anderson]] for the NWA National Tag Team Championship. After leaving Crockett, the duo joined [[Bob Geigel]]'s [[Heart of America Sports Attractions|NWA Central States]] territory (based in Kansas City) in 1985.\n\nThey received a shot at NWA Central States Tag Team Champions [[Marty Jannetty]] and \"Bulldog\" Bob Brown, but lost the match. Dan Spivey's stay in the Central States territory was brief. He returned to the Carolinas and Crockett, [[Job (professional wrestling)|jobbing]] in the freshly rebranded [[Jim Crockett Promotions]] as \"American Starship\" Eagle. Hall, meanwhile, stayed in Central States, receiving a solid [[Push (professional wrestling)|push]].\n\n=== American Wrestling Association (1985 - 1989) ===\nHall joined the [[American Wrestling Association]] (AWA) in 1985, where he wrestled as \"Magnum\" Scott Hall and, later, \"Big\" Scott Hall. He wrestled as a [[Face (professional wrestling)|babyface]] wrestler.<ref name=\"OWOW\"/><ref name=\"awa\">{{cite web|url=http://www.accelerator3359.com/Wrestling/bios/hall.html#awa|title=Scott Hall's AWA Career|work=Accelerator's Wrestling Rollercoaster|accessdate=June 18, 2008}}</ref> [[Verne Gagne]], the owner and promoter of the AWA, had wanted to push Hall to the same heights as he had [[Hulk Hogan]], following Hogan's departure for [[Vince McMahon]]'s [[WWE|World Wrestling Federation]] (WWF).<ref name=\"scottbio\"/><ref name=\"awa\"/> Gagne had Hall use mannerisms and moves similar to Hogan.<ref name=\"scottbio\"/> Hall also travelled to Japan, where he wrestled several matches for [[New Japan Pro-Wrestling]] (NJPW) between 1987 and 1990.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.profightdb.com/wrestlers/scott-hall-147.html?prom_id=27|title=NJPW matches wrestled by Scott Hall|publisher=ProFightDB|accessdate=September 4, 2019}}</ref>\n\nHall formed a tag team with his more experienced friend [[Curt Hennig]], whom he later would credit for cultivating his early professional wrestling career.<ref>Keller, Wade [http://www.blogtalkradio.com/pro-wrestling-torch/2013/05/03/pwtorch-livecast PWTorch Livecast \u2013 Wade Keller Interviews Scott Hall] PWTorch (May 3, 2013). Retrieved August 9, 2013.</ref> The team defeated [[Jimmy Garvin]] and [[Steve Regal]] for the [[AWA World Tag Team Championship]] on January 18, 1986, in a 58-minute match in [[Albuquerque, New Mexico]].<ref name=\"OWOW\"/><ref name=\"awatag\"/> The champions defended against such challengers as [[Buddy Rose]] and [[Doug Somers]], [[John Nord|Nord the Barbarian]] and [[Boris Zhukov]], and [[Bill Irwin (wrestler)|Bill]] and [[Scott Irwin]].<ref name=\"OWOW\"/><ref name=\"scottbio\"/><ref name=\"awa\"/> They lost the belts to Rose and Somers by [[countout]] (an unusual and unexplained deviation from the standard rule of pro wrestling) on May 17, after interference by [[Colonel DeBeers]].<ref name=\"scottbio\"/> After losing the title, Hall and Hennig soon parted ways. Hall then received shots at the [[AWA World Heavyweight Championship]], against [[Stan Hansen]] and [[Rick Martel]].<ref name=\"scottbio\"/><ref name=\"awa\"/> Although Gagne wanted to put the belt on Hall, Hall hated the cold weather in the territory, recognized the AWA as a \"sinking ship,\" and left for the NWA in 1989.<ref name=\"scottbio\"/> The AWA folded the following year.\n\n=== World Championship Wrestling (1989) ===\nHall was brought into the NWA's [[World Championship Wrestling]] (WCW) territory by [[Jim Ross]] in 1989, as part of the NWA's initiative to develop new, young stars (also including [[Brian Pillman]] and [[Sid Eudy|Sid Vicious]]).<ref name=\"scottbio\"/> He made his debut on the June 3 edition of '''World Championship Wrestling''' (the predecessor to WCW Saturday Night) in a vignette that showed Scott \"Gator\" Hall swimming and playing volleyball at a beach, riding boats, fishing, and scaring alligators. His in-ring debut came on June 16 on a house show in Cleveland, OH, where he teamed with [[Randy Rose]] in a losing effort against [[WCW World Tag-Team Champions]] {[The Freebirds]]. While waiting for his first television match, he continued to wrestle on the road and was winless in tag-team and singles action, facing [[Norman}}, The Freebirds, and [[Dan Spivey]]. Hall finally gained his first victory on June 29 when he pinned Rip Morgan in Salisbury, MD, and then entered a successful house show series with [[Bill Irwin]].\n\nHis television debut finally came on the July 9 edition of World Championship Wrestling where he was pinned by [[The Great Muta]]. On the July 9 edition of [[WCW Pro]] he faced [[Terry Funk]] and was defeated.<ref>http://www.thehistoryofwwe.com/wcw89.htm</ref>His PPV debut came at [[The Great American Bash 1989|The Great American Bash: The Glory Days]], where he participated in a [[Battle royal (professional wrestling)|King of the Hill battle royal]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.prowrestlinghistory.com/supercards/usa/wcw/gabash.html#89|title=The Great American Bash 1989: The Glory Days results|work=Wrestling Supercards and Tournaments|accessdate=June 27, 2008}}</ref> He then began [[Job (professional wrestling)|jobbing]] regularly, losing to The Great Muta, [[Mike Rotunda]], [[Sid Vicious]], [[Ron Simmons]], and [[Butch Reed]]. His final match came on November 7 when he was defeated by Butch Reed at a house show in Chicago, IL. After this he went on hiatus.<ref name=\"scottbio\"/><ref name=\"nwa\">{{cite web|url=http://www.accelerator3359.com/Wrestling/bios/hall.html#nwa|title=Scott Hall's NWA Career|work=Accelerator's Wrestling Rollercoaster|accessdate=June 28, 2008}}</ref>\n\n=== World Wrestling Federation (1990) ===\nA little over two years after having received a tryout at a house show in August 1987<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.cagematch.net/?id=1&nr=42455 |title = WWF House Show \" Events Database \" CAGEMATCH - the Internet Wrestling Database |accessdate=April 5, 2020}}</ref>, Hall received another tryout at a [[WWF Wrestling Challenge]] taping in Fort Myers, FL. He was defeated by [[Paul Roma]] and did not sign with the company at this time.<ref>http://www.thehistoryofwwe.com/90.htm</ref>\n\n=== New Japan Pro Wrestling (1990) ===\nShortly afterwards Hall joined [[New Japan Pro Wrestling]], teaming with [[Larry Cameron]] and defeating [[Hiroshi Hase]] & [[Kuniaki Kobayashi]] March 2, 1990 at Korakuen Hall in Tokyo, Japan<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.cagematch.net/?id=1&nr=60156 |title = NJPW Big Fight Series 1990 \" Events Database \" CAGEMATCH - the Internet Wrestling Database |accessdate=April 5, 2020}}</ref> He wrestled numerous times for the company, facing a diverse group of opponents including [[Bam Bam Bigelow]], [[Koji Kitao]], [[Nord the Barbarian]], and [[Shinya Hashimoto]].\n\n=== Catch Wrestling Association (1990) ===\nScott Hall, as '''Texas Scott''', competed for the [[Catch Wrestling Association]] (CWA) at the \"Catch Cup '90\" tournament on December 22, 1990 in Bremen, Germany before 6,000 fans. Hall was defeated by the Soul Taker in the tournament final. This big event featured the retirement match of [[Otto Wanz]], as well as [[Terry Funk]], Bull Power ([[Big Van Vader]]), [[Chris Benoit]], [[Dave Taylor (wrestler)|David Taylor]], [[Fit Finlay]], and [[Akira Nogami]] in action.\n\n=== World Wrestling Council (1990 - 1991) ===\nFrom 1990 to 1991, Hall had a stint in the [[Puerto Rico|Puerto Rican]] promotion [[World Wrestling Council]] (WWC).<ref name=\"nwa\"/> On March 3, he defeated [[Miguel P\u00e9rez, Jr.]] for the [[WWC Caribbean Heavyweight Championship]].<ref name=\"caribbeantitle\"/> He lost it to Super Medic III on April 20.<ref name=\"nwa\"/>\n\n=== World Championship Wrestling (1991\u20131992) ===\n{{main|Diamond Exchange#The Diamond Mine}}\nAfter wrestling a dark match on April 29, 1991 in Atlanta, GA at a taping of World Championship Wrestling<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.cagematch.net/?id=1&nr=81657 |title = WCW World Championship Wrestling \" Events Database \" CAGEMATCH - the Internet Wrestling Database |accessdate=April 5, 2020}}</ref>, Hall made his official return to WCW<ref name=\"wcw\">{{cite web|url=http://www.accelerator3359.com/Wrestling/bios/hall.html#wcw|title=Scott Hall's WCW Career (1991\u20131992)|work=Accelerator's Wrestling Rollercoaster|accessdate=June 28, 2008}}</ref> and was renamed '''The Diamond Studd''', a [[Gimmick (professional wrestling)|gimmick]] similar to [[Rick Rude]]'s (both were cocky, vain and would invite attractive [[Plant (professional wrestling)|women from the audience]] into the ring). He was [[Manager (professional wrestling)|managed]] by [[Diamond Dallas Page]], and made his first appearance on May 19 at [[SuperBrawl 1]].<ref name=\"wcw\"/> In his debut match, he [[Squash (professional wrestling)|squashed]] [[Tommy Rich]] on the June 14 episode of ''[[Clash of the Champions XV: Knocksville USA]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.prowrestlinghistory.com/supercards/usa/wcw/clash.html#XV |title=Clash of the Champions XV: Knocksville USA results |work=Wrestling Supercards and Tournaments |accessdate=June 28, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080623095650/http://www.prowrestlinghistory.com/supercards/usa/wcw/clash.html |archivedate=June 23, 2008 }}</ref> He defeated [[Tom Zenk]] at [[The Great American Bash 1991|The Great American Bash]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.prowrestlinghistory.com/supercards/usa/wcw/gabash.html#91|title=The Great American Bash 1991 results|work=Wrestling Supercards and Tournaments|accessdate=June 28, 2008}}</ref> At ''[[Clash of the Champions XVI: Fall Brawl]]'' on September 2, The Diamond Studd lost to [[Ron Simmons]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.prowrestlinghistory.com/supercards/usa/wcw/clash.html#XVI |title=Clash of the Champions XVI: Fall Brawl results |work=Wrestling Supercards and Tournaments |accessdate=June 28, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080623095650/http://www.prowrestlinghistory.com/supercards/usa/wcw/clash.html |archivedate=June 23, 2008 }}</ref> At [[Halloween Havoc 1991]], the team of Studd, [[Abdullah the Butcher]], [[Mick Foley|Cactus Jack]], and [[Big Van Vader]] lost to [[Steve Borden|Sting]], [[Jorge Gonz\u00e1lez (wrestler)|El Gigante]], and [[The Steiner Brothers]] in a \"Chamber of Horrors Match\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.prowrestlinghistory.com/supercards/usa/wcw/havoc.html#91|title=Halloween Havoc 1991: Chamber of Horrors results|work=Wrestling Supercards and Tournaments|accessdate=June 28, 2008}}</ref> On the November 19 episode of ''[[Clash of the Champions XVII]]'', Studd lost to Zenk in a rematch from The Great American Bash.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.prowrestlinghistory.com/supercards/usa/wcw/clash.html#XVII |title=Clash of the Champions XVII results |work=Wrestling Supercards and Tournaments |accessdate=June 28, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080623095650/http://www.prowrestlinghistory.com/supercards/usa/wcw/clash.html |archivedate=June 23, 2008 }}</ref>\n\nAfter an injury sidelined him for [[Starrcade (1991)|Starrcade]] in December 1991, Hall entered 1992 forming short-lived tag teams with [[Kevin Nash|Vinnie Vegas]] and [[Raven (wrestler)|Scotty Flamingo]] (as part of The Diamond Mine [[Smark|stable]]), as well as with members of [[Paul Heyman|Paul E. Dangerously]]'s [[Dangerous Alliance]].<ref name=\"wcw\"/> Hall began a feud with [[Dustin Rhodes]] in April 1992 when he interfered in two televised matches Rhodes had with [[Bobby Eaton]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thehistoryofwwe.com/wcw92.htm|title=WCW 1992|website=Thehistoryofwwe.com}}</ref> The idea of adding him to the Dangerous Alliance was contemplated, but fell through, and Hall left WCW shortly after a final televised match against Ron Campbell on May 8.<ref name=\"wcw\"/>\n\n=== World Wrestling Federation/WWF===\n==== Debut and various feuds (1992\u20131993) ====\n[[File:Razor Ramon posing.jpg|thumb|175px|left|Hall as Razor Ramon]]\nHall joined the [[WWE|World Wrestling Federation]] (WWF) later that month, as '''Razor Ramon''', a shady and stylish [[Cuban American]] bully from [[Miami]].<ref name=\"scottbio\"/><ref name=\"wwf\"/> The character was modeled after the characters [[Tony Montana]] and [[Manny Ribera]] from the movie ''[[Scarface (1983 film)|Scarface]]''.<ref name=\"wwf\"/> Ramon's nickname (The Bad Guy) and catchphrase (\"Say hello to The Bad Guy\") derive from Montana's quotes: \"Say hello to my little friend\" and \"Say goodnight to the bad guy\".<ref name=\"wwf\">{{cite web|url=http://www.accelerator3359.com/Wrestling/bios/hall.html#wwf|title=Scott Hall's WWF Career (1992)|work=Accelerator's Wrestling Rollercoaster|accessdate=June 28, 2008}}</ref> He made his first appearance in a dark match on a ''[[WWF Wrestling Challenge|Wrestling Challenge]]'' taping against Chris Hahn on May 18, 1992.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thehistoryofwwe.com/92.htm|title=History of WWE|website=Thehistoryofwwe.com|accessdate=December 6, 2015}}</ref> Later in his career, Hall claimed he pitched the idea of a ''Scarface''-like character during a meeting with [[Vince McMahon]] and [[Pat Patterson (wrestler)|Pat Patterson]], as a joke.<ref name=\"scottbio\"/> Hall quoted lines from the film with a Cuban accent and gave ideas for [[Glossary of professional wrestling terms#V|vignettes]] that would recreate several of the film's scenes, such as driving around [[South Florida metropolitan area|South Florida]] in a [[convertible]] with a [[animal print|leopard-skin]] interior.<ref name=\"scottbio\"/> Although taken right from the film, Hall claims McMahon and Patterson were nevertheless floored by the ideas and called him a \"genius\".<ref name=\"scottbio\"/> Hall later learned that McMahon and Patterson had neither seen nor heard of the film, and believed that Hall was coming up with the ideas himself. Patterson and McMahon came up with the name \"Razor\", but agreed with Hall's suggestion that it should be a nickname, and that the character should have a proper given name. Hall later asked [[Tito Santana]] for a Latino-sounding name that starts with \"R\". Santana suggested \"Ramon\", Hall brought it back to McMahon and the name stuck.<ref name=\"scottbio\"/> The Razor Ramon logo and costume were designed by [[Tom Fleming (artist)|Tom Fleming]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Never-before-seen Superstar sketches from the WWE Vault|url=http://www.wwe.com/classics/superstar-sketches-photos|website=WWE.com|accessdate=March 21, 2016}}</ref>\n\nAfter weeks of introductory vignettes, Razor Ramon made his ring debut on the August 8, 1992 episode of ''[[WWF Superstars of Wrestling|Superstars]]'', defeating local jobber Paul Van Dow with his finishing move, [[Powerbomb#Crucifix powerbomb|The Razor's Edge]] (previously called \"The Diamond Death Drop\" in WCW).<ref>{{cite web|date=July 20, 1992|url=http://www.angelfire.com/wrestling/cawthon777/superstars.htm|title=WWF Superstars (1986\u20131997)|work=Angelfire|accessdate=June 28, 2008|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080429091409/http://www.angelfire.com/wrestling/cawthon777/superstars.htm|archivedate = April 29, 2008}}</ref> Early on, Ramon wore large gold chain necklaces to the ring. While handing them to an attendant at ringside he would threaten \"Something happens to this, something gonna happen to you\", and then flick his toothpick at the helpless attendant.<ref name=\"scottbio\"/>\n\nRazor's first major [[Glossary of professional wrestling terms#A|angle]] began on the September 14 episode of ''[[WWF Prime Time Wrestling|Prime Time Wrestling]]'', when he interfered in a [[WWE World Championship|WWF Championship]] match between champion [[Randy Savage]] and [[Ric Flair]], attacking Savage on the floor and enabling Flair to win the title.<ref name=\"Flair vs Savage\">{{cite web|date=September 1, 1992|url=http://www.angelfire.com/wrestling/cawthon777/92.htm|title=WWF Show Results 1992|work=Angelfire|accessdate=June 28, 2008|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080505064406/http://www.angelfire.com/wrestling/cawthon777/92.htm|archivedate=May 5, 2008}}</ref> As a result, Razor and Savage started a [[Feud (professional wrestling)|feud]], which later involved [[The Ultimate Warrior]], after Warrior saved Savage from a post-match beating by Razor.<ref name=\"Flair vs Savage\"/> Razor and Flair were scheduled to face The Ultimate Maniacs (Savage and Warrior) at [[Survivor Series (1992)|Survivor Series]]. However, Warrior was fired from the WWF prior to the event and replaced by Flair's \"executive consultant\", [[Curt Hennig|Mr. Perfect]]. Razor and Flair lost to Savage and Perfect via disqualification, for constantly double-teaming them.<ref name=\"wwf\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/survivorseries/history/1992/results/|title=Survivor Series 1992 official results|publisher=WWE|accessdate=June 28, 2008}}</ref>\n\nWWF Champion [[Bret Hart]] was scheduled to defend his title against The Ultimate Warrior at the [[Royal Rumble (1993)|Royal Rumble]], but Razor Ramon replaced Warrior after he left the company.<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=UdSpoy6g5ZE&t=4m25s Bret Hart talks Roddy Piper & Shawn Michaels]. ''Aftermath''. [[The Score Television Network]]. June 11, 2012. Retrieved July 19, 2012.</ref> During the feud, Razor verbally disrespected Hart and the [[Hart wrestling family]].<ref name=\"scottbio\"/> Razor lost to Hart at the Royal Rumble, submitting to the [[Sharpshooter (professional wrestling)|Sharpshooter]].<ref name=\"OWOW\"/><ref name=\"scottbio\"/><ref name=\"wwf\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/royalrumble/history/19881161/results/|title=Royal Rumble 1993 official results|publisher=WWE|accessdate=June 28, 2008}}</ref> Razor made his [[WrestleMania]] debut at [[WrestleMania IX]], pinning former WWF Champion [[Bob Backlund]] with a roll-up.<ref name=\"OWOW\"/><ref name=\"scottbio\"/><ref name=\"wwf\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/wrestlemania/history/wm9/results/|title=WrestleMania IX official results|publisher=WWE|accessdate=June 28, 2008}}</ref>\n\nOn the May 17 episode of ''[[WWE Raw|Monday Night Raw]]'' he suffered an upset loss to [[Job (professional wrestling)|jobber]] [[Sean Waltman|\"The Kid\"]] (who consequently became known as \"The 1\u20132\u20133 Kid\"), beginning feud between the two.<ref name=\"OWOW\"/><ref name=\"wwf\"/><ref>{{cite web|author=Christopher Robin Zimmerman |date=May 17, 1993 |url=http://www.otherarena.com/htm/cgi-bin/history.cgi?1993/raw051793 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20030530104819/http://www.otherarena.com/htm/cgi-bin/history.cgi?1993%2Fraw051793 |archivedate=May 30, 2003 |title=WWF Raw: May 17, 1993 |work=The Other Arena |accessdate=June 28, 2008 |url-status=dead }}</ref> It carried into the [[King of the Ring tournament]] and triggered a slow [[Face (professional wrestling)|fan favorite]] turn for Razor, as he gained respect for The 1\u20132\u20133 Kid and support from the crowd.<ref name=\"OWOW\"/><ref name=\"scottbio\"/><ref name=\"wwf\"/> [[Ted DiBiase]], however, did not show respect for Razor, making fun of him for losing to such a small jobber. Ramon helped The 1\u20132\u20133 Kid defeat DiBiase, solidifying his face turn.<ref name=\"1993bio\">{{cite web|url=http://www.accelerator3359.com/Wrestling/bios/hall.html#93|title=Scott Hall's WWF Career (1993)|work=Accelerator's Wrestling Rollercoaster|accessdate=June 28, 2008}}</ref> The feud culminated at [[SummerSlam (1993)|SummerSlam]], where Ramon defeated DiBiase in DiBiase's final WWF match.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/summerslam/history/1993/results/|title=SummerSlam 1993 official results|publisher=WWE|accessdate=June 28, 2008}}</ref>\n\n==== Record-setting Intercontinental Champion (1993\u20131996) ====\nOn the October 4, 1993 episode of ''Monday Night Raw'', a 20-man [[Battle royal (professional wrestling)|battle royal]] was held; the last two participants would face each other the next week for the vacant [[WWE Intercontinental Championship|WWF Intercontinental Championship]]. Razor and [[Rick Martel]] were those final two.<ref name=\"ictitle\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/inside/titlehistory/intercontinental/|title=WWE Intercontinental Championship official title history|publisher=WWE|accessdate=June 18, 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Christopher Robin Zimmerman |date=October 4, 1993 |url=http://otherarena.com/htm/cgi-bin/history.cgi?1993/raw100493 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20030610154328/http://otherarena.com/htm/cgi-bin/history.cgi?1993%2Fraw100493 |archivedate=June 10, 2003 |title=WWF Raw: October 04, 1993 |work=The Other Arena |accessdate=June 28, 2008 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The next week on ''Raw'', Razor pinned Martel after a Razor's Edge to win the Intercontinental Championship.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/inside/titlehistory/intercontinental/322472 |title=Razor Ramon's first Intercontinental Championship reign |publisher=WWE |accessdate=June 28, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071230091947/http://www.wwe.com/inside/titlehistory/intercontinental/322472 |archivedate=December 30, 2007 }}</ref>\n\nRamon began a feud with [[Shawn Michaels]] over which man had the stronger [[Claim rights and liberty rights|claim]] to the Intercontinental Championship. Michaels had been stripped of the title months before due to \"[[Kayfabe|inactivity]]\" (he was actually suspended during that time). He returned to television with his own version of the belt, claiming he was still the champion, since he hadn't been beaten for it.<ref name=\"1994bio\"/> The matter was settled when Ramon defeated Michaels in a [[ladder match]] at [[WrestleMania X]], becoming the undisputed Intercontinental Champion after retrieving both belts.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/wrestlemania/history/wm10/results/|title=WrestleMania X official results|publisher=WWE|accessdate=June 28, 2008}}</ref> This match was voted ''[[Pro Wrestling Illustrated]]'''s [[PWI Match of the Year|Match of the Year]] for 1994.<ref name=\"1994bio\"/> It was also the first WWF match to receive a [[Dave Meltzer#Rating system#5-star match|five star rating]] from [[Dave Meltzer]] in his ''[[Wrestling Observer Newsletter]]''.<ref name=\"1994bio\">{{cite web|url=http://www.accelerator3359.com/Wrestling/bios/hall.html#94|title=Scott Hall's WWF Career (1994)|work=Accelerator's Wrestling Rollercoaster|accessdate=June 28, 2008}}</ref> On WWE.com, this match is ranked No. 5 of the Top 24 Matches in WrestleMania History.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/wrestlemania/history/top21 |title=Top 22 Matches in WrestleMania History \u2013 Shawn Michaels vs. Razor Ramon in a Ladder Match for the Intercontinental Championship \u2013 WrestleMania X |work=Accelerator's Wrestling Rollercoaster |accessdate=June 28, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071011023332/http://www.wwe.com/shows/wrestlemania/history/top21 |archivedate=October 11, 2007 }}</ref>\n\n[[File:Razor Ramon in England.jpg|thumb|190px|Ramon with the [[WWE Intercontinental Championship|Intercontinental Championship]] at a WWF event]]\nRazor continued to feud with Michaels and his [[Enforcer (professional wrestling)|bodyguard]] [[Kevin Nash|Diesel]]. On the April 30 episode of ''Superstars'', he lost the Intercontinental Title to Diesel, after interference from Michaels.<ref>{{cite web|date=April 13, 1994|url=http://www.angelfire.com/wrestling/cawthon777/94.htm|title=WWF Show Results 1994|work=Angelfire|accessdate=July 2, 2008|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080501152837/http://www.angelfire.com/wrestling/cawthon777/94.htm|archivedate = May 1, 2008}}</ref> At [[SummerSlam (1994)|SummerSlam]], Razor (with [[Walter Payton]] in his corner) defeated Diesel to win the WWF Intercontinental Championship for a second time, after Shawn Michaels accidentally hit Diesel with [[Superkick|Sweet Chin Music]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/summerslam/history/1994/results/|title=SummerSlam 1994 official results|publisher=WWE|accessdate=July 2, 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/inside/titlehistory/intercontinental/322480 |title=Razor Ramon's second Intercontinental Championship reign |publisher=WWE |accessdate=July 2, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070423103313/http://www.wwe.com/inside/titlehistory/intercontinental/322480 |archivedate=April 23, 2007 }}</ref>\n\nAt [[Survivor Series (1994)|Survivor Series]], he captained a team called \"The Bad Guys\", consisting of himself, The 1\u20132\u20133 Kid, [[Davey Boy Smith]], and [[The Headshrinkers]] ([[Solofa Fatu|Fatu]] and [[Sione Vailahi|Sione]]). They faced The Teamsters (Shawn Michaels, Diesel, Owen Hart, [[Jim Neidhart]], and [[Jeff Jarrett]]). Ramon ended up the sole survivor of the match. This began a feud with Jeff Jarrett, which led into the next year.<ref name=\"1994bio\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/survivorseries/history/1994/results/|title=Survivor Series 1994 official results|publisher=WWE|accessdate=July 2, 2008}}</ref> At the 1995 [[Royal Rumble (1995)|Royal Rumble]], Razor lost the Intercontinental Championship to Jarrett, in controversial fashion; Jarrett had originally won the match by count-out, but demanded that the match be restarted so he could win the title. It was, and Jarrett pinned Razor with a small package.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/royalrumble/history/1988117/results/|title=Royal Rumble 1995 official results|publisher=WWE|accessdate=July 2, 2008}}</ref><ref name=\"1995bio\">{{cite web|url=http://www.accelerator3359.com/Wrestling/bios/hall.html#95|title=Scott Hall's WWF Career (1995)|work=Accelerator's Wrestling Rollercoaster|accessdate=June 28, 2008}}</ref> Razor faced Jarrett in a rematch for the Intercontinental Championship at [[WrestleMania XI]], winning by disqualification when Jarrett's [[Manager (professional wrestling)|assistant]] [[Road Dogg|The Roadie]] interfered. Jarrett retained the title, as a title cannot change hands by countout or disqualification.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/wrestlemania/history/wm11/results/|title=WrestleMania XI official results|publisher=WWE|accessdate=July 2, 2008}}</ref> Razor defeated Jarrett and The Roadie at [[In Your House 1]], in a [[handicap match]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.softwolves.pp.se/wrestling/wwf/1995#iyh1|title=In Your House 1 results|publisher=American Wrestling Trivia|accessdate=July 2, 2008}}</ref>\n\nRazor defeated Jarrett in a ladder match at a May 19, 1995 [[house show]] to win his third WWF Intercontinental Championship.<ref name=\"razor3\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/inside/titlehistory/intercontinental/322492 |title=Razor Ramon's third Intercontinental Championship reign |publisher=WWE |accessdate=July 2, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080724205533/http://www.wwe.com/inside/titlehistory/intercontinental/322492 |archivedate=July 24, 2008 }}</ref> Razor Ramon was the first man to win the Intercontinental Title [[List of WWE Intercontinental Champions|three times]].<ref name=\"razor3\"/> On May 22, he re-lost the title to Jarrett.<ref name=\"razor3\"/> On June 9, Razor suffered a rib injury during a ladder match rematch against Jarrett.<ref name=\"1995bio\"/> Around this time, he had formed a team with [[Savio Vega]], and Vega replaced Razor to defeat Irwin R. Schyster in the [[WWE Free for All|Free for All]] tournament match before the [[King of the Ring (1995)|King of the Ring]] [[pay-per-view]].<ref name=\"1995bio\"/> Razor managed Vega throughout the tournament. He lost to [[Viscera (wrestler)|Mabel]] in the final match.<ref name=\"1995bio\"/> Razor and Vega lost to [[Men on a Mission]] (Mabel and [[Robert Horne (wrestler)|Mo]]) at [[In Your House 2: The Lumberjacks]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.softwolves.pp.se/wrestling/wwf/1995#iyh2|title=In Your House 2 results|publisher=American Wrestling Trivia|accessdate=July 2, 2008}}</ref> and lost a [[World Tag Team Championship (WWE)|WWF (World) Tag Team Championship]] match to [[Owen Hart and Yokozuna]] on the August 7 episode of ''Raw''.<ref>{{cite web|date=July 24, 1995|url=http://www.angelfire.com/wrestling/cawthon777/95.htm|title=WWF Show Results 1995|work=Angelfire|accessdate=July 2, 2008|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080504011947/http://www.angelfire.com/wrestling/cawthon777/95.htm|archivedate = May 4, 2008}}</ref>\n\nRazor had an Intercontinental Championship ladder match (a rematch from WrestleMania X) against the new champion Shawn Michaels at [[SummerSlam (1995)|SummerSlam]],<ref name=\"OWOW\"/><ref name=\"scottbio\"/><ref name=\"1995bio\"/> but lost.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/summerslam/history/1995/results/|title=SummerSlam 1995 official results|publisher=WWE|accessdate=July 2, 2008}}</ref> He then began a feud with [[Shane Douglas|Dean Douglas]]. Razor defeated Douglas at [[In Your House 4]] to win the Intercontinental Championship, after Michaels had just forfeited the title to Douglas. This win made him the first four-time Intercontinental Champion in WWF history.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/inside/titlehistory/intercontinental/322508 |title=Razor Ramon's fourth Intercontinental Championship reign |publisher=WWE |accessdate=July 2, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070429224630/http://www.wwe.com/inside/titlehistory/intercontinental/322508 |archivedate=April 29, 2007 }}</ref>\n\nIn early 1996, Razor feuded with newcomer [[Goldust]], leading to an Intercontinental Championship match at the [[Royal Rumble (1996)|Royal Rumble]]. Razor lost the title to Goldust after Razor's former partner The 1\u20132\u20133 Kid attacked him.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/royalrumble/history/198811412/results/|title=Royal Rumble 1996 official results|publisher=WWE|accessdate=July 2, 2008}}</ref> Ramon was originally scheduled to face Goldust in a rematch for the title at [[WrestleMania XII]] in a Miami Street Fight, but Hall was suspended for six weeks by the WWF due to his drug use.<ref name=\"1996bio\"/> He returned to WWF television at April's [[In Your House 7: Good Friends, Better Enemies|In Your House 7]], where he lost to [[Big Van Vader|Vader]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.softwolves.pp.se/wrestling/wwf/1996#iyh7|title=In Your House 7 results|publisher=American Wrestling Trivia|accessdate=July 2, 2008}}</ref>\n\nHe became associated with the backstage group known as [[The Kliq]] (also consisting of [[Kevin Nash]] (Diesel), Paul Levesque ([[Triple H|Hunter Hearst Helmsley]]), [[Shawn Michaels]], and [[Sean Waltman]] (The 1\u20132\u20133 Kid)).<ref name=\"1996bio\">{{cite web|url=http://www.accelerator3359.com/Wrestling/bios/hall.html#96|title=Scott Hall's WWF Career (1996)|work=Accelerator's Wrestling Rollercoaster|accessdate=June 28, 2008}}</ref> Hall was involved in an incident dubbed the [[The Kliq#The MSG \"Curtain Call\"|\"Curtain Call\"]] at a [[Madison Square Garden|MSG]] show. Because Hall and fellow Kliq member Kevin Nash were departing for WCW, the pair (along with Michaels and Levesque) broke [[kayfabe]] by celebrating and embracing in the ring together, though the characters they portrayed were supposed to be enemies. According to Hall, he went to WCW not for the money, but because they offered him days off.<ref>{{cite DVD|title=WWE Monday Night War S01 E06:The Hart of War|publisher=WWE}}</ref>\n\n=== Return to WCW===\n==== New World Order (1996\u20131998) ====\n{{main|The Outsiders (professional wrestling)|l1=The Outsiders|New World Order (professional wrestling)|l2=New World Order (nWo)}}\nHall returned to WCW for a second time after leaving the WWF with an unannounced [[Promos (professional wrestling)|promo]] on May 27, 1996, in which he appeared from the crowd in street clothes and claimed to be \"an outsider.\"<ref name=\"wcw96bio\">{{cite web|url=http://www.accelerator3359.com/Wrestling/bios/hall.html#wcw2|title=Scott Hall's WCW Career (1996)|work=Accelerator's Wrestling Rollercoaster|accessdate=July 2, 2008}}</ref> On June 10, he was joined by Kevin Nash. They stated they were undertaking a hostile takeover of WCW, then slammed interviewer [[Eric Bischoff]] through the commentator's table.<ref name=\"wcw96bio\"/> The angle paralleled the [[Monday Night Wars|real-life competition]] between WCW and the WWF.<ref name=\"wcw96bio\"/> At [[Bash at the Beach (1996)|Bash at the Beach]], Nash and Hall (now known as The Outsiders)<ref name=\"outsiders\">{{cite web|url=http://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/profiles/o/outsiders.html|title=Outsiders Profile|publisher=Online World of Wrestling|accessdate=July 2, 2008}}</ref> challenged [[Sting (wrestler)|Sting]], [[Lex Luger]], and [[Randy Savage]] to a six-man tag team match, saying they had a mystery partner. That partner turned out to be Hulk Hogan, and the three formed the [[New World Order (professional wrestling)|New World Order (nWo)]].<ref name=\"nwo\">{{cite web|url=http://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/profiles/n/nwo-original.html|title=New World Order (nWo) Profile|publisher=Online World of Wrestling|accessdate=July 2, 2008}}</ref> The [[Smark|stable]] stormed WCW, recruiting such stars as [[Sean Waltman|Syxx]] and [[Big Show|The Giant]].<ref name=\"nwo\"/>\n\nThe Outsiders closed out 1996 with a victory over Sting and Lex Luger at [[Hog Wild 1996|Hog Wild]], and a [[WarGames match]] win at [[Fall Brawl 1996|Fall Brawl]].<ref name=\"wcw96bio\"/> They defeated [[Harlem Heat]] at [[Halloween Havoc 1996|Halloween Havoc]] for their first [[WCW World Tag Team Championship]].<ref name=\"wcwtag\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wrestling-titles.com/wcw/wcw-t.html|title=WCW World Tag Team Title history|publisher=Wrestling-titles.com|accessdate=March 5, 2009}}</ref> They successfully defended the title against [[The Nasty Boys]] and The [[Faces of Fear]] in a three-way match at [[World War 3 (1996)|World War 3]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.prowrestlinghistory.com/supercards/usa/wcw/ww3.html#96|title=World War 3 1996 results|work=Wrestling Supercards and Tournaments|accessdate=July 22, 2008}}</ref> and then again defeated The Faces of Fear at [[Starrcade (1996)|Starrcade]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.prowrestlinghistory.com/supercards/usa/wcw/starrcad.html#96|title=Starrcade 1996 results|work=Wrestling Supercards and Tournaments|accessdate=July 22, 2008}}</ref> They lost the title to The Steiner Brothers at Souled Out, but two days later Eric Bischoff returned the title due to the fact that the referee was not the official referee for the match. The Outsiders held the World Tag Team Championship from February 24, 1997 to October 13, 1997, often facing [[The Steiner Brothers]], Lex Luger and The Giant, and combinations of [[Four Horsemen (professional wrestling)|The Four Horsemen]]. In May 1997, Hall and Nash teamed with [[Masahiro Chono]] to defeat the Steiner Brothers and [[Keiji Mutoh]] at [[New Japan Pro-Wrestling]] (NJPW)'s Strong Style Evolution in the [[Osaka Dome]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.prowrestlinghistory.com/supercards/japan/newjapan/dome.html#osaka97|title=Other NJPW Dome Shows|publisher=Pro Wrestling History|accessdate=September 4, 2019}}</ref>\n\nSince Eric Bischoff (the Executive Vice President of WCW) was a member of the nWo, he used his power to return the title to The Outsiders on a technicality whenever they lost it.<ref name=\"wcw96bio\"/> The Outsiders would also use the [[The Fabulous Freebirds|Freebird Rule]] to defend their title. With Nash and Syxx out with injuries, Hall mostly wrestled singles matches in the last quarter of 1997, and in one of them he submitted to Lex Luger in a grudge match at [[Halloween Havoc 1997|Halloween Havoc]], with [[Larry Zbyszko]] as the guest referee.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.prowrestlinghistory.com/supercards/usa/wcw/havoc.html#97|title=Halloween Havoc 1997 results|work=Wrestling Supercards and Tournaments|accessdate=July 22, 2008}}</ref> Hall won the [[Battle royal (professional wrestling)#World War 3|60-man battle royal]] at [[World War 3 (1997)|World War 3]] in November 1997 to earn a shot at the [[WCW World Heavyweight Championship]].<ref name=\"1997worldwar3\">{{cite web|url=http://www.prowrestlinghistory.com/supercards/usa/wcw/ww3.html#97|title=World War 3 1997 results|work=Wrestling Supercards and Tournaments|accessdate=June 18, 2008}}</ref>\n\nOn the January 12, 1998 episode of ''[[WCW Monday Nitro|Nitro]]'', The Outsiders defeated The Steiner Brothers to win the WCW World Tag Team Championship for a fourth time.<ref name=\"wcwtag\"/> Hall wrestled Larry Zbyszko at [[Souled Out 1998|Souled Out]] and lost by disqualification.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.prowrestlinghistory.com/supercards/usa/wcw/nwoppv.html#98|title=Souled Out 1998 results|work=Wrestling Supercards and Tournaments|accessdate=July 22, 2008}}</ref> The Outsiders lost the title back to The Steiner Brothers on the February 9 episode of ''Nitro''.<ref name=\"1998bio\">{{cite web|url=http://www.accelerator3359.com/Wrestling/bios/hall.html#98|title=Scott Hall's WCW Career (1998)|work=Accelerator's Wrestling Rollercoaster|accessdate=July 22, 2008}}</ref> At [[SuperBrawl VIII]], The Outsiders won the WCW World Tag Team Championship for a fifth time, again by defeating The Steiner Brothers.<ref name=\"wcwtag\"/> At [[Uncensored (1998)|Uncensored]], Hall got his WCW World Heavyweight Championship shot against Sting, losing the match despite interference on his behalf from [[Dusty Rhodes (wrestler)|Dusty Rhodes]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.prowrestlinghistory.com/supercards/usa/wcw/uncensor.html#98|title=Uncensored 1998 results|work=Wrestling Supercards and Tournaments|accessdate=July 22, 2008}}</ref> Hall was ([[Kayfabe|legitimately]]) taken off TV for a short while and forced by WCW to enter [[Drug rehabilitation|rehab]], after he and Nash showed up to the March 16, 1998 episode of ''Nitro'' heavily intoxicated and under the influence of painkillers.<ref name=\"1998bio\"/><ref>[http://www.ddtdigest.com/updates/1998033m.htm WCW Monday Nitro \u2013 Monday, 03/16/98]. Ddtdigest.com. Retrieved on October 11, 2011.</ref> While Hall was absent, the nWo split into two feuding factions.<ref name=\"1998bio\"/> At [[Slamboree 1998|Slamboree]], Hall returned to team with Kevin Nash, for a tag team title defense against Sting and The Giant. Hall turned on Nash, costing them the title, and switched sides to align himself with Hulk Hogan and his splinter faction, [[New World Order (professional wrestling)#List of incarnations and members|nWo Hollywood]].<ref name=\"1998bio\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/profiles/n/nwo-hollywood.html|title=nWo Hollywood Profile|publisher=Online World of Wrestling|accessdate=July 22, 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.prowrestlinghistory.com/supercards/usa/wcw/slambore.html#98|title=Slamboree 1998 results|work=Wrestling Supercards and Tournaments|accessdate=July 22, 2008}}</ref>\n\nOn the July 6 episode of ''Nitro'', Hall was handpicked by Hogan to wrestle [[WWE United States Championship|United States Heavyweight Champion]] [[Bill Goldberg]].<ref name=\"1998bio\"/> Hall lost the match, giving Goldberg a shot at Hogan's World Heavyweight Championship later that night (which Goldberg won).<ref name=\"1998bio\"/> Hogan publicly blamed Hall for the loss, and Hall was treated as a \"weak link\" by the rest of the nWo, especially [[Scott Steiner]].<ref name=\"1998bio\"/> On July 13, Hogan challenged Hall to a match on ''Nitro'', during which Kevin Nash (leader of the nWo \"Wolfpac\" faction) interfered, but as he was apparently about to [[Powerbomb#Release powerbomb|Jacknife Powerbomb]] Hogan and regain Hall as his friend, Hall viciously attacked him, proving his allegiance to Hogan and nWo Hollywood.<ref name=\"1998bio\"/> In the following weeks, Hall mocked Nash, calling himself \"Medium Sexy (later \"Super Sexy\"), the Nash Killer\".<ref name=\"1998bio\"/> On the July 20 episode of ''Nitro'', Hall (with The Giant) won the WCW World Tag Team Championship for a sixth time,<ref name=\"wcwtag\"/> defeating Sting and Nash after outside interference from Bret Hart (who was feuding with Sting at the time).<ref name=\"1998bio\"/> This reign ended at [[Halloween Havoc 1998|Halloween Havoc]], when Rick Steiner defeated The Giant and Scott Steiner (who replaced Hall) to win the title, even after Rick's partner [[Buff Bagwell]] had turned on him.<ref name=\"1998bio\"/> Hall and Nash faced each other on October 25 at [[Halloween Havoc (1998)|Halloween Havoc]]. After hitting Hall with two Jacknife Powerbombs, Nash left the ring and lost the match by countout, in what was described by the commentators as an act of mercy.<ref name=\"1998bio\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.prowrestlinghistory.com/supercards/usa/wcw/havoc.html#98|title=Halloween Havoc 1998 results|work=Wrestling Supercards and Tournaments|accessdate=July 22, 2008}}</ref>\n\nHall was ejected from nWo Hollywood in late 1998, after Scott Steiner took control of the group in Hogan's absence, and then referred to himself as \"The Lone Wolf\".<ref name=\"1998bio\"/> On November 30, 1998, Hall needed a tag team partner to face Steiner and [[Horace Hogan]]. Initially, Hall said he would do it alone, but Kevin Nash came to the entrance and offered his help. The team (no longer billed as The Outsiders) won the match. At [[Starrcade (1998)|Starrcade]], Hall, disguised as a security guard, used a [[electroshock weapon|stun gun]] on WCW World Heavyweight Champion Goldberg during his title defense against Kevin Nash. Not having seen the interference, Nash powerbombed and covered Goldberg to become the WCW World Heavyweight Champion, and break Goldberg's 173 match winning streak.<ref name=\"1998bio\"/>\n\n==== nWo reunion and championship reigns (1999\u20132000) ====\nHall and Nash were allied again and, in January 1999, the two nWo factions rejoined.<ref name=\"1999bio\">{{cite web|url=http://www.accelerator3359.com/Wrestling/bios/hall.html#99|title=Scott Hall's WCW Career (1999)|work=Accelerator's Wrestling Rollercoaster|accessdate=July 22, 2008}}</ref> Hall feuded with Goldberg and faced him in a [[Ladder match|ladder]] taser match on January 19 at [[Souled Out 1999|Souled Out]]. He lost the match when Goldberg used the taser gun on him.<ref name=\"1999bio\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.prowrestlinghistory.com/supercards/usa/wcw/nwoppv.html#99|title=Souled Out 1999 results|work=Wrestling Supercards and Tournaments|accessdate=July 22, 2008}}</ref>\n\nAt [[SuperBrawl IX]], Hall defeated [[Roddy Piper]] for the [[WWE United States Championship|WCW United States Heavyweight Championship]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/inside/titlehistory/unitedstates/30445411132 |title=Scott Hall's first United States Championship reign |publisher=WWE |accessdate=July 22, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20051129082912/http://www.wwe.com/inside/titlehistory/unitedstates/30445411132 |archivedate=November 29, 2005 }}</ref> Shortly after, he suffered a foot injury which forced him to forfeit the title.<ref name=\"1999bio\"/> Hall was not seen again until October 1999, when he and Kevin Nash began sitting at ringside during WCW television, proclaiming \"the band was getting back together.\"<ref name=\"1999bio\"/>\n\nOn the November 8 episode of ''Nitro'', Hall defeated Goldberg, Bret Hart, and [[Sid Eudy|Sid Vicious]] in a Texas tornado ladder match to regain the United States Heavyweight Championship.<ref name=\"hall2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/inside/titlehistory/unitedstates/304454112121 |title=Scott Hall's second United States Championship reign |publisher=WWE |accessdate=August 26, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20051129194240/http://www.wwe.com/inside/titlehistory/unitedstates/304454112121 |archivedate=November 29, 2005 }}</ref> Two weeks later, at [[Mayhem 1999|Mayhem]], he defeated [[Rick Steiner]] by forfeit to also win the [[WCW World Television Championship]].<ref name=\"tvtitle\"/> He successfully defended both titles against [[Booker T (wrestler)|Booker T]] later that night.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.prowrestlinghistory.com/supercards/usa/wcw/mayhem.html#mayhem|title=Mayhem 1999 results|work=Wrestling Supercards and Tournaments|accessdate=August 26, 2008}}</ref> Eight days later, on ''Nitro'', Hall vacated the Television title by throwing it into a trash can.<ref name=\"1999bio\"/> He was soon stripped of his United States title, after being sidelined with a knee injury.<ref name=\"hall2\"/>\n\nHall and Nash teamed up to defeat Bret Hart and Goldberg on the December 13 episode of ''Nitro'', winning the WCW World Tag Team Championship for the sixth time together.<ref name=\"wcwtag\"/><ref>{{cite web|date=December 13, 1999|url=http://www.ddtdigest.com/updates/1999122m.htm|title=WCW Monday Nitro \u2013 December 13th, 1999|work=DDT Digest|accessdate=August 26, 2008}}</ref> Soon afterwards, Hall was injured again and the tag team title was vacated.<ref name=\"1999bio\"/>\n\nAfter the nWo returned in December 1999, Hall joined Kevin Nash, Bret Hart, Jeff Jarrett, and Scott Steiner in what was coined \"[[New World Order (professional wrestling)#Revival|nWo 2000]].\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/profiles/n/nwo-2000.html|title=nWo 2000 Profile|publisher=Online World of Wrestling|accessdate=August 26, 2008}}</ref> Hall feuded with WCW World Heavyweight Champion Sid Vicious, and nWo teammate Jeff Jarrett, over the world title. Sid pinned Hall in a match also involving Jarrett at [[SuperBrawl 2000|SuperBrawl]] on February 20. This was Scott Hall's last appearance in WCW.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.prowrestlinghistory.com/supercards/usa/wcw/s-brawl.html#X|title=SuperBrawl 2000 results|work=Wrestling Supercards and Tournaments|accessdate=August 26, 2008}}</ref>\n\nOn Kayfabe Commentaries' \"YouShoot\" interview series in 2015, Hall revealed he was having an on-and-off relationship with production assistant Emily Sherman, whose uncle was TNT president Brad Siegel. Hall added that while in Europe, which is believed to be WCW's March 2000 shows in England, a former girlfriend of Hall's that worked at the hotel met with Hall at his room to which Sherman encountered them. As a result, Hall was asked not to go on the plane back home.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://kayfabecommentaries.com/DVD_YS_Hall.html|title=YouShoot with Scott Hall \u2013 2015 (running time 2 hours 25 mins) \u2013 1 hour 15 mark|publisher=kayfabecommentaries.com|accessdate=November 29, 2015}}</ref> Reports indicate that Siegel was made aware of this and as a result, Hall had little chance to go back to WCW.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/Ask_the_Editor_18/article_7118.shtml|title=Inside Story on Goldberg-Jericho problems, who's really tough, Hall-Nash problems \u2013 Feb 11, 2004 \u2013 Sub-title \u2013 From the Ask the Torch Vault \u2013 July 24, 2000|publisher=PWTorch.com|accessdate=November 29, 2015}}</ref>\n\n=== Extreme Championship Wrestling (2000) ===\nAfter departing WCW, Hall wrestled two non-televised matches in [[Extreme Championship Wrestling]] in November 2000, first in a loss to Big Sal on November 10, then in a tag match with [[Jerry Lynn]] against [[Justin Credible]] and [[Rhyno|Rhino]] on November 11 in a successful victory.<ref name=\"indy\">{{cite web|url=http://www.accelerator3359.com/Wrestling/bios/hall.html#01|title=Scott Hall's Independent Career (2000\u20132001)|work=Accelerator's Wrestling Rollercoaster|accessdate=August 26, 2008}}</ref>\n\n===Return to NJPW (2001)===\nIn 2001, Hall returned to NJPW. In March, he become part of [[Team 2000]], usually tagging with [[Masahiro Chono]] and fellow WCW alumni [[Scott Norton]] or [[Jeff Farmer (wrestler)|Super J]], the former nWo Sting.<ref name=\"indy\"/> The highlights of his time in NJPW were defeats: a loss to [[All Japan Pro Wrestling]]'s (AJPW) [[Triple Crown Heavyweight Championship|Triple Crown Heavyweight Champion]] [[Keiji Mutoh]] and a loss to [[Hiroshi Tanahashi]], who was a rookie at the time, trying to break into the heavyweight division.<ref name=\"indy\"/>\n\n=== Return to WWF/E (2002) ===\nOn the January 24, 2002 episode of ''[[WWE SmackDown|SmackDown!]]'', WWF co-owner [[Vince McMahon]] stated that his company had a \"cancer\", and that he would inject the WWF with a \"lethal dose of poison\", so he would no longer have to share ownership of the WWF with Ric Flair. He then revealed the \"poison\" to be the nWo, who would help McMahon destroy his own company, before it could be ruined by anyone else.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/results/smackdown/020124.html|title=SmackDown! \u2013 January 24, 2002|publisher=Online World of Wrestling|accessdate=December 9, 2018}}</ref> Six years after defecting from the promotion, Hall returned to the WWF on February 17 at the [[No Way Out (2002)|No Way Out]] pay-per-view, and was reunited with Kevin Nash and Hollywood Hogan in a [[New World Order (professional wrestling)#World Wrestling Federation/Entertainment (2002)|repackaged nWo]]. Later on in the night, the nWo attacked [[Stone Cold Steve Austin]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/results/wwe/wweppv/nowayout/nowayout02/|title=No Way Out 2002 Results|publisher=Online World of Wrestling|accessdate=December 9, 2018}}</ref> On the March 4 episode of ''Raw'', Hall wrestled his first WWF match since May 1996, defeating [[Spike Dudley]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wrestleview.com/results/raw/63.shtml?_gl=1*dlatoa*_ga*YW1wLUstX2VZbGpKeW1CV19OMEM3bFIxV2NPVGtrUTQtNHJSQjRsb2hIYWx4aUt1VG5MRXNta2dDZE12UU9aTVNwY08.|title=WWF Raw Results \u2013 March 4, 2002|first=Paul|last=Nemer|date=March 4, 2002|accessdate=December 9, 2018|work=WrestleView}}</ref>\n\nAt [[WrestleMania X8]], Hall lost to Austin, his first loss at a WrestleMania. Later in the night, after Hollywood Hogan had lost to the Rock, Hogan proceeded to shake the Rock's hand out of respect, thus turning his back on the nWo. Hall and Nash then attempted to attack Hogan and Rock, but were promptly dispatched by the duo.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wrestleview.com/messages1/1355.shtml|title=Full WWF WrestleMania X8 Results|work=WrestleView|date=March 18, 2002|first=Kevin|last=Romano|accessdate=December 9, 2018}}</ref> Hall and Nash later recruited X-Pac into the nWo on the following episode of ''SmackDown!''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/results/smackdown/020321.html|title=SmackDown! results \u2013 March 21, 2002|accessdate=January 24, 2008|publisher=Online World of Wrestling}}</ref> On the March 25 episode of ''Raw'', Hall was [[WWE Draft|drafted]] to the [[Raw (WWE brand)|Raw brand]] with the rest of the nWo, as a result of the [[2002 WWF draft lottery|WWF draft lottery]].<ref>{{cite web|date=March 25, 2002|url=http://www.pwwew.net/wwfdraft.htm|title=WWF Draft2002|work=pWwew \u2013 Everything Wrestling|accessdate=August 26, 2008}}</ref> Hall faced [[John Layfield|Bradshaw]] in a match at [[Backlash (2002)|Backlash]], which he won with help from X-Pac.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/backlash/history/backlash2002/results/|title=Backlash 2002 official results|publisher=WWE|accessdate=August 26, 2008}}</ref> On the next night on ''Raw'', Hall and X-Pac took on Austin and [[Big Show]]. Late in the match Big Show [[chokeslam]]med Austin and joined the nWo.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wrestleview.com/results/raw/70.shtml?_gl=1*1w5by67*_ga*YW1wLU9rSzVYbXJ6YnFuWGNSVkYwWUtJTTRIZGNHeWlzdUJBODdLZEtZOTBpNUZRekJVRk9QSlZaY3AtVmRhUEVqbUg.|title=Full WWF RAW Results \u2013 April 22, 2002|work=WrestleView|first=Paul|last=Nemer|date=April 22, 2002|accessdate=December 9, 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn May 5, on a flight back from England to the United States, retroactively dubbed \"the plane ride from hell\", Hall became incredibly intoxicated and unresponsive. Hall's last appearance was in a six-man tag match with Big Show and X-Pac against Austin, Bradshaw and Ric Flair on the May 6 episode of ''Raw'', which ended in a [[Professional wrestling#No contest|no contest]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/results/raw/020506.html|title=RAW \u2013 May 6, 2002|publisher=Online World of Wrestling|accessdate=December 9, 2018}}</ref> Hall was released from the promotion the following day due to ongoing issues stemming from his substance abuse.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://slam.canoe.com/SlamWrestlingArchive2001/may12_baines-sun.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170724103546/http://slam.canoe.com/SlamWrestlingArchive2001/may12_baines-sun.html|title=Hall, Henning and F are out|work=Slam! Sports|publisher=[[Canoe.com|Canadian Online Explorer]]|first=Tim|last=Baines|date=May 8, 2002|archivedate=July 24, 2017|accessdate=February 24, 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Total Nonstop Action Wrestling (2002, 2004\u20132005, 2007, 2010) ===\nHall worked for [[Total Nonstop Action Wrestling]] (TNA) briefly in 2002, appearing on their first pay-per-view event. on the July 31 NWATNA PPV, Hall lost to Jeff Jarrett in a [[Professional wrestling match types#Container-based variations|Stretcher match]]. on the September 18 NWATNA PPV, Hall and Syxx-Pac competed in the Tag Team Gauntlet for the Gold Match but did not win. on the September 25 NWATNA PPV, Hall and Syxx-Pac defeated [[Elix Skipper]] and [[Brian Lawler]]. on October 23 NWATNA PPV, Hall defeated [[Jeff Jarrett]]. on October 30 NWATNA PPV, Hall got a shot at the [[NWA World Heavyweight Championship]] but lost to [[Ron Killings]]. Hall would leave NWATNA after his match with Killings.\n\nIn late 2004, Hall returned to TNA, along with Kevin Nash, as TNA prepared for their first monthly pay-per-view, [[Victory Road (2004)|Victory Road]]. Hall joined Nash and Jeff Jarrett in the stable The Kings of Wrestling. on the November 26 episode of Impact, Hall defeated [[A.J. Styles]]. at [[Turning Point (2004 wrestling)|Turning Point]], The Kings of Wrestling lost to [[Randy Savage]], [[Jeff Hardy]], and [[A.J. Styles]]. on the December 24 episode of Impact, Hall interrupted a \"In The Pit with Piper\" and confronted [[H\u00e9ctor Garza]] which led to a match a week later on the December 31 episode of Impact where Hall won the match. Hall lost to Hardy at [[Final Resolution (2005)|Final Resolution]] on January 16, 2005.\n\nOn the November 1, 2007 episode of ''[[TNA Impact!|Impact!]]'', Kevin Nash \"predicted\" Hall would be Sting's mystery partner at [[Genesis (2007)|Genesis]]. The next week, Hall made his return, rebuffing the romantic advances of [[Kurt Angle]]'s wife, [[Karen Jarrett|Karen]], then battling Kurt in his dressing room. He stated he was in TNA solely to confront Nash. Hall asked Nash why he was not there to help him in his troubled past, and Nash responded that it was a result of his own nonstop partying and risk of losing his family. Hall then claimed that all was forgiven and the two embraced in the ring. He also revealed that he was not Sting's mystery partner. on the November 15 episode of ''[[TNA Impact!|Impact!]]'',The reunited Outsiders and [[Samoa Joe]] began a feud with [[The Angle Alliance]]. on the November 29 episode of Impact, Hall and Nash came out to the stage and clapped for Samoa Joe after his match. They were scheduled to compete together at [[Turning Point (2007 wrestling)|Turning Point]], but Hall no-showed.\n\nAt [[Turning Point (2008 wrestling)|Turning Point (2008)]], Hall and the [[Insane Clown Posse]] (ICP) were seen in attendance. This was later revealed to have been scripted to occur, as TNA had asked ICP to attend the event, but were unaware of Hall being their guest.\n\nOn the January 4, 2010 three-hour [[TNA Impact!'s move to Monday nights|Monday night live episode of ''Impact!'']], Hall and [[Sean Waltman]] returned to TNA. That same night, Hulk Hogan made his TNA debut. Hall, Nash and Waltman quickly reformed their alliance, but Hogan kept himself out of the group, claiming \"times have changed\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/TV_Reports_9/article_37861.shtml|title=KELLER'S TNA IMPACT LIVE REPORT 1/4: Jeff Hardy, NWO reunion, Hulk Hogan, TNA Knockout Title match, more surprises \u2013 ongoing coverage|last=Keller|first=Wade|date=January 4, 2010|work=PWTorch|accessdate=January 5, 2010}}</ref> The following week, the revived alliance was named \"[[The Band (professional wrestling)|The Band]]\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/TV_Reports_9/article_38126.shtml|title=WILKENFELD'S TNA IMPACT REPORT 1/14: Ongoing \"virtual time\" coverage of Spike TV broadcast|last=Wilkenfeld|first=Daniel|date=January 14, 2010|accessdate=January 17, 2010|work=PWTorch}}</ref>\n\nHall was scheduled to team with Nash at [[Genesis (2010)|Genesis]] in a match against [[Beer Money, Inc.]], but was replaced by Waltman (as Syxx-Pac). In the end, Hall inadvertently cost his stablemates the match.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/PPV_Reports_5/article_38198.shtml|title=CALDWELL'S TNA GENESIS PPV REPORT 1/17: Ongoing \"virtual time\" coverage of A.J. Styles vs. Kurt Angle, Hulk Hogan's TNA PPV debut|last=Caldwell|first=James|date=January 17, 2010|work=PWTorch|accessdate=January 18, 2010}}</ref> On the next episode of ''Impact!'', Hogan, displeased with the actions of The Band, had security remove Hall and Waltman from the arena, since they were not under contract with TNA.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/TV_Reports_9/article_38325.shtml|title=WILKENFELD'S TNA IMPACT REPORT 1/21: Ongoing \"virtual time\" coverage of Spike TV broadcast|last=Wilkenfeld|first=Daniel|date=January 21, 2010|accessdate=January 29, 2010|work=PWTorch}}</ref> Despite this, Hall and Syxx-Pac continued returning to ''Impact!'' to assault various wrestlers. On the February 4 episode, they turned on Nash and beat him down.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/TV_Reports_9/article_38756.shtml|title=WILKENFELD'S TNA IMPACT REPORT 2/4: Ongoing \"virtual time\" coverage of Spike TV broadcast|date=February 4, 2010|accessdate=February 5, 2010|last=Wilkenfeld|first=Daniel|publisher=PWTorch}}</ref> on the February 11 episode of ''Impact!'' Hall and Waltman attacked Kurt Angle until Hulk Hogan made the save. on the February 18 episode of ''Impact!'' Hall and Waltman had a brawl with Kevin Nash and Eric Young. on the February 25 episode of ''Impact!'' Hall and Waltman had a brawl with Kevin Nash and Eric Young in the parking lot. on the March 15 episode of ''Impact!'' Hall defeated Nash in a 5-Min $25,000 challenge after interference from Waltman. At [[Destination X (2010)|Destination X]], Hall and Syxx-Pac faced Nash and [[Eric Young (wrestler)|Eric Young]] in a tag team match, with The Band's TNA future on the line. In the end, Nash turned on Young and helped The Band win, earning them contracts with TNA.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/PPV_Reports_5/article_40000.shtml|title=CALDWELL'S TNA DESTINATION X PPV REPORT 3/21: Ongoing \"virtual time\" coverage of A.J. Styles vs. Abyss, Ultimate X, Anderson vs. Angle|last=Caldwell|first=James|date= March 21, 2010|work=PWTorch|accessdate=March 22, 2010}}</ref>\n\nOn the March 29 episode of ''Impact!'', The Band lost a six-man tag team steel cage match to Eric Young, [[Rob Van Dam]] and Jeff Hardy.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://wrestleview.com/viewnews.php?id=1269919705|title=Impact Results \u2013 3/29/10|last=Martin|first=Adam|date= March 29, 2010|work=WrestleView|accessdate=March 30, 2010}}</ref> on the April 5 episode of ''Impact!'', The Band interfered in a match and attacked both Team 3D and [[The Motor City Machine Guns]]. on the April 12 episode of ''Impact!'', The Band (Hall, Nash, Waltman) defeated Team 3-D and [[Jesse Neal]] in a Street Fight. At [[Lockdown (2010)|Lockdown]], Hall and Nash lost to [[Dudley Boyz|Team 3D]] in a \"St. Louis Street Fight\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/PPV_Reports_5/article_40725.shtml|title=Caldwell's TNA Lockdown Results 4/18: Ongoing \"virtual time\" coverage of PPV \u2013 Styles vs. The Pope, Team Hogan vs. Team Flair, Angle vs. Anderson|first=James|last=Caldwell|date=April 18, 2010|accessdate=April 18, 2010|publisher=Pro Wrestling Torch}}</ref> On the May 3 ''Impact!'', Eric Young turned on Team 3D and joined The Band.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/wwerawreport/article_41070.shtml|title=TNA Impact Results 5/3: Keller's ongoing \"virtual time\" coverage of live show from Orlando|first=Wade|last=Keller|date=May 3, 2010|accessdate=May 4, 2010|publisher=Pro Wrestling Torch}}</ref> On May 4, at the taping of the May 13 episode of ''Impact!'', Hall teamed with Nash, cashed in his \"[[Professional wrestling match types#Feast or Fired|Feast or Fired]]\" contract and defeated [[Matt Morgan (wrestler)|Matt Morgan]] to win the [[TNA World Tag Team Championship]].<ref name=Impact05132010>{{cite web|url=http://wrestleview.com/viewnews.php?id=1273024520|title=SPOILERS: TNA Impact for next Thursday|last=Gerweck|first=Steve|date= May 4, 2010|work=WrestleView|accessdate=May 5, 2010}}</ref> Nash later declared Young one third of the champions, citing the \"Freebird Rule\".<ref name=Sacrifice2010>{{cite web|url=http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/tnappvs/article_41360.shtml|title=Caldwell's TNA Sacrifice results 5/16: Ongoing \"virtual time\" coverage of PPV \u2013 RVD vs. Styles, Jeff Hardy vs. Mr. Anderson|date=May 16, 2010|accessdate=May 16, 2010|last=Caldwell|first=James|publisher=Pro Wrestling Torch}}</ref><ref name=Impact061010>{{cite web|url=http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/tnaimpact/article_41877.shtml|title=Wilkenfeld's TNA Impact report 6/10: Ongoing \"virtual time\" coverage of Spike TV broadcast|last=Wilkenfeld|first=Daniel|date= June 10, 2010|work=Pro Wrestling Torch|accessdate=June 11, 2010}}</ref> At [[Sacrifice (2010)]], Hall and Nash defeated [[Ink Inc.]] ([[Jesse Neal]] and [[Shannon Moore]]) to retain the titles. on the June 10 episode of ''Impact!'', the Band defeated Matt Morgan (by himself) to retain their titles and this was Hall's final appearance in TNA.\n\nOn the June 14 ''Impact!'' taping, The Band was stripped of the Tag Team Championship, due to Hall's real-life legal problems.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://wrestleview.com/viewnews.php?id=1276582066|title=Spoilers: TNA Impact TV tapings for June 17|last=Martin|first=Adam|date=June 15, 2010|work=WrestleView|accessdate=June 15, 2010}}</ref> The following day, it was announced Hall had been released from TNA after 8 years of working part-time for the company.<ref name=Release061510>{{cite web|url=http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/TNA_News_1/article_41973.shtml|title=TNA News: Scott Hall reportedly fired by TNA; SPOILERS on TNA tag title situation|last=Caldwell|first=James|date= June 15, 2010|work=Pro Wrestling Torch|accessdate=June 15, 2010}}</ref>\n\n=== Return to WWC (2007) ===\nOn July 13, Hall made his return to wrestling for the [[World Wrestling Council]] (WWC) as Razor Ramon (though wearing [[New World Order (professional wrestling)|WolfPac]] themed attire). He wrestled the main event of a [[WWC Anniversary#2007|WWC Anniversary]] tour show at the [[Jos\u00e9 Miguel Agrelot Coliseum]] in San Juan, against [[Carly Col\u00f3n|Carlito]]. He lost after [[Germ\u00e1n Figueroa|Apollo]] interfered on Carlito's behalf.\n\nThe next night, Hall won his second World Championship, the [[WWC Universal Heavyweight Championship]], by defeating Carlito and champion Apollo in a Three-Way Dance main event.<ref name=Uni>{{cite web|url=http://www.wrestling-titles.com/us/pr/wwc/wwc-h.html|title=WWC Universal Heavyweight Title history|publisher=Wrestling-titles.com|accessdate=March 5, 2009}}</ref> On August 4 and September 23, Hall successfully defended the title against [[Eddie Col\u00f3n]]. On October 27, managed by Rico Casanova, he retained the title at WWC's ''Halloween Wrestling Xtravaganza'', defeating [[Orlando Col\u00f3n|Orlando \"Fireblaze\" Colon]].\n\n=== Juggalo Championship Wrestling (2007\u20132009) ===\n{{main|Juggalo World Order}}\nHall made his [[Juggalo Championship Wrestling]] (JCW) debut on August 12, 2007, at ''[[Bloodymania (2007)|Bloodymania]]'', losing to [[JCW Heavyweight Championship|JCW Heavyweight Champion]] [[Steve Robinson (wrestler)|Corporal Robinson]].<ref name=\"JCW SLAM TV, Volume 2\">{{cite AV media|date=October 30, 2007|title=JCW SLAM TV, Volume 2|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt1194584/|medium=DVD|publisher=Psychopathic Video|location=Royal Oak, Michigan|isbn=|accessdate=June 6, 2008}}</ref> In this match, Hall took his first ever [[Bump (professional wrestling)|bump]] on [[thumbtacks]].\n\nOn October 6, 2007, at ''Evansville Invasion'', Corporal Robinson, Hall, and [[Violent J]] formed the Juggalo World Order (JWO) stable.<ref name=\"JCW Slam TV - Hallowicked\">{{cite episode|title=Slam TV: Hallowicked 2007!|url=http://video.google.com/videoplay?docid=-3177937582334783638&hl=en|series=SlamTV!|credits=Creator and Producer: [[Insane Clown Posse]]|location=Detroit, Michigan|airdate=November 17, 2007}}</ref> At the 2007 ''Hallowicked After Party'', on October 31, [[Shaggy 2 Dope]] was introduced as a member of the group. After the main event, [[special guest referee]] [[Kazushige Nosawa|Nosawa]] ripped off his referee shirt to reveal that he, too, was a member of the JWO.<ref name=\"JCW Slam TV - Hallowicked\"/> At ''[[Bloodymania II]]'', Hall teamed with Kevin Nash, who proclaimed himself a member of the group. At the 2008 ''Hallowicked After Party'', the JWO inducted its newest member, [[2 Tuff Tony]].\n\nOn November 9, the JWO \"invaded\" Total Nonstop Action Wrestling's [[Turning Point (2008 wrestling)|Turning Point]] PPV, by purchasing front row tickets to the event. They promote their faction by flashing their JWO jerseys, before being removed from the building.<ref name=\"PWTorch November 9\">{{cite web|url=http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/TNA_News_1/article_27798.shtml|last=Caldwell|first=James|title=Scott Hall appears on camera with ICP at tonight's TNA PPV|accessdate=November 10, 2008|publisher=ProWrestlingTorch|date=November 9, 2008}}</ref><ref name=\"The Main Event November 11\">{{cite episode|title=The Main Event |url=http://wfuckoffradio.com/wfko.php/shows/15 |series=JCW Television |credits=Presenters: Violent J, 2 Tuff Tony, and Corporal Robinson |station=WFKO |airdate=November 11, 2008 |minutes=48:18 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100328093423/http://www.wfuckoffradio.com/wfko.php/shows/15 |archivedate=March 28, 2010 }}</ref> The group expressed interest in \"invading\" WWE's 2009 [[Royal Rumble (2009)|Royal Rumble]], but were unable, due to filming commitments for [[Big Money Rustlas]] in Los Angeles.<ref name=\"The Main Event November 18\">{{cite episode|series=JCW Television |title=The Main Event |url=http://wfuckoffradio.com/wfko.php/shows/15 |credits=Presenters: Violent J, 2 Tuff Tony, and Corporal Robinson |station=WFKO |airdate=November 18, 2008 |minutes=1:40:00 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100328093423/http://www.wfuckoffradio.com/wfko.php/shows/15 |archivedate=March 28, 2010 }}</ref> They have also shown interest in \"invading\" [[Ring of Honor]] and [[Ultimate Fighting Championship]].<ref name=\"The Main Event November 4\">{{cite episode|title=The Main Event |url=http://wfuckoffradio.com/wfko.php/shows/15 |series=JCW Television |credits=Presenters: Violent J, 2 Tuff Tony, and Corporal Robinson |station=WFKO |airdate=November 4, 2008 |minutes=1:12:04 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100328093423/http://www.wfuckoffradio.com/wfko.php/shows/15 |archivedate=March 28, 2010 }}</ref>\n\n=== Independent circuit (2010\u2013present) ===\nOn May 3, 2010, Hall appeared in Continental Championship Wrestling. He and Syxx-Pac escorted [[Richard Young (wrestler)|Ricky Ortiz]] to the ring for his match with Navy Seal (which Ortiz won). On January 14, 2011, Hall managed Ortiz at a Vintage Pro Wrestling show with Ortiz, Hall made an impact costing Kennedy Kendrick the match but when Ortiz continued beating on Kendrick it was reversed.\n\nOn January 8, 2011, Hall appeared at I Believe in Wrestling in Orlando, talking about his health before bringing out Ortiz for his match with \"Hotshot\" Mike Reed. Hall along with Nash and Waltman made an appearance at the 2011 Gathering of the Juggalos. On July 14, 2012, Hall appeared at Belleview Pro Wrestling, accompanying his son, Cody, to the ring for his match against Josh Hess.\n\nOn May 13, 2015, [[Global Force Wrestling (2014\u20132017)|Global Force Wrestling]] (GFW) announced Hall as part of their roster.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.globalforcewrestling.com/roster/|title=Global Force Wrestling Roster|date=May 15, 2015|accessdate=May 15, 2015|work=Global Force Wrestling}}</ref> However, on May 18, 2015, Hall was released from his contract with GFW.\n\nOn January 30, 2016, Hall took part of [[World Association of Wrestling]] television tapings, which took place in the Epic Studios at Norwich, England. It was aired on [[Mustard TV]] on September 10, 2016.<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.mustardtv.co.uk/episode/waw-2/ |title = About Mustard TV}}</ref>\n\n=== Second return to WWE (2014\u2013present) ===\nOn March 24, 2014, Razor Ramon was announced as the seventh and final inductee into that year's class of the [[WWE Hall of Fame]]. He was inducted in [[New Orleans]] on April 5, the night before [[WrestleMania XXX]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/videos/2014-wwe-hall-of-fame-inductee-razor-ramon-raw-march-24-2014-26214743|title=2014 WWE Hall of Fame Inductee: Razor Ramon: Raw, March 24, 2014|work=WWE}}</ref> [[Shawn Michaels]], [[Triple H]], [[Sean Waltman|X-Pac]] and [[Kevin Nash]] joined Hall onstage after his speech, reuniting [[The Kliq]]. WWE promotional material for the event referred to him solely as Razor Ramon, without footage or mention of his work under his real name. At WrestleMania XXX, Hall, as Razor Ramon, appeared onstage with the other Hall of Fame inductees. Hall appeared on the August 11, 2014 episode of ''Raw'' for the first time since 2002 to reunite the nWo with Nash and [[Hulk Hogan]] to celebrate Hogan's birthday.\n\n{{quote|Hard work pays off. Dreams come true. Bad times don't last, but bad guys do.|author=excerpt from Hall's [[WWE Hall of Fame]] induction speech, April 2014}}\n\n[[File:NWo WM31.jpg|thumb|The three original members of [[New World Order (professional wrestling)|the nWo]] making their way to the ring at [[WrestleMania 31]] in 2015]]\nOn the January 19, 2015 episode of ''Raw'', Hall appeared with X-Pac and Nash to reunite the nWo, and along with [[The Acolytes Protection Agency|the APA]] and [[The New Age Outlaws]] they beat down [[The Ascension (professional wrestling)|The Ascension]], who had been insulting legends from past weeks. At [[WrestleMania 31]], Hall, along with Nash and Hogan, reunited as the nWo to help [[Sting (wrestler)|Sting]] in his match against Triple H, who had [[D-Generation X]] helping on his behalf.\n\nIn 2016, Razor Ramon was backstage at [[WrestleMania 32]] celebrating with the new [[WWE Intercontinental Championship|Intercontinental Champion]] [[Zack Ryder]]. The following night on ''Raw'', he asked [[The Miz]] to give Ryder a rematch for the Intercontinental Championship.\n\nThe [[WWE]] revealed that Scott Hall would make an appearance on [[Raw 25 Years]] that took place on January 22, 2018. Under the Razor Ramon gimmick, Hall returned in a segment featuring D-Generation X, The Balor Club, and The Revival. Hall also returned to WWE for the RAW Reunion show on July 22, 2019.\n\nOn December 9, 2019, it was announced that Hall would be inducted into the WWE Hall of Fame a second time (this time under his real name instead of as Razor Ramon), as a member of the [[New World Order (professional wrestling)|New World Order]], together with fellow former nWo stablemates [[Hulk Hogan]], [[Kevin Nash]], and [[Sean Waltman]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.espn.com/wwe/story/_/id/28256144/wwe-honor-nwo-hall-fame-induction|title=WWE to honor nWo with Hall of Fame induction|date=December 9, 2019|website=ESPN.com|language=en|access-date=December 9, 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nHall married Dana Lee Burgio in 1990. They divorced in 1998 due to Hall's drug use.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/Other_News_4/article_54405.shtml|title=Hall News: Full recap of ESPN's Scott Hall documentary, quotes from Hall, McMahon, Bischoff, Hogan, Nash, Waltman, indy promoter, more (w/Analysis of the story)|date=October 19, 2011|accessdate=March 30, 2012|last=Caldwell|first=James|work=Pro Wrestling Torch}}</ref> They remarried in 1999 and divorced again in 2001. He has a son ([[Cody Hall|Cody Taylor]], born 1991)<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.rfvideo.com/shootwiththeoutsiders.aspx|title=The Outsiders Shoot Interview|website=RF Video Inc. - Wrestling Merchandise, Wrestling DVDs, Shoot Interviews, ECW}}</ref> and a daughter (Cassidy Lee, born March 27, 1995).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/SCOTTHALLNWO/status/449218833505476608|date=March 27, 2014|accessdate=March 29, 2014|title=19 years ago today was one of the happiest days of my life...Happy Birthday to Cassidy Lee Hall. All my love, Daddy}}</ref> Hall married his second wife Jessica Hart, in 2006. The marriage lasted for only a year when they divorced in 2007.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thesportster.com/wrestling/15-things-you-didnt-know-about-the-relationships-of-the-nwo-wolfpack/amp/|title=15 Things You Didn't Know About The Relationships of the nWo Wolfpack|date=July 12, 2017|website=TheSportster}}</ref>\n\n=== Health ===\nHall's problems with drugs were made public in the late 1990s and were incorporated into a controversial [[World Championship Wrestling|WCW]] storyline. While the storyline was playing out, Hall was legitimately arrested for keying a limousine while intoxicated outside of a night club in [[Orlando, Florida]], causing $2,000 in damages.<ref name=1998limoarrest>{{cite book|last1=Reynolds|first1=R.D.|last2=Alvarez|first2=Bryan|title=The Death of WCW: WrestleCrap and Figure Four Weekly Present . . .|edition=Paperback|date=November 2004|publisher=[[ECW Press]]|isbn=1-55022-661-4|page=155|chapter=1998: Monumentum is Money|quote=Scott Hall was arrested again the following week for allegedly causing $2,000 dollars in damage by keying a limo outside the Diamond Mine strip club during a drunken fit...}}</ref>\n\nAfter his release from TNA in 2010, Hall checked into rehab paid for by [[WWE]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/Other_News_4/article_43306.shtml|title=Other News: Scott Hall health update \u2013 confirmed to be in WWE-sponsored rehab on October 20th 2010 it has confirmed that hall has been released from rehab|date=August 23, 2010|accessdate=August 23, 2010|last=Caldwell|first=James|work=Pro Wrestling Torch}}</ref> Hall checked out of the rehab facility in early October 2010.<ref>[http://www.prowrestling.net/artman/publish/miscnews/article10014447.shtml Prowrestling.net]. Prowrestling.net (October 5, 2010). Retrieved on October 11, 2011.</ref> Weeks after he checked into rehab, Hall had both a [[Defibrillation|defibrillator]] and a [[Artificial cardiac pacemaker|pacemaker]] implanted in his chest.<ref>[http://www.yardbarker.com/wwe/articles/wwe_scott_hall_talks_helping_a_former_wwe_star_going_into_rehab_and_more/4054649 (WWE) Scott Hall Talks Helping a Former WWE Star, Going Into Rehab and More]. Yardbarker.com (January 28, 2011). Retrieved on October 11, 2011.</ref> He was hospitalized twice in 2010 for double pneumonia (affecting both lungs).<ref>[http://rajah.com/base/node/22485 WWE Wrestling News, Rumors, Results & Spoilers|Rajah.com Scott Hall Reportedly Hospitalized Following Drug Overdose]. Rajah.com (April 7, 2011). Retrieved on November 29, 2013.</ref> During this time, Hall started having seizures and was soon diagnosed with [[epilepsy]], resulting in him requiring to take eleven different medications on a daily basis to treat his heart and seizure problems.<ref name=scottesix />\n\nOn April 6, 2011, Hall was reportedly taken to the hospital due to a seizure.<ref name=scottesix /> Hall's [[Public relations|representative]], Geena Anac, said Hall was in the hospital that night to be treated for [[Hypotension|extremely low blood pressure]], and that Hall visits his doctor on a regular basis while recovering from double pneumonia, for [[blood test|blood work]] and [[General medical examination|checkups]].<ref>[http://mi2n.com/press.php3?press_nb=140808 Former WWE Wrestler Scott Hall's Rep Denies Rumors Regarding Drug Over Dose]. Mi2N.com. Retrieved on October 11, 2011.</ref> Three days later, [[TMZ.com|TMZ]] reported Hall had been taken to a hospital, treated for cardiac issues and remained in the hospital for three days. According to medical reports, Hall was being treated after overdosing on both [[opiate]]s and [[benzodiazepine]]s.<ref name=scottesix />\n\nLongtime friend Kevin Nash claims Hall's substance abuse stems from [[posttraumatic stress disorder]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://weblogs.baltimoresun.com/sports/wrestling/blog/2011/04/kevin_nash_scott_hall_is_in_bad_shape.html|title=Kevin Nash: Scott Hall is in bad shape|date=April 21, 2011|last=Eck|first=Kevin|accessdate=April 23, 2011|publisher=Baltimore Sun}}</ref> On October 20, 2011 ESPN's ''[[E:60]]'' featured a documentary detailing Hall's experience with drugs and alcohol. It included interviews with several of Hall's family members (including his ex-wife and his son, Cody), as well as several prominent figures and close friends from the wrestling industry (including Hulk Hogan, Kevin Nash, Sean Waltman, Eric Bischoff, and [[Stephanie McMahon]]).<ref name=scottesix>[http://espn.go.com/espn/e60/story/_/id/7112089/wwe-pro-wrestler-scott-hall-confront-substance-abuse-health-issues-e60 WWE, pro wrestler Scott Hall confront substance abuse, health issues \u2013 E:60 \u2013 ESPN]. Espn.go.com (October 19, 2011). Retrieved on November 29, 2013.</ref>\n\nIn early 2013, former professional wrestler [[Diamond Dallas Page]] invited Hall into his home in order for Hall to stay sober and \"rebuild his life from the ground up... physically, mentally, professionally, and spiritually.\" Page also initiated a fundraising drive, which raised nearly $110,000 ($30,000 over their $80,000 goal) to pay for hip replacement surgery and dental work for Hall.<ref>[http://www.indiegogo.com/projects/we-can-rebuild-him Indiegogo fundraiser for Hall]. Indiegogo.com. Retrieved on November 29, 2013.</ref>\n\n=== Legal issues ===\nIn 1983, Hall was charged with [[second degree murder]] after shooting a man with his own gun (after wrestling it away from him) in an altercation outside of a nightclub in [[Orlando, Florida]]. According to Hall, this was done in self-defense. The charges were dropped due to lack of evidence. In a 2011 interview for ESPN, Hall admitted killing the man and said he is unable to forget the incident.<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=iA9Upk0j2tE 149]. Youtube.com. Retrieved on November 29, 2013.</ref>\n\nIn 1998, Hall was also arrested for groping a 56-year-old woman outside a hotel in [[Baton Rouge, Louisiana]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.postandcourier.com/article/20120415/PC20/120419546&slId=1|title=Scott Hall past the point of no return?|date=April 15, 2012|accessdate=March 17, 2013|last=Mooneyham|first=Mike|work=The Post and Courier}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ddtdigest.com/updates/1998084m.htm|title=WCW Monday Nitro Report|date=August 24, 1998|accessdate=March 17, 2013|work=DDT Digest}}</ref>\n\nOn October 10, 2008, Hall was arrested during a [[Roast (comedy)|roast]] of [[The Iron Sheik]], held at a [[Crowne Plaza]] hotel in New Jersey. A comedian, Jimmy Graham, had joked, \"After The Sheik and [[Hacksaw Jim Duggan]] got caught snorting [[Cocaine|coke]] in the parking lot, his career fell faster than [[Owen Hart]].\" An enraged Hall charged at Graham and knocked down a podium, then grabbed the microphone from him and yelled about how the joke was disrespectful to Hart.<ref>[http://www.prowrestling.com/article/news/10571 Scott Hall arrested for attack] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081012164040/http://www.prowrestling.com/article/news/10571 |date=October 12, 2008 }} Retrieved on October 11, 2008</ref> Graham described the incident on his MySpace page, claiming Hall was drunk at the time of the attack.<ref>[http://www.prowrestling.com/article/news/10578 Graham explains joke] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081013164143/http://www.prowrestling.com/article/news/10578 |date=October 13, 2008 }} Retrieved on October 12, 2008</ref>\n\nHall was arrested on May 14, 2010 and charged with disorderly conduct and resisting a police officer. Police were called to the Hitching Post Bar in [[Chuluota, Florida]] after Hall (who had been \"drinking heavily\", according to the police report), \"became aggressive\". When they arrived, they found Hall yelling and cursing at amateur wrestling personalities and bar staff. Hall was told he was not allowed to return to the establishment. In his police statement, Hall described himself as an unemployed professional wrestler, despite having a job with TNA Wrestling (who would release him a month later).<ref name=Release061510/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.orlandosentinel.com/news/crime/os-scott-hall-bar-incident-20100521,0,2124800.story|title=Scott Hall arrested: Wrestler charged with disorderly intoxication, resisting at Seminole County bar|date=May 22, 2010|accessdate=June 1, 2010|last=Colarossi|first=Anthony|work=Orlando Sentinel}}</ref>\n\nOn April 6, 2012, Hall was arrested in [[Chuluota, Florida]] at around 9:31&nbsp;pm, by deputies of the [[Seminole County, Florida|Seminole County]] Sheriff's office. The arrest was later reported to be for a [[domestic violence|domestic disturbance]] involving his girlfriend, Lisa Howell. Hall allegedly choked Howell while he was drunk. He was taken to a hospital in Seminole County to be medically cleared prior to being taken to a [[drunk tank]].<ref name=\"sescoops arrest\">{{cite web|url=http://www.sescoops.com/scott-hall-arrested-for-domestic-battery-drank-for-days/|title=Scott Hall Arrested For Choking Girlfriend, Drunk \"For Days\"|last=Pena|first=Daniel|date=April 10, 2012|publisher=SEScoops.com|accessdate=April 26, 2012}}</ref> Hall denied the choking allegations.<ref name=\"sescoops deny\">{{cite web|url=http://www.sescoops.com/scott-hall-denies-choking-his-girlfriend-in-drunken-rage/|title=Scott Hall Denies Choking His Girlfriend in Drunken Rage|last=561|first=Mr.|date=April 11, 2012|publisher=SEScoops.com|accessdate=April 26, 2012}}</ref> The prosecutor dropped the charges, citing insufficient evidence.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://slam.canoe.com/Slam/Wrestling/2012/05/04/19716651-wenn-story.html |title= Charges dropped against Scott Hall |website=[[Canoe.ca|Canadian Online Explorer]] |publisher=SLAM! Wrestling |accessdate=April 9, 2016}}</ref>\n\n== Other media ==\nDuring Hall's fourth reign as [[WWE Intercontinental Championship|WWF Intercontinental Champion]], he appeared [[Kayfabe|in character]] as Razor Ramon on ''[[The Jerry Springer Show]]''. As part of his appearance, Hall handed the Intercontinental Championship belt, T-shirts, chain necklaces, and tickets to [[WrestleMania XII]] to two preteens that had gotten ceremonially\u2014but not legally\u2014married on an episode of the show two years prior. One of the preteens had [[HIV/AIDS|AIDS]], while the other was a wrestling fan who liked Ramon.<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=7E2MsItKMJ0 Razor Ramon on Jerry Springer]. YouTube (September 28, 2009). Retrieved on November 29, 2013.</ref> However, Hall ultimately did not compete at WrestleMania XII due to his suspension.<ref name=\"1996bio\"/>\n\nOn August 24, 2009, Hall began hosting a show on [[YouTube]] called ''Last Call with Scott Hall''. Guests have included [[Sid Eudy|Sid Vicious]], [[Kevin Nash]], [[Richard Young (wrestler)|Ricky Ortiz]], [[Larry Zbyszko]], and [[Sean Waltman]].<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/user/scotthalltv Scott Hall TV]. YouTube. Retrieved on November 29, 2013.</ref>\n\nOn August 20, 2013, Hall appeared on [[HBO]]'s ''[[Real Sports with Bryant Gumbel]]'', along with [[Diamond Dallas Page]] and [[Jake Roberts]] to talk about how he and Roberts have been recuperating since moving in with Page.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.caulifloweralleyclub.org/2013/09/27/hbo-real-sports-presents-dallas-page-scott-hall-and-jake-roberts-segment/|title=HBO \"Real Sports\" presents: Dallas Page, Scott Hall, and Jake Roberts segment|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151019050151/http://www.caulifloweralleyclub.org/2013/09/27/hbo-real-sports-presents-dallas-page-scott-hall-and-jake-roberts-segment/|archivedate=October 19, 2015}}</ref>\n\nRamon has appeared in the video games ''[[WWF Raw (1994 video game)|WWF Raw]]'', ''[[WWF Royal Rumble (1993 video games)|WWF Royal Rumble]]'', ''[[WWF WrestleMania: The Arcade Game]]'', ''[[WWE WrestleMania X8]]'' (as Scott Hall), ''[[WWE 2K14]]'', ''[[WWE 2K16]]'', ''[[WWE 2K17]]'', ''[[WWE 2K18]]'', ''[[WWE 2K19]]'' and ''[[WWE 2K20]]''. In the fourth-to-latter, Hall's nWo and Outsiders attires are available as [[downloadable content]], and in the third-to-latter, Hall is once again DLC, but only in his Outsiders attire.\n\n===Filmography===\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"float: centre; margin-centre: 0; margin-centre: 1em;\"\n!Year\n!Title\n!Role\n!Notes\n|-\n|1995\n|''[[The Jerry Springer Show]]''\n|Razor Ramon\n|1 episode\n|-\n|2011\n|''E:60''\n|Himself\n|Documentary; 1 episode\n|-\n|2010\n|''[[Big Money Rustlas]]''\n|Sign guy\n|\n|-\n|2013\n|''[[Real Sports with Bryant Gumbel]]''\n|Himself\n|1 episode\n|-\n|2015\n|''[[Larry King Show]]''\n|Himself/Guest\n|1 episode\n|-\n|2016\n|''[[Table for 3]]''\n|Himself\n|1 episode\n|-\n|2019\n|''Traveling the Stars: Action Bronson and Friends Watch Ancient Aliens''\n|Himself\n|1 episode\n|}\n\n== Championships and accomplishments ==\n[[File:Razor Ramon IC Champ.jpg|right|thumb|Hall held the [[WWE Intercontinental Championship|WWF Intercontinental Championship]] four times, a former record for the championship]]\n[[File:Scott Hall Hall of Fame (cropped).jpg|thumb|Hall was inducted into the [[WWE Hall of Fame]] in 2014]]\n* '''[[American Wrestling Association]]'''\n** [[AWA World Tag Team Championship]] ([[List of AWA World Tag Team Champions|1 time]]) \u2013 with [[Curt Hennig]]<ref name=\"awatag\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wrestling-titles.com/awa/awa-t.html|title=AWA World Tag Team Title history|publisher=Wrestling-titles.com|accessdate=March 5, 2009}}</ref>\n* '''[[DDT Pro-Wrestling]]'''\n** [[Ironman Heavymetalweight Championship]] ([[Ironman Heavymetalweight Championship#Title history|1 time]])<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wrestling-titles.com/japan/ddt/ironman-hm.html|title=Ironman Heavymetalweight Title|accessdate=August 12, 2016|publisher=Wrestling-Titles.com}}</ref>\n* '''''[[Pro Wrestling Illustrated]]'''''\n** [[List of Pro Wrestling Illustrated awards#Match of the Year|Match of the Year]] (1994)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.100megsfree4.com/wiawrestling/pages/pwi/pwimoty.htm |accessdate=June 23, 2008 |title=Pro Wrestling Illustrated Award Winners Match of the Year |publisher=Wrestling Information Archive |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080616063308/http://www.100megsfree4.com/wiawrestling/pages/pwi/pwimoty.htm |archivedate=June 16, 2008 }}</ref> {{small|vs. [[Shawn Michaels]] in a [[ladder match]] at [[WrestleMania X]]}}\n** [[List of Pro Wrestling Illustrated awards#Most Improved Wrestler of the Year|Most Improved Wrestler of the Year]] (1992)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.100megsfree4.com/wiawrestling/pages/pwi/pwiimp.htm |accessdate=June 23, 2008 |title=Pro Wrestling Illustrated Award Winners Most Improved Wrestler of the Year |publisher=Wrestling Information Archive |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110921094752/http://www.100megsfree4.com/wiawrestling/pages/pwi/pwiimp.htm |archivedate=September 21, 2011 }}</ref>\n** [[List of Pro Wrestling Illustrated awards#Tag Team of the Year|Tag Team of the Year]] (1997)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.100megsfree4.com/wiawrestling/pages/pwi/pwittoty.htm |accessdate=June 23, 2008 |title=Pro Wrestling Illustrated Award Winners Tag Team of the Year |publisher=Wrestling Information Archive |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110813033722/http://100megsfree4.com/wiawrestling/pages/pwi/pwittoty.htm |archivedate=August 13, 2011 }}</ref> {{small|with [[Kevin Nash]]}}\n** Ranked No. 7 of the top 500 singles wrestlers in the ''[[Pro Wrestling Illustrated#PWI 500|PWI 500]]'' in 1994<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.100megsfree4.com/wiawrestling/pages/pwi/pwi50094.htm |accessdate=July 1, 2008 |title=Pro Wrestling Illustrated Top 500 \u2013 1994 |publisher=Wrestling Information Archive |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110522005445/http://www.100megsfree4.com/wiawrestling/pages/pwi/pwi50094.htm |archivedate=May 22, 2011 }}</ref>\n** Ranked No. 72 of the top 500 singles wrestlers of the ''PWI Years'' in 2003<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.100megsfree4.com/wiawrestling/pages/pwi/pwi500yr.htm|title=Pro Wrestling Illustrated's Top 500 Wrestlers of the PWI Years|accessdate=March 14, 2009|publisher=Wrestling Information Archive|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090227054535/http://www.100megsfree4.com/wiawrestling/pages/pwi/pwi500yr.htm|archivedate=February 27, 2009}}</ref>\n** Ranked No. 40 and No. 98 of the top 100 tag teams of the ''PWI Years'' with Kevin Nash and Curt Hennig, respectively, in 2003<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.100megsfree4.com/wiawrestling/pages/pwi/pwi100tg.htm |accessdate=June 23, 2008 |title=Pro Wrestling Illustrated's Top 100 Tag Teams of the PWI Years |publisher=Wrestling Information Archive |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090325080845/http://www.100megsfree4.com/wiawrestling/pages/pwi/pwi100tg.htm |archivedate=March 25, 2009 }}</ref>\n* '''[[United States Wrestling Association]]'''\n** [[USWA Unified World Heavyweight Championship]] ([[USWA Unified World Heavyweight Championship#Title history|1 time]])<ref name=\"uswa\">[http://www.wrestling-titles.com/us/tn/uswa/uswa-uh.html Unified World Heavyweight Title (USWA)]. Wrestling-titles.com. Retrieved on November 29, 2013.</ref>\n* '''[[World Championship Wrestling]]'''\n** [[WCW World Television Championship]] ([[List of WCW World Television Champions|1 time]])<ref name=\"tvtitle\">[http://www.wrestling-titles.com/wcw/wcw-tv.html NWA/WCW World Television Title]. Wrestling-titles.com. Retrieved on November 29, 2013.</ref>\n** [[WWE United States Championship|WCW United States Heavyweight Championship]] ([[List of WWE United States Champions|2 times]])<ref>[http://www.wwe.com/classics/titlehistory/unitedstates/30445411132 19990221 \u2013 Scott Hall]. WWE.com. Retrieved on November 29, 2013.</ref><ref>[http://www.wwe.com/classics/titlehistory/unitedstates/304454112121 19991108 \u2013 Scott Hall]. WWE.com. Retrieved on November 29, 2013.</ref>\n** [[WCW World Tag Team Championship]] ([[List of WCW World Tag Team Champions|7 times]]) \u2013 with Kevin Nash (6) and [[Big Show|The Giant]] (1)<ref name=\"wcwtag\"/>\n** [[World War 3 (1997)]]<ref name=\"1997worldwar3\"/>\n* '''[[Total Nonstop Action Wrestling]]'''\n** [[TNA World Tag Team Championship]] ([[List of TNA World Tag Team Champions|1 time]]) \u2013 with Kevin Nash and [[Eric Young (wrestler)|Eric Young]]{{Efn|Hall defended the championship with either Nash or Young under the [[Freebird Rule]].}}\n* '''[[World Wrestling Council]]'''\n** [[WWC Caribbean Heavyweight Championship]] ([[WWC Caribbean Heavyweight Championship#Title history|1 time]])<ref name=\"caribbeantitle\">[http://www.wrestling-titles.com/us/pr/wwc/carib-h.html Caribbean Heavyweight Title]. Wrestling-titles.com. Retrieved on November 29, 2013.</ref>\n** [[WWC Universal Heavyweight Championship]] ([[WWC Universal Heavyweight Championship#Title history|1 time]])<ref name=Uni/>\n* '''[[WWE|World Wrestling Federation/WWE]]'''\n** [[WWE Intercontinental Championship|WWF Intercontinental Championship]] ([[List of WWE Intercontinental Champions|4 times]])<ref>[http://www.wwe.com/classics/titlehistory/intercontinental/322472 Intercontinental Championship \u2013 Razor Ramon September 27, 1993 \u2013 April 13, 1994]. WWE.com. Retrieved on November 29, 2013.</ref><ref>[http://www.wwe.com/classics/titlehistory/intercontinental/322480 Intercontinental Championship \u2013 Razor Ramon August 29, 1994 \u2013 January 22, 1995]. WWE.com. Retrieved on November 29, 2013.</ref><ref>[http://www.wwe.com/classics/titlehistory/intercontinental/322492 Intercontinental Championship \u2013 Razor Ramon May 19, 1995 \u2013 May 22, 1995]. WWE.com. Retrieved on November 29, 2013.</ref><ref>[http://www.wwe.com/classics/titlehistory/intercontinental/322508 Intercontinental Championship \u2013 Razor Ramon October 22, 1995 \u2013 January 21, 1996]. WWE.com. Retrieved on November 29, 2013.</ref>\n** [[WWE Hall of Fame]] (2 times)\n***[[WWE Hall of Fame (2014)|Class of 2014]] \u2013 individually<ref name=\"WWE\"/>\n*** [[WWE Hall of Fame (2020)|Class of 2020]] \u2013 as a member of the [[New World Order (professional wrestling)|New World Order]]<ref>{{cite news |last1=Johnson |first1=Mike |title=2020 WWE HALL OF FAME CLASS HEADLINERS ANNOUNCED {{!}} PWInsider.com |url=https://www.pwinsider.com/article/132054/2020-wwe-hall-of-fame-class-headliners-announced.html?p=1 |accessdate=December 10, 2019 |work=www.pwinsider.com |date=December 9, 2019}}</ref>\n** [[Slammy Award]] (2 times)\n*** Most Spectacular Match ([[Slammy Award#1994 Slammy Awards|1994]]) {{small|vs. Shawn Michaels in a ladder match at WrestleMania X}}<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.prowrestlinghistory.com/supercards/usa/wwf/slammy.html#94|title=The Slammy Awards|website=www.prowrestlinghistory.com}}</ref>\n*** Match of the Year ([[1996 Slammy Awards|1996]]) {{small|vs. Shawn Michaels at [[SummerSlam (1995)|SummerSlam]]}}<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.prowrestlinghistory.com/supercards/usa/wwf/slammy.html#96|title=The Slammy Awards|website=www.prowrestlinghistory.com}}</ref>\n* '''''[[Wrestling Observer Newsletter]]'''''\n** [[List of Wrestling Observer Newsletter awards#Match of the Year|Match of the Year]] (1994) {{small|vs. Shawn Michaels in a ladder match at WrestleMania X}}<ref name=\"won\">{{cite journal|last=Meltzer|first=Dave|authorlink=Dave Meltzer|date=January 26, 2011|title=Biggest issue of the year: The 2011 Wrestling Observer Newsletter Awards Issue|periodical=[[Wrestling Observer Newsletter]]|location=Campbell, CA|pages=1\u201340|issn=1083-9593}}</ref>\n** [[List of Wrestling Observer Newsletter awards#Best Gimmick|Best Gimmick]] (1996) {{small|as a member of New World Order}}<ref name=\"won\"/>\n** [[List of Wrestling Observer Newsletter awards#Most Disgusting Promotional Tactic|Most Disgusting Promotional Tactic]] (1998) {{small|WCW exploiting his alcoholism in a gimmick}}<ref name=\"won\"/>\n\n== Notes ==\n{{notelist}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category}}\n* {{WWE superstar|name=Razor Ramon}}\n* {{Professional wrestling profiles}}\n* {{IMDb name}}\n*[http://wrestlingexaminer.com/scott-hall-say-hello-to-the-bad-guy/ Scott Hall Article]\n\n{{Navboxes|\n|list1=\n{{New World Order}}\n{{TNA World Tag Team Championship}}\n{{WCW World Television Championship}}\n{{WWC Universal Heavyweight Championship}}\n{{WWE Intercontinental Championship}}\n{{WWE United States Championship}}\n{{WCW World Tag Team Championship}}\n{{WWE Hall of Fame}}\n}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hall, Scott}}\n[[Category:1958 births]]\n[[Category:American male professional wrestlers]]\n[[Category:Bridgeport Bluefish guest managers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Military brats]]\n[[Category:NWA/WCW World Television Champions]]\n[[Category:NWA/WCW/WWE United States Heavyweight Champions]]\n[[Category:People from St. Mary's County, Maryland]]\n[[Category:Professional wrestlers from Florida]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Seminole County, Florida]]\n[[Category:The Kliq members]]\n[[Category:The New World Order (professional wrestling) members]]\n[[Category:USWA Unified World Heavyweight Champions]]\n[[Category:WWE Hall of Fame inductees]]\n[[Category:WWF/WWE Intercontinental Champions]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American professional wrestler}}\n{{about|the professional wrestler}}\n{{Redirect|Razor Ramon|other uses|Razor Ramon (disambiguation)}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=December 2019}}\n{{Infobox professional wrestler\n|name        = Scott Hall\n|image       = Scott Hall with Paul Billets (cropped).jpg\n|image_size  = \n|alt         =\n|caption     = Hall in 1998\n|birthname   = Scott Oliver Hall<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://windsorstar.com/arts-2/scott-hall-wrestled-with-life-as-razor-ramon|title=Scott Hall wrestled with life as Razor Ramon &#124; Windsor Star|date=October 17, 2013}}</ref>\n|spouse      = {{Plainlist|Dana Burgio ({{abbr|m.|married}} 1990\u2013{{abbr|div.|divorced}} 1998; {{abbr|m.|married}} 1999\u2013{{abbr|div.|divorced}} 2001)<br>{{marriage|Jessica Hart|2006|2007|reason=divorced}}}}\n|children    = 2, including [[Cody Hall]]\n|names       = The Diamond Studd<ref name=\"OWOW\"/><br>Razor Ramon<ref name=\"OWOW\"/><br>'''Scott Hall'''<ref name=\"OWOW\"/><br>Starship Coyote<ref name=\"OWOW\"/><br>Texas Scott<ref name=\"OWOW\"/>\n|height      = 6 ft 7 in<ref name=\"WWE\"/>\n|weight      = 287 lb<ref name=\"WWE\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/superstars/razor-ramon|title=Razor Ramon bio|publisher=[[WWE]]|accessdate=April 30, 2018}}</ref>\n|birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|1958|10|20|mf=y}}<ref name=\"OWOW\"/>\n|birth_place = [[St. Mary's County, Maryland]], U.S.\n|resides     = [[Duluth, Georgia]], U.S.<ref>[http://podcastone.com/Steve-Austin-Show?showAllEpisodes=true Steve Austin Show podcast, \"SAS-EP#32 \u2013 Razor Ramon\" (21:50)]. Podcastone.com. Retrieved on November 29, 2013.</ref>\n|billed      = '''[[Chuluota, Florida]]'''<br>[[Miami]], [[Florida]]<ref name=\"WWE\"/>\n|trainer     = [[Hiro Matsuda]] \n|debut       = 1984<ref>[http://www.wrestlingdata.com/index.php?befehl=bios&wrestler=44 Scott Hall's profile at]. Wrestlingdata.com. Retrieved on November 29, 2013.</ref>\n|retired     = 2010<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.grunge.com/90291/retired-wrestlers-completely-unrecognizable-today/|title=Retired wrestlers who are completely unrecognizable today|first=Jason|last=Iannone|website=Grunge.com|date=October 10, 2017 |accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref>\n}}\n'''Scott Oliver Hall''' (born October 20, 1958) is an American retired [[Professional wrestling|professional wrestler]]. He is best known for his work with the World Wrestling Federation (WWF, now [[WWE]]) as '''Razor Ramon''' and with World Championship Wrestling ([[World Championship Wrestling|WCW]]) under his real name.\n\nBeginning with his time in the [[American Wrestling Association]] (AWA), Hall maintained a perennially high profile as a wrestler, as he became a [[List of WWE Intercontinental Champions|four time]] [[WWE Intercontinental Championship|WWF Intercontinental Champion]] (a record from 1995 to 1999), a [[List of WWE United States Champions|two-time]] [[WWE United States Championship|WCW United States Heavyweight Champion]], a [[List of WCW World Television Champions|one-time]] [[WCW World Television Championship|WCW World Television Champion]], and a nine-time [[World tag team championship|world tag team champion]] ([[List of WCW World Tag Team Champions|seven times in WCW]], [[List of TNA World Tag Team Champions|once in TNA]], and [[AWA World Tag Team Championship|once in the AWA]]). In addition, Hall is a two-time [[world champion]], having won the [[WWC Universal Heavyweight Championship]] and the [[USWA Unified World Heavyweight Championship]]. He is also notable for being a founding member of the [[New World Order (professional wrestling)|New World Order (nWo)]]. On April 5, 2014, Hall was inducted individually into the [[WWE Hall of Fame]] as Razor Ramon, and he will be inducted a second time (this time under his real name) in 2020 as a member of nWo, together with fellow former stablemates [[Hulk Hogan]], [[Kevin Nash]] and [[Sean Waltman]].\n\n== Early life ==\nHall was born in St. Mary's County, Maryland. He grew up as an [[army brat]] and moved once every year before he was fifteen.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://slam.canoe.com/Slam/Wrestling/2016/06/24/22646003.html|title=Scott Hall once again the Bad Guy|author=Murphy, Jan|work=Slam! Wrestling|publisher=[[Canadian Online Explorer]]|date=April 3, 2016|accessdate=September 12, 2016}}</ref> He attended [[high school]] in [[Munich]], [[West Germany]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=SHJsJPpIXWg|title=Scott Hall reveals he'd eat out Paige + Talks Sexcapades & Ring Rats|last=Controversial Wrestling Shoots|date=November 14, 2016|publisher=|via=YouTube}}</ref>\n\n== Professional wrestling career ==\n\n=== National Wrestling Alliance (1984) ===\nHall began his career in 1984 in the [[National Wrestling Alliance]]'s (NWA) Florida territory [[Championship Wrestling from Florida]] (CWF) and soon began a [[Feud (professional wrestling)|feud]] with [[Dusty Rhodes (wrestler)|Dusty Rhodes]].<ref name=\"scottbio\">{{cite web|url=http://www.thescotthall.com/about.html|title=Biography|work=Scott Hall's Official Website|accessdate=June 18, 2008}}</ref> He and [[Dan Spivey]] trained together in Florida (mainly under Rhodes, but also under [[Mike Rotunda]] and [[Barry Windham]]). When it was time for the two to debut as a tag team, Rhodes sent them to work in [[Jim Crockett]]'s [[Charlotte, North Carolina]] based territory. They debuted as American Starship, Hall under the ring name Starship Coyote and Spivey under the ring name Starship Eagle.<ref name=\"OWOW\">{{cite web|url=http://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/profiles/s/scott-hall.html|title=Scott Hall Profile|publisher=Online World of Wrestling|accessdate=June 18, 2008}}</ref><ref name=\"earlycareer\">{{cite web|url=http://www.accelerator3359.com/Wrestling/bios/hall.html#beginning|title=Scott Hall's Early Career|work=Accelerator's Wrestling Rollercoaster|accessdate=June 18, 2008}}</ref>\n\nAt first, American Starship were booked to wrestle infrequently; so much so that the two were given ground crew jobs for the Charlotte Orioles (which Jim Crockett owned at the time). When they did get in the ring, it was with little success. The highlight of their stay in Crockett's [[Jim Crockett Promotions|Mid Atlantic Championship Wrestling]] was a losing challenge to [[Arn Anderson|Arn]] and [[Ole Anderson]] for the NWA National Tag Team Championship. After leaving Crockett, the duo joined [[Bob Geigel]]'s [[Heart of America Sports Attractions|NWA Central States]] territory (based in Kansas City) in 1985.\n\nThey received a shot at NWA Central States Tag Team Champions [[Marty Jannetty]] and \"Bulldog\" Bob Brown, but lost the match. Dan Spivey's stay in the Central States territory was brief. He returned to the Carolinas and Crockett, [[Job (professional wrestling)|jobbing]] in the freshly rebranded [[Jim Crockett Promotions]] as \"American Starship\" Eagle. Hall, meanwhile, stayed in Central States, receiving a solid [[Push (professional wrestling)|push]].\n\n=== American Wrestling Association (1985 - 1989) ===\nHall joined the [[American Wrestling Association]] (AWA) in 1985, where he wrestled as \"Magnum\" Scott Hall and, later, \"Big\" Scott Hall. He wrestled as a [[Face (professional wrestling)|babyface]] wrestler.<ref name=\"OWOW\"/><ref name=\"awa\">{{cite web|url=http://www.accelerator3359.com/Wrestling/bios/hall.html#awa|title=Scott Hall's AWA Career|work=Accelerator's Wrestling Rollercoaster|accessdate=June 18, 2008}}</ref> [[Verne Gagne]], the owner and promoter of the AWA, had wanted to push Hall to the same heights as he had [[Hulk Hogan]], following Hogan's departure for [[Vince McMahon]]'s [[WWE|World Wrestling Federation]] (WWF).<ref name=\"scottbio\"/><ref name=\"awa\"/> Gagne had Hall use mannerisms and moves similar to Hogan.<ref name=\"scottbio\"/> Hall also travelled to Japan, where he wrestled several matches for [[New Japan Pro-Wrestling]] (NJPW) between 1987 and 1990.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.profightdb.com/wrestlers/scott-hall-147.html?prom_id=27|title=NJPW matches wrestled by Scott Hall|publisher=ProFightDB|accessdate=September 4, 2019}}</ref>\n\nHall formed a tag team with his more experienced friend [[Curt Hennig]], whom he later would credit for cultivating his early professional wrestling career.<ref>Keller, Wade [http://www.blogtalkradio.com/pro-wrestling-torch/2013/05/03/pwtorch-livecast PWTorch Livecast \u2013 Wade Keller Interviews Scott Hall] PWTorch (May 3, 2013). Retrieved August 9, 2013.</ref> The team defeated [[Jimmy Garvin]] and [[Steve Regal]] for the [[AWA World Tag Team Championship]] on January 18, 1986, in a 58-minute match in [[Albuquerque, New Mexico]].<ref name=\"OWOW\"/><ref name=\"awatag\"/> The champions defended against such challengers as [[Buddy Rose]] and [[Doug Somers]], [[John Nord|Nord the Barbarian]] and [[Boris Zhukov]], and [[Bill Irwin (wrestler)|Bill]] and [[Scott Irwin]].<ref name=\"OWOW\"/><ref name=\"scottbio\"/><ref name=\"awa\"/> They lost the belts to Rose and Somers by [[countout]] (an unusual and unexplained deviation from the standard rule of pro wrestling) on May 17, after interference by [[Colonel DeBeers]].<ref name=\"scottbio\"/> After losing the title, Hall and Hennig soon parted ways. Hall then received shots at the [[AWA World Heavyweight Championship]], against [[Stan Hansen]] and [[Rick Martel]].<ref name=\"scottbio\"/><ref name=\"awa\"/> Although Gagne wanted to put the belt on Hall, Hall hated the cold weather in the territory, recognized the AWA as a \"sinking ship,\" and left for the NWA in 1989.<ref name=\"scottbio\"/> The AWA folded the following year.\n\n=== World Championship Wrestling (1989) ===\nHall was brought into the NWA's [[World Championship Wrestling]] (WCW) territory by [[Jim Ross]] in 1989, as part of the NWA's initiative to develop new, young stars (also including [[Brian Pillman]] and [[Sid Eudy|Sid Vicious]]).<ref name=\"scottbio\"/> He made his debut on the June 3rd edition of '''World Championship Wrestling''' (the predecessor to WCW Saturday Night) in a vignette that showed Scott \"Gator\" Hall swimming and playing volleyball at a beach, riding boats, fishing, and scaring alligators. His in-ring debut came on June 16th on a house show in Cleveland, OH, where he teamed with [[Randy Rose]] in a losing effort against [[WCW World Tag-Team Champions]] {[The Freebirds]]. While waiting for his first television match, he continued to wrestle on the road and was winless in tag-team and singles action, facing [[Norman}}, The Freebirds, and [[Dan Spivey]]. Hall finally gained his first victory on June 29th when he pinned Rip Morgan in Salisbury, MD, and then entered a successful house show series with [[Bill Irwin]].\n\nHis television debut finally came on the July 9th edition of World Championship Wrestling where he was pinned by [[The Great Muta]]. On the July 9th edition of [[WCW Pro]] he faced [[Terry Funk]] and was defeated.<ref>http://www.thehistoryofwwe.com/wcw89.htm</ref>His PPV debut came at [[The Great American Bash 1989|The Great American Bash: The Glory Days]], where he participated in a [[Battle royal (professional wrestling)|King of the Hill battle royal]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.prowrestlinghistory.com/supercards/usa/wcw/gabash.html#89|title=The Great American Bash 1989: The Glory Days results|work=Wrestling Supercards and Tournaments|accessdate=June 27, 2008}}</ref> He then began [[Job (professional wrestling)|jobbing]] regularly, losing to The Great Muta, [[Mike Rotunda]], [[Sid Vicious]], [[Ron Simmons]], and [[Butch Reed]]. His final match came on November 7th when he was defeated by Butch Reed at a house show in Chicago, IL. After this he went on hiatus.<ref name=\"scottbio\"/><ref name=\"nwa\">{{cite web|url=http://www.accelerator3359.com/Wrestling/bios/hall.html#nwa|title=Scott Hall's NWA Career|work=Accelerator's Wrestling Rollercoaster|accessdate=June 28, 2008}}</ref>\n\n=== World Wrestling Federation (1990) ===\nA little over two years after having received a tryout at a house show in August 1987<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.cagematch.net/?id=1&nr=42455 |title = WWF House Show \" Events Database \" CAGEMATCH - the Internet Wrestling Database |accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref>, Hall received another tryout at a [[WWF Wrestling Challenge]] taping in Fort Myers, FL. He was defeated by [[Paul Roma]] and did not sign with the company at this time.<ref>http://www.thehistoryofwwe.com/90.htm</ref>\n\n=== New Japan Pro Wrestling (1990) ===\nShortly afterwards Hall joined [[New Japan Pro Wrestling]], teaming with [[Larry Cameron]] and defeating [[Hiroshi Hase]] & [[Kuniaki Kobayashi]] March 2, 1990 at Korakuen Hall in Tokyo, Japan<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.cagematch.net/?id=1&nr=60156 |title = NJPW Big Fight Series 1990 \" Events Database \" CAGEMATCH - the Internet Wrestling Database |accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref> He wrestled numerous times for the company, facing a diverse group of opponents including [[Bam Bam Bigelow]], [[Koji Kitao]], [[Nord the Barbarian]], and [[Shinya Hashimoto]].\n\n=== Catch Wrestling Association (1990) ===\nScott Hall, as '''Texas Scott''', competed for the [[Catch Wrestling Association]] (CWA) at the \"Catch Cup '90\" tournament on December 22, 1990 in Bremen, Germany before 6,000 fans. Hall was defeated by the Soul Taker in the tournament final. This big event featured the retirement match of [[Otto Wanz]], as well as [[Terry Funk]], Bull Power ([[Big Van Vader]]), [[Chris Benoit]], [[Dave Taylor (wrestler)|David Taylor]], [[Fit Finlay]], and [[Akira Nogami]] in action.\n\n=== World Wrestling Council (1990 - 1991) ===\nFrom 1990 to 1991, Hall had a stint in the [[Puerto Rico|Puerto Rican]] promotion [[World Wrestling Council]] (WWC).<ref name=\"nwa\"/> On March 3, he defeated [[Miguel P\u00e9rez, Jr.]] for the [[WWC Caribbean Heavyweight Championship]].<ref name=\"caribbeantitle\"/> He lost it to Super Medic III on April 20.<ref name=\"nwa\"/>\n\n=== World Championship Wrestling (1991\u20131992) ===\n{{main|Diamond Exchange#The Diamond Mine}}\nAfter wrestling a dark match on April 29th, 1991 in Atlanta, GA at a taping of World Championship Wrestling<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.cagematch.net/?id=1&nr=81657 |title = WCW World Championship Wrestling \" Events Database \" CAGEMATCH - the Internet Wrestling Database |accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref>, Hall made his official return to WCW<ref name=\"wcw\">{{cite web|url=http://www.accelerator3359.com/Wrestling/bios/hall.html#wcw|title=Scott Hall's WCW Career (1991\u20131992)|work=Accelerator's Wrestling Rollercoaster|accessdate=June 28, 2008}}</ref> and was renamed '''The Diamond Studd''', a [[Gimmick (professional wrestling)|gimmick]] similar to [[Rick Rude]]'s (both were cocky, vain and would invite attractive [[Plant (professional wrestling)|women from the audience]] into the ring). He was [[Manager (professional wrestling)|managed]] by [[Diamond Dallas Page]], and made his first appearance on May 19th at [[SuperBrawl 1]].<ref name=\"wcw\"/> In his debut match, he [[Squash (professional wrestling)|squashed]] [[Tommy Rich]] on the June 14 episode of ''[[Clash of the Champions XV: Knocksville USA]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.prowrestlinghistory.com/supercards/usa/wcw/clash.html#XV |title=Clash of the Champions XV: Knocksville USA results |work=Wrestling Supercards and Tournaments |accessdate=June 28, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080623095650/http://www.prowrestlinghistory.com/supercards/usa/wcw/clash.html |archivedate=June 23, 2008 }}</ref> He defeated [[Tom Zenk]] at [[The Great American Bash 1991|The Great American Bash]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.prowrestlinghistory.com/supercards/usa/wcw/gabash.html#91|title=The Great American Bash 1991 results|work=Wrestling Supercards and Tournaments|accessdate=June 28, 2008}}</ref> At ''[[Clash of the Champions XVI: Fall Brawl]]'' on September 2, The Diamond Studd lost to [[Ron Simmons]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.prowrestlinghistory.com/supercards/usa/wcw/clash.html#XVI |title=Clash of the Champions XVI: Fall Brawl results |work=Wrestling Supercards and Tournaments |accessdate=June 28, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080623095650/http://www.prowrestlinghistory.com/supercards/usa/wcw/clash.html |archivedate=June 23, 2008 }}</ref> At [[Halloween Havoc 1991]], the team of Studd, [[Abdullah the Butcher]], [[Mick Foley|Cactus Jack]], and [[Big Van Vader]] lost to [[Steve Borden|Sting]], [[Jorge Gonz\u00e1lez (wrestler)|El Gigante]], and [[The Steiner Brothers]] in a \"Chamber of Horrors Match\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.prowrestlinghistory.com/supercards/usa/wcw/havoc.html#91|title=Halloween Havoc 1991: Chamber of Horrors results|work=Wrestling Supercards and Tournaments|accessdate=June 28, 2008}}</ref> On the November 19 episode of ''[[Clash of the Champions XVII]]'', Studd lost to Zenk in a rematch from The Great American Bash.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.prowrestlinghistory.com/supercards/usa/wcw/clash.html#XVII |title=Clash of the Champions XVII results |work=Wrestling Supercards and Tournaments |accessdate=June 28, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080623095650/http://www.prowrestlinghistory.com/supercards/usa/wcw/clash.html |archivedate=June 23, 2008 }}</ref>\n\nAfter an injury sidelined him for [[Starrcade (1991)|Starrcade]] in December 1991, Hall entered 1992 forming short-lived tag teams with [[Kevin Nash|Vinnie Vegas]] and [[Raven (wrestler)|Scotty Flamingo]] (as part of The Diamond Mine [[Smark|stable]]), as well as with members of [[Paul Heyman|Paul E. Dangerously]]'s [[Dangerous Alliance]].<ref name=\"wcw\"/> Hall began a feud with [[Dustin Rhodes]] in April 1992 when he interfered in two televised matches Rhodes had with [[Bobby Eaton]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thehistoryofwwe.com/wcw92.htm|title=WCW 1992|website=Thehistoryofwwe.com}}</ref> The idea of adding him to the Dangerous Alliance was contemplated, but fell through, and Hall left WCW shortly after a final televised match against Ron Campbell on May 8.<ref name=\"wcw\"/>\n\n=== World Wrestling Federation/WWF===\n==== Debut and various feuds (1992\u20131993) ====\n[[File:Razor Ramon posing.jpg|thumb|175px|left|Hall as Razor Ramon]]\nHall joined the [[WWE|World Wrestling Federation]] (WWF) later that month, as '''Razor Ramon''', a shady and stylish [[Cuban American]] bully from [[Miami]].<ref name=\"scottbio\"/><ref name=\"wwf\"/> The character was modeled after the characters [[Tony Montana]] and [[Manny Ribera]] from the movie ''[[Scarface (1983 film)|Scarface]]''.<ref name=\"wwf\"/> Ramon's nickname (The Bad Guy) and catchphrase (\"Say hello to The Bad Guy\") derive from Montana's quotes: \"Say hello to my little friend\" and \"Say goodnight to the bad guy\".<ref name=\"wwf\">{{cite web|url=http://www.accelerator3359.com/Wrestling/bios/hall.html#wwf|title=Scott Hall's WWF Career (1992)|work=Accelerator's Wrestling Rollercoaster|accessdate=June 28, 2008}}</ref> He made his first appearance in a dark match on a ''[[WWF Wrestling Challenge|Wrestling Challenge]]'' taping against Chris Hahn on May 18, 1992.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thehistoryofwwe.com/92.htm|title=History of WWE|website=Thehistoryofwwe.com|accessdate=December 6, 2015}}</ref> Later in his career, Hall claimed he pitched the idea of a ''Scarface''-like character during a meeting with [[Vince McMahon]] and [[Pat Patterson (wrestler)|Pat Patterson]], as a joke.<ref name=\"scottbio\"/> Hall quoted lines from the film with a Cuban accent and gave ideas for [[Glossary of professional wrestling terms#V|vignettes]] that would recreate several of the film's scenes, such as driving around [[South Florida metropolitan area|South Florida]] in a [[convertible]] with a [[animal print|leopard-skin]] interior.<ref name=\"scottbio\"/> Although taken right from the film, Hall claims McMahon and Patterson were nevertheless floored by the ideas and called him a \"genius\".<ref name=\"scottbio\"/> Hall later learned that McMahon and Patterson had neither seen nor heard of the film, and believed that Hall was coming up with the ideas himself. Patterson and McMahon came up with the name \"Razor\", but agreed with Hall's suggestion that it should be a nickname, and that the character should have a proper given name. Hall later asked [[Tito Santana]] for a Latino-sounding name that starts with \"R\". Santana suggested \"Ramon\", Hall brought it back to McMahon and the name stuck.<ref name=\"scottbio\"/> The Razor Ramon logo and costume were designed by [[Tom Fleming (artist)|Tom Fleming]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Never-before-seen Superstar sketches from the WWE Vault|url=http://www.wwe.com/classics/superstar-sketches-photos|website=WWE.com|accessdate=March 21, 2016}}</ref>\n\nAfter weeks of introductory vignettes, Razor Ramon made his ring debut on the August 8, 1992 episode of ''[[WWF Superstars of Wrestling|Superstars]]'', defeating local jobber Paul Van Dow with his finishing move, [[Powerbomb#Crucifix powerbomb|The Razor's Edge]] (previously called \"The Diamond Death Drop\" in WCW).<ref>{{cite web|date=July 20, 1992|url=http://www.angelfire.com/wrestling/cawthon777/superstars.htm|title=WWF Superstars (1986\u20131997)|work=Angelfire|accessdate=June 28, 2008|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080429091409/http://www.angelfire.com/wrestling/cawthon777/superstars.htm|archivedate = April 29, 2008}}</ref> Early on, Ramon wore large gold chain necklaces to the ring. While handing them to an attendant at ringside he would threaten \"Something happens to this, something gonna happen to you\", and then flick his toothpick at the helpless attendant.<ref name=\"scottbio\"/>\n\nRazor's first major [[Glossary of professional wrestling terms#A|angle]] began on the September 14 episode of ''[[WWF Prime Time Wrestling|Prime Time Wrestling]]'', when he interfered in a [[WWE World Championship|WWF Championship]] match between champion [[Randy Savage]] and [[Ric Flair]], attacking Savage on the floor and enabling Flair to win the title.<ref name=\"Flair vs Savage\">{{cite web|date=September 1, 1992|url=http://www.angelfire.com/wrestling/cawthon777/92.htm|title=WWF Show Results 1992|work=Angelfire|accessdate=June 28, 2008|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080505064406/http://www.angelfire.com/wrestling/cawthon777/92.htm|archivedate=May 5, 2008}}</ref> As a result, Razor and Savage started a [[Feud (professional wrestling)|feud]], which later involved [[The Ultimate Warrior]], after Warrior saved Savage from a post-match beating by Razor.<ref name=\"Flair vs Savage\"/> Razor and Flair were scheduled to face The Ultimate Maniacs (Savage and Warrior) at [[Survivor Series (1992)|Survivor Series]]. However, Warrior was fired from the WWF prior to the event and replaced by Flair's \"executive consultant\", [[Curt Hennig|Mr. Perfect]]. Razor and Flair lost to Savage and Perfect via disqualification, for constantly double-teaming them.<ref name=\"wwf\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/survivorseries/history/1992/results/|title=Survivor Series 1992 official results|publisher=WWE|accessdate=June 28, 2008}}</ref>\n\nWWF Champion [[Bret Hart]] was scheduled to defend his title against The Ultimate Warrior at the [[Royal Rumble (1993)|Royal Rumble]], but Razor Ramon replaced Warrior after he left the company.<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=UdSpoy6g5ZE&t=4m25s Bret Hart talks Roddy Piper & Shawn Michaels]. ''Aftermath''. [[The Score Television Network]]. June 11, 2012. Retrieved July 19, 2012.</ref> During the feud, Razor verbally disrespected Hart and the [[Hart wrestling family]].<ref name=\"scottbio\"/> Razor lost to Hart at the Royal Rumble, submitting to the [[Sharpshooter (professional wrestling)|Sharpshooter]].<ref name=\"OWOW\"/><ref name=\"scottbio\"/><ref name=\"wwf\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/royalrumble/history/19881161/results/|title=Royal Rumble 1993 official results|publisher=WWE|accessdate=June 28, 2008}}</ref> Razor made his [[WrestleMania]] debut at [[WrestleMania IX]], pinning former WWF Champion [[Bob Backlund]] with a roll-up.<ref name=\"OWOW\"/><ref name=\"scottbio\"/><ref name=\"wwf\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/wrestlemania/history/wm9/results/|title=WrestleMania IX official results|publisher=WWE|accessdate=June 28, 2008}}</ref>\n\nOn the May 17 episode of ''[[WWE Raw|Monday Night Raw]]'' he suffered an upset loss to [[Job (professional wrestling)|jobber]] [[Sean Waltman|\"The Kid\"]] (who consequently became known as \"The 1\u20132\u20133 Kid\"), beginning feud between the two.<ref name=\"OWOW\"/><ref name=\"wwf\"/><ref>{{cite web|author=Christopher Robin Zimmerman |date=May 17, 1993 |url=http://www.otherarena.com/htm/cgi-bin/history.cgi?1993/raw051793 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20030530104819/http://www.otherarena.com/htm/cgi-bin/history.cgi?1993%2Fraw051793 |archivedate=May 30, 2003 |title=WWF Raw: May 17, 1993 |work=The Other Arena |accessdate=June 28, 2008 |url-status=dead }}</ref> It carried into the [[King of the Ring tournament]] and triggered a slow [[Face (professional wrestling)|fan favorite]] turn for Razor, as he gained respect for The 1\u20132\u20133 Kid and support from the crowd.<ref name=\"OWOW\"/><ref name=\"scottbio\"/><ref name=\"wwf\"/> [[Ted DiBiase]], however, did not show respect for Razor, making fun of him for losing to such a small jobber. Ramon helped The 1\u20132\u20133 Kid defeat DiBiase, solidifying his face turn.<ref name=\"1993bio\">{{cite web|url=http://www.accelerator3359.com/Wrestling/bios/hall.html#93|title=Scott Hall's WWF Career (1993)|work=Accelerator's Wrestling Rollercoaster|accessdate=June 28, 2008}}</ref> The feud culminated at [[SummerSlam (1993)|SummerSlam]], where Ramon defeated DiBiase in DiBiase's final WWF match.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/summerslam/history/1993/results/|title=SummerSlam 1993 official results|publisher=WWE|accessdate=June 28, 2008}}</ref>\n\n==== Record-setting Intercontinental Champion (1993\u20131996) ====\nOn the October 4, 1993 episode of ''Monday Night Raw'', a 20-man [[Battle royal (professional wrestling)|battle royal]] was held; the last two participants would face each other the next week for the vacant [[WWE Intercontinental Championship|WWF Intercontinental Championship]]. Razor and [[Rick Martel]] were those final two.<ref name=\"ictitle\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/inside/titlehistory/intercontinental/|title=WWE Intercontinental Championship official title history|publisher=WWE|accessdate=June 18, 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Christopher Robin Zimmerman |date=October 4, 1993 |url=http://otherarena.com/htm/cgi-bin/history.cgi?1993/raw100493 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20030610154328/http://otherarena.com/htm/cgi-bin/history.cgi?1993%2Fraw100493 |archivedate=June 10, 2003 |title=WWF Raw: October 04, 1993 |work=The Other Arena |accessdate=June 28, 2008 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The next week on ''Raw'', Razor pinned Martel after a Razor's Edge to win the Intercontinental Championship.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/inside/titlehistory/intercontinental/322472 |title=Razor Ramon's first Intercontinental Championship reign |publisher=WWE |accessdate=June 28, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071230091947/http://www.wwe.com/inside/titlehistory/intercontinental/322472 |archivedate=December 30, 2007 }}</ref>\n\nRamon began a feud with [[Shawn Michaels]] over which man had the stronger [[Claim rights and liberty rights|claim]] to the Intercontinental Championship. Michaels had been stripped of the title months before due to \"[[Kayfabe|inactivity]]\" (he was actually suspended during that time). He returned to television with his own version of the belt, claiming he was still the champion, since he hadn't been beaten for it.<ref name=\"1994bio\"/> The matter was settled when Ramon defeated Michaels in a [[ladder match]] at [[WrestleMania X]], becoming the undisputed Intercontinental Champion after retrieving both belts.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/wrestlemania/history/wm10/results/|title=WrestleMania X official results|publisher=WWE|accessdate=June 28, 2008}}</ref> This match was voted ''[[Pro Wrestling Illustrated]]'''s [[PWI Match of the Year|Match of the Year]] for 1994.<ref name=\"1994bio\"/> It was also the first WWF match to receive a [[Dave Meltzer#Rating system#5-star match|five star rating]] from [[Dave Meltzer]] in his ''[[Wrestling Observer Newsletter]]''.<ref name=\"1994bio\">{{cite web|url=http://www.accelerator3359.com/Wrestling/bios/hall.html#94|title=Scott Hall's WWF Career (1994)|work=Accelerator's Wrestling Rollercoaster|accessdate=June 28, 2008}}</ref> On WWE.com, this match is ranked No. 5 of the Top 24 Matches in WrestleMania History.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/wrestlemania/history/top21 |title=Top 22 Matches in WrestleMania History \u2013 Shawn Michaels vs. Razor Ramon in a Ladder Match for the Intercontinental Championship \u2013 WrestleMania X |work=Accelerator's Wrestling Rollercoaster |accessdate=June 28, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071011023332/http://www.wwe.com/shows/wrestlemania/history/top21 |archivedate=October 11, 2007 }}</ref>\n\n[[File:Razor Ramon in England.jpg|thumb|190px|Ramon with the [[WWE Intercontinental Championship|Intercontinental Championship]] at a WWF event]]\nRazor continued to feud with Michaels and his [[Enforcer (professional wrestling)|bodyguard]] [[Kevin Nash|Diesel]]. On the April 30 episode of ''Superstars'', he lost the Intercontinental Title to Diesel, after interference from Michaels.<ref>{{cite web|date=April 13, 1994|url=http://www.angelfire.com/wrestling/cawthon777/94.htm|title=WWF Show Results 1994|work=Angelfire|accessdate=July 2, 2008|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080501152837/http://www.angelfire.com/wrestling/cawthon777/94.htm|archivedate = May 1, 2008}}</ref> At [[SummerSlam (1994)|SummerSlam]], Razor (with [[Walter Payton]] in his corner) defeated Diesel to win the WWF Intercontinental Championship for a second time, after Shawn Michaels accidentally hit Diesel with [[Superkick|Sweet Chin Music]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/summerslam/history/1994/results/|title=SummerSlam 1994 official results|publisher=WWE|accessdate=July 2, 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/inside/titlehistory/intercontinental/322480 |title=Razor Ramon's second Intercontinental Championship reign |publisher=WWE |accessdate=July 2, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070423103313/http://www.wwe.com/inside/titlehistory/intercontinental/322480 |archivedate=April 23, 2007 }}</ref>\n\nAt [[Survivor Series (1994)|Survivor Series]], he captained a team called \"The Bad Guys\", consisting of himself, The 1\u20132\u20133 Kid, [[Davey Boy Smith]], and [[The Headshrinkers]] ([[Solofa Fatu|Fatu]] and [[Sione Vailahi|Sione]]). They faced The Teamsters (Shawn Michaels, Diesel, Owen Hart, [[Jim Neidhart]], and [[Jeff Jarrett]]). Ramon ended up the sole survivor of the match. This began a feud with Jeff Jarrett, which led into the next year.<ref name=\"1994bio\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/survivorseries/history/1994/results/|title=Survivor Series 1994 official results|publisher=WWE|accessdate=July 2, 2008}}</ref> At the 1995 [[Royal Rumble (1995)|Royal Rumble]], Razor lost the Intercontinental Championship to Jarrett, in controversial fashion; Jarrett had originally won the match by count-out, but demanded that the match be restarted so he could win the title. It was, and Jarrett pinned Razor with a small package.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/royalrumble/history/1988117/results/|title=Royal Rumble 1995 official results|publisher=WWE|accessdate=July 2, 2008}}</ref><ref name=\"1995bio\">{{cite web|url=http://www.accelerator3359.com/Wrestling/bios/hall.html#95|title=Scott Hall's WWF Career (1995)|work=Accelerator's Wrestling Rollercoaster|accessdate=June 28, 2008}}</ref> Razor faced Jarrett in a rematch for the Intercontinental Championship at [[WrestleMania XI]], winning by disqualification when Jarrett's [[Manager (professional wrestling)|assistant]] [[Road Dogg|The Roadie]] interfered. Jarrett retained the title, as a title cannot change hands by countout or disqualification.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/wrestlemania/history/wm11/results/|title=WrestleMania XI official results|publisher=WWE|accessdate=July 2, 2008}}</ref> Razor defeated Jarrett and The Roadie at [[In Your House 1]], in a [[handicap match]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.softwolves.pp.se/wrestling/wwf/1995#iyh1|title=In Your House 1 results|publisher=American Wrestling Trivia|accessdate=July 2, 2008}}</ref>\n\nRazor defeated Jarrett in a ladder match at a May 19, 1995 [[house show]] to win his third WWF Intercontinental Championship.<ref name=\"razor3\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/inside/titlehistory/intercontinental/322492 |title=Razor Ramon's third Intercontinental Championship reign |publisher=WWE |accessdate=July 2, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080724205533/http://www.wwe.com/inside/titlehistory/intercontinental/322492 |archivedate=July 24, 2008 }}</ref> Razor Ramon was the first man to win the Intercontinental Title [[List of WWE Intercontinental Champions|three times]].<ref name=\"razor3\"/> On May 22, he re-lost the title to Jarrett.<ref name=\"razor3\"/> On June 9, Razor suffered a rib injury during a ladder match rematch against Jarrett.<ref name=\"1995bio\"/> Around this time, he had formed a team with [[Savio Vega]], and Vega replaced Razor to defeat Irwin R. Schyster in the [[WWE Free for All|Free for All]] tournament match before the [[King of the Ring (1995)|King of the Ring]] [[pay-per-view]].<ref name=\"1995bio\"/> Razor managed Vega throughout the tournament. He lost to [[Viscera (wrestler)|Mabel]] in the final match.<ref name=\"1995bio\"/> Razor and Vega lost to [[Men on a Mission]] (Mabel and [[Robert Horne (wrestler)|Mo]]) at [[In Your House 2: The Lumberjacks]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.softwolves.pp.se/wrestling/wwf/1995#iyh2|title=In Your House 2 results|publisher=American Wrestling Trivia|accessdate=July 2, 2008}}</ref> and lost a [[World Tag Team Championship (WWE)|WWF (World) Tag Team Championship]] match to [[Owen Hart and Yokozuna]] on the August 7 episode of ''Raw''.<ref>{{cite web|date=July 24, 1995|url=http://www.angelfire.com/wrestling/cawthon777/95.htm|title=WWF Show Results 1995|work=Angelfire|accessdate=July 2, 2008|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080504011947/http://www.angelfire.com/wrestling/cawthon777/95.htm|archivedate = May 4, 2008}}</ref>\n\nRazor had an Intercontinental Championship ladder match (a rematch from WrestleMania X) against the new champion Shawn Michaels at [[SummerSlam (1995)|SummerSlam]],<ref name=\"OWOW\"/><ref name=\"scottbio\"/><ref name=\"1995bio\"/> but lost.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/summerslam/history/1995/results/|title=SummerSlam 1995 official results|publisher=WWE|accessdate=July 2, 2008}}</ref> He then began a feud with [[Shane Douglas|Dean Douglas]]. Razor defeated Douglas at [[In Your House 4]] to win the Intercontinental Championship, after Michaels had just forfeited the title to Douglas. This win made him the first four-time Intercontinental Champion in WWF history.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/inside/titlehistory/intercontinental/322508 |title=Razor Ramon's fourth Intercontinental Championship reign |publisher=WWE |accessdate=July 2, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070429224630/http://www.wwe.com/inside/titlehistory/intercontinental/322508 |archivedate=April 29, 2007 }}</ref>\n\nIn early 1996, Razor feuded with newcomer [[Goldust]], leading to an Intercontinental Championship match at the [[Royal Rumble (1996)|Royal Rumble]]. Razor lost the title to Goldust after Razor's former partner The 1\u20132\u20133 Kid attacked him.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/royalrumble/history/198811412/results/|title=Royal Rumble 1996 official results|publisher=WWE|accessdate=July 2, 2008}}</ref> Ramon was originally scheduled to face Goldust in a rematch for the title at [[WrestleMania XII]] in a Miami Street Fight, but Hall was suspended for six weeks by the WWF due to his drug use.<ref name=\"1996bio\"/> He returned to WWF television at April's [[In Your House 7: Good Friends, Better Enemies|In Your House 7]], where he lost to [[Big Van Vader|Vader]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.softwolves.pp.se/wrestling/wwf/1996#iyh7|title=In Your House 7 results|publisher=American Wrestling Trivia|accessdate=July 2, 2008}}</ref>\n\nHe became associated with the backstage group known as [[The Kliq]] (also consisting of [[Kevin Nash]] (Diesel), Paul Levesque ([[Triple H|Hunter Hearst Helmsley]]), [[Shawn Michaels]], and [[Sean Waltman]] (The 1\u20132\u20133 Kid)).<ref name=\"1996bio\">{{cite web|url=http://www.accelerator3359.com/Wrestling/bios/hall.html#96|title=Scott Hall's WWF Career (1996)|work=Accelerator's Wrestling Rollercoaster|accessdate=June 28, 2008}}</ref> Hall was involved in an incident dubbed the [[The Kliq#The MSG \"Curtain Call\"|\"Curtain Call\"]] at a [[Madison Square Garden|MSG]] show. Because Hall and fellow Kliq member Kevin Nash were departing for WCW, the pair (along with Michaels and Levesque) broke [[kayfabe]] by celebrating and embracing in the ring together, though the characters they portrayed were supposed to be enemies. According to Hall, he went to WCW not for the money, but because they offered him days off.<ref>{{cite DVD|title=WWE Monday Night War S01 E06:The Hart of War|publisher=WWE}}</ref>\n\n=== Return to WCW===\n==== New World Order (1996\u20131998) ====\n{{main|The Outsiders (professional wrestling)|l1=The Outsiders|New World Order (professional wrestling)|l2=New World Order (nWo)}}\nHall returned to WCW for a second time after leaving the WWF with an unannounced [[Promos (professional wrestling)|promo]] on May 27, 1996, in which he appeared from the crowd in street clothes and claimed to be \"an outsider.\"<ref name=\"wcw96bio\">{{cite web|url=http://www.accelerator3359.com/Wrestling/bios/hall.html#wcw2|title=Scott Hall's WCW Career (1996)|work=Accelerator's Wrestling Rollercoaster|accessdate=July 2, 2008}}</ref> On June 10, he was joined by Kevin Nash. They stated they were undertaking a hostile takeover of WCW, then slammed interviewer [[Eric Bischoff]] through the commentator's table.<ref name=\"wcw96bio\"/> The angle paralleled the [[Monday Night Wars|real-life competition]] between WCW and the WWF.<ref name=\"wcw96bio\"/> At [[Bash at the Beach (1996)|Bash at the Beach]], Nash and Hall (now known as The Outsiders)<ref name=\"outsiders\">{{cite web|url=http://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/profiles/o/outsiders.html|title=Outsiders Profile|publisher=Online World of Wrestling|accessdate=July 2, 2008}}</ref> challenged [[Sting (wrestler)|Sting]], [[Lex Luger]], and [[Randy Savage]] to a six-man tag team match, saying they had a mystery partner. That partner turned out to be Hulk Hogan, and the three formed the [[New World Order (professional wrestling)|New World Order (nWo)]].<ref name=\"nwo\">{{cite web|url=http://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/profiles/n/nwo-original.html|title=New World Order (nWo) Profile|publisher=Online World of Wrestling|accessdate=July 2, 2008}}</ref> The [[Smark|stable]] stormed WCW, recruiting such stars as [[Sean Waltman|Syxx]] and [[Big Show|The Giant]].<ref name=\"nwo\"/>\n\nThe Outsiders closed out 1996 with a victory over Sting and Lex Luger at [[Hog Wild 1996|Hog Wild]], and a [[WarGames match]] win at [[Fall Brawl 1996|Fall Brawl]].<ref name=\"wcw96bio\"/> They defeated [[Harlem Heat]] at [[Halloween Havoc 1996|Halloween Havoc]] for their first [[WCW World Tag Team Championship]].<ref name=\"wcwtag\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wrestling-titles.com/wcw/wcw-t.html|title=WCW World Tag Team Title history|publisher=Wrestling-titles.com|accessdate=March 5, 2009}}</ref> They successfully defended the title against [[The Nasty Boys]] and The [[Faces of Fear]] in a three-way match at [[World War 3 (1996)|World War 3]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.prowrestlinghistory.com/supercards/usa/wcw/ww3.html#96|title=World War 3 1996 results|work=Wrestling Supercards and Tournaments|accessdate=July 22, 2008}}</ref> and then again defeated The Faces of Fear at [[Starrcade (1996)|Starrcade]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.prowrestlinghistory.com/supercards/usa/wcw/starrcad.html#96|title=Starrcade 1996 results|work=Wrestling Supercards and Tournaments|accessdate=July 22, 2008}}</ref> They lost the title to The Steiner Brothers at Souled Out, but two days later Eric Bischoff returned the title due to the fact that the referee was not the official referee for the match. The Outsiders held the World Tag Team Championship from February 24, 1997 to October 13, 1997, often facing [[The Steiner Brothers]], Lex Luger and The Giant, and combinations of [[Four Horsemen (professional wrestling)|The Four Horsemen]]. In May 1997, Hall and Nash teamed with [[Masahiro Chono]] to defeat the Steiner Brothers and [[Keiji Mutoh]] at [[New Japan Pro-Wrestling]] (NJPW)'s Strong Style Evolution in the [[Osaka Dome]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.prowrestlinghistory.com/supercards/japan/newjapan/dome.html#osaka97|title=Other NJPW Dome Shows|publisher=Pro Wrestling History|accessdate=September 4, 2019}}</ref>\n\nSince Eric Bischoff (the Executive Vice President of WCW) was a member of the nWo, he used his power to return the title to The Outsiders on a technicality whenever they lost it.<ref name=\"wcw96bio\"/> The Outsiders would also use the [[The Fabulous Freebirds|Freebird Rule]] to defend their title. With Nash and Syxx out with injuries, Hall mostly wrestled singles matches in the last quarter of 1997, and in one of them he submitted to Lex Luger in a grudge match at [[Halloween Havoc 1997|Halloween Havoc]], with [[Larry Zbyszko]] as the guest referee.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.prowrestlinghistory.com/supercards/usa/wcw/havoc.html#97|title=Halloween Havoc 1997 results|work=Wrestling Supercards and Tournaments|accessdate=July 22, 2008}}</ref> Hall won the [[Battle royal (professional wrestling)#World War 3|60-man battle royal]] at [[World War 3 (1997)|World War 3]] in November 1997 to earn a shot at the [[WCW World Heavyweight Championship]].<ref name=\"1997worldwar3\">{{cite web|url=http://www.prowrestlinghistory.com/supercards/usa/wcw/ww3.html#97|title=World War 3 1997 results|work=Wrestling Supercards and Tournaments|accessdate=June 18, 2008}}</ref>\n\nOn the January 12, 1998 episode of ''[[WCW Monday Nitro|Nitro]]'', The Outsiders defeated The Steiner Brothers to win the WCW World Tag Team Championship for a fourth time.<ref name=\"wcwtag\"/> Hall wrestled Larry Zbyszko at [[Souled Out 1998|Souled Out]] and lost by disqualification.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.prowrestlinghistory.com/supercards/usa/wcw/nwoppv.html#98|title=Souled Out 1998 results|work=Wrestling Supercards and Tournaments|accessdate=July 22, 2008}}</ref> The Outsiders lost the title back to The Steiner Brothers on the February 9 episode of ''Nitro''.<ref name=\"1998bio\">{{cite web|url=http://www.accelerator3359.com/Wrestling/bios/hall.html#98|title=Scott Hall's WCW Career (1998)|work=Accelerator's Wrestling Rollercoaster|accessdate=July 22, 2008}}</ref> At [[SuperBrawl VIII]], The Outsiders won the WCW World Tag Team Championship for a fifth time, again by defeating The Steiner Brothers.<ref name=\"wcwtag\"/> At [[Uncensored (1998)|Uncensored]], Hall got his WCW World Heavyweight Championship shot against Sting, losing the match despite interference on his behalf from [[Dusty Rhodes (wrestler)|Dusty Rhodes]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.prowrestlinghistory.com/supercards/usa/wcw/uncensor.html#98|title=Uncensored 1998 results|work=Wrestling Supercards and Tournaments|accessdate=July 22, 2008}}</ref> Hall was ([[Kayfabe|legitimately]]) taken off TV for a short while and forced by WCW to enter [[Drug rehabilitation|rehab]], after he and Nash showed up to the March 16, 1998 episode of ''Nitro'' heavily intoxicated and under the influence of painkillers.<ref name=\"1998bio\"/><ref>[http://www.ddtdigest.com/updates/1998033m.htm WCW Monday Nitro \u2013 Monday, 03/16/98]. Ddtdigest.com. Retrieved on October 11, 2011.</ref> While Hall was absent, the nWo split into two feuding factions.<ref name=\"1998bio\"/> At [[Slamboree 1998|Slamboree]], Hall returned to team with Kevin Nash, for a tag team title defense against Sting and The Giant. Hall turned on Nash, costing them the title, and switched sides to align himself with Hulk Hogan and his splinter faction, [[New World Order (professional wrestling)#List of incarnations and members|nWo Hollywood]].<ref name=\"1998bio\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/profiles/n/nwo-hollywood.html|title=nWo Hollywood Profile|publisher=Online World of Wrestling|accessdate=July 22, 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.prowrestlinghistory.com/supercards/usa/wcw/slambore.html#98|title=Slamboree 1998 results|work=Wrestling Supercards and Tournaments|accessdate=July 22, 2008}}</ref>\n\nOn the July 6 episode of ''Nitro'', Hall was handpicked by Hogan to wrestle [[WWE United States Championship|United States Heavyweight Champion]] [[Bill Goldberg]].<ref name=\"1998bio\"/> Hall lost the match, giving Goldberg a shot at Hogan's World Heavyweight Championship later that night (which Goldberg won).<ref name=\"1998bio\"/> Hogan publicly blamed Hall for the loss, and Hall was treated as a \"weak link\" by the rest of the nWo, especially [[Scott Steiner]].<ref name=\"1998bio\"/> On July 13, Hogan challenged Hall to a match on ''Nitro'', during which Kevin Nash (leader of the nWo \"Wolfpac\" faction) interfered, but as he was apparently about to [[Powerbomb#Release powerbomb|Jacknife Powerbomb]] Hogan and regain Hall as his friend, Hall viciously attacked him, proving his allegiance to Hogan and nWo Hollywood.<ref name=\"1998bio\"/> In the following weeks, Hall mocked Nash, calling himself \"Medium Sexy (later \"Super Sexy\"), the Nash Killer\".<ref name=\"1998bio\"/> On the July 20 episode of ''Nitro'', Hall (with The Giant) won the WCW World Tag Team Championship for a sixth time,<ref name=\"wcwtag\"/> defeating Sting and Nash after outside interference from Bret Hart (who was feuding with Sting at the time).<ref name=\"1998bio\"/> This reign ended at [[Halloween Havoc 1998|Halloween Havoc]], when Rick Steiner defeated The Giant and Scott Steiner (who replaced Hall) to win the title, even after Rick's partner [[Buff Bagwell]] had turned on him.<ref name=\"1998bio\"/> Hall and Nash faced each other on October 25 at [[Halloween Havoc (1998)|Halloween Havoc]]. After hitting Hall with two Jacknife Powerbombs, Nash left the ring and lost the match by countout, in what was described by the commentators as an act of mercy.<ref name=\"1998bio\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.prowrestlinghistory.com/supercards/usa/wcw/havoc.html#98|title=Halloween Havoc 1998 results|work=Wrestling Supercards and Tournaments|accessdate=July 22, 2008}}</ref>\n\nHall was ejected from nWo Hollywood in late 1998, after Scott Steiner took control of the group in Hogan's absence, and then referred to himself as \"The Lone Wolf\".<ref name=\"1998bio\"/> On November 30, 1998, Hall needed a tag team partner to face Steiner and [[Horace Hogan]]. Initially, Hall said he would do it alone, but Kevin Nash came to the entrance and offered his help. The team (no longer billed as The Outsiders) won the match. At [[Starrcade (1998)|Starrcade]], Hall, disguised as a security guard, used a [[electroshock weapon|stun gun]] on WCW World Heavyweight Champion Goldberg during his title defense against Kevin Nash. Not having seen the interference, Nash powerbombed and covered Goldberg to become the WCW World Heavyweight Champion, and break Goldberg's 173 match winning streak.<ref name=\"1998bio\"/>\n\n==== nWo reunion and championship reigns (1999\u20132000) ====\nHall and Nash were allied again and, in January 1999, the two nWo factions rejoined.<ref name=\"1999bio\">{{cite web|url=http://www.accelerator3359.com/Wrestling/bios/hall.html#99|title=Scott Hall's WCW Career (1999)|work=Accelerator's Wrestling Rollercoaster|accessdate=July 22, 2008}}</ref> Hall feuded with Goldberg and faced him in a [[Ladder match|ladder]] taser match on January 19 at [[Souled Out 1999|Souled Out]]. He lost the match when Goldberg used the taser gun on him.<ref name=\"1999bio\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.prowrestlinghistory.com/supercards/usa/wcw/nwoppv.html#99|title=Souled Out 1999 results|work=Wrestling Supercards and Tournaments|accessdate=July 22, 2008}}</ref>\n\nAt [[SuperBrawl IX]], Hall defeated [[Roddy Piper]] for the [[WWE United States Championship|WCW United States Heavyweight Championship]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/inside/titlehistory/unitedstates/30445411132 |title=Scott Hall's first United States Championship reign |publisher=WWE |accessdate=July 22, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20051129082912/http://www.wwe.com/inside/titlehistory/unitedstates/30445411132 |archivedate=November 29, 2005 }}</ref> Shortly after, he suffered a foot injury which forced him to forfeit the title.<ref name=\"1999bio\"/> Hall was not seen again until October 1999, when he and Kevin Nash began sitting at ringside during WCW television, proclaiming \"the band was getting back together.\"<ref name=\"1999bio\"/>\n\nOn the November 8 episode of ''Nitro'', Hall defeated Goldberg, Bret Hart, and [[Sid Eudy|Sid Vicious]] in a Texas tornado ladder match to regain the United States Heavyweight Championship.<ref name=\"hall2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/inside/titlehistory/unitedstates/304454112121 |title=Scott Hall's second United States Championship reign |publisher=WWE |accessdate=August 26, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20051129194240/http://www.wwe.com/inside/titlehistory/unitedstates/304454112121 |archivedate=November 29, 2005 }}</ref> Two weeks later, at [[Mayhem 1999|Mayhem]], he defeated [[Rick Steiner]] by forfeit to also win the [[WCW World Television Championship]].<ref name=\"tvtitle\"/> He successfully defended both titles against [[Booker T (wrestler)|Booker T]] later that night.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.prowrestlinghistory.com/supercards/usa/wcw/mayhem.html#mayhem|title=Mayhem 1999 results|work=Wrestling Supercards and Tournaments|accessdate=August 26, 2008}}</ref> Eight days later, on ''Nitro'', Hall vacated the Television title by throwing it into a trash can.<ref name=\"1999bio\"/> He was soon stripped of his United States title, after being sidelined with a knee injury.<ref name=\"hall2\"/>\n\nHall and Nash teamed up to defeat Bret Hart and Goldberg on the December 13 episode of ''Nitro'', winning the WCW World Tag Team Championship for the sixth time together.<ref name=\"wcwtag\"/><ref>{{cite web|date=December 13, 1999|url=http://www.ddtdigest.com/updates/1999122m.htm|title=WCW Monday Nitro \u2013 December 13th, 1999|work=DDT Digest|accessdate=August 26, 2008}}</ref> Soon afterwards, Hall was injured again and the tag team title was vacated.<ref name=\"1999bio\"/>\n\nAfter the nWo returned in December 1999, Hall joined Kevin Nash, Bret Hart, Jeff Jarrett, and Scott Steiner in what was coined \"[[New World Order (professional wrestling)#Revival|nWo 2000]].\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/profiles/n/nwo-2000.html|title=nWo 2000 Profile|publisher=Online World of Wrestling|accessdate=August 26, 2008}}</ref> Hall feuded with WCW World Heavyweight Champion Sid Vicious, and nWo teammate Jeff Jarrett, over the world title. Sid pinned Hall in a match also involving Jarrett at [[SuperBrawl 2000|SuperBrawl]] on February 20. This was Scott Hall's last appearance in WCW.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.prowrestlinghistory.com/supercards/usa/wcw/s-brawl.html#X|title=SuperBrawl 2000 results|work=Wrestling Supercards and Tournaments|accessdate=August 26, 2008}}</ref>\n\nOn Kayfabe Commentaries' \"YouShoot\" interview series in 2015, Hall revealed he was having an on-and-off relationship with production assistant Emily Sherman, whose uncle was TNT president Brad Siegel. Hall added that while in Europe, which is believed to be WCW's March 2000 shows in England, a former girlfriend of Hall's that worked at the hotel met with Hall at his room to which Sherman encountered them. As a result, Hall was asked not to go on the plane back home.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://kayfabecommentaries.com/DVD_YS_Hall.html|title=YouShoot with Scott Hall \u2013 2015 (running time 2 hours 25 mins) \u2013 1 hour 15 mark|publisher=kayfabecommentaries.com|accessdate=November 29, 2015}}</ref> Reports indicate that Siegel was made aware of this and as a result, Hall had little chance to go back to WCW.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/Ask_the_Editor_18/article_7118.shtml|title=Inside Story on Goldberg-Jericho problems, who's really tough, Hall-Nash problems \u2013 Feb 11, 2004 \u2013 Sub-title \u2013 From the Ask the Torch Vault \u2013 July 24, 2000|publisher=PWTorch.com|accessdate=November 29, 2015}}</ref>\n\n=== Extreme Championship Wrestling (2000) ===\nAfter departing WCW, Hall wrestled two non-televised matches in [[Extreme Championship Wrestling]] in November 2000, first in a loss to Big Sal on November 10, then in a tag match with [[Jerry Lynn]] against [[Justin Credible]] and [[Rhyno|Rhino]] on November 11 in a successful victory.<ref name=\"indy\">{{cite web|url=http://www.accelerator3359.com/Wrestling/bios/hall.html#01|title=Scott Hall's Independent Career (2000\u20132001)|work=Accelerator's Wrestling Rollercoaster|accessdate=August 26, 2008}}</ref>\n\n===Return to NJPW (2001)===\nIn 2001, Hall returned to NJPW. In March, he become part of [[Team 2000]], usually tagging with [[Masahiro Chono]] and fellow WCW alumni [[Scott Norton]] or [[Jeff Farmer (wrestler)|Super J]], the former nWo Sting.<ref name=\"indy\"/> The highlights of his time in NJPW were defeats: a loss to [[All Japan Pro Wrestling]]'s (AJPW) [[Triple Crown Heavyweight Championship|Triple Crown Heavyweight Champion]] [[Keiji Mutoh]] and a loss to [[Hiroshi Tanahashi]], who was a rookie at the time, trying to break into the heavyweight division.<ref name=\"indy\"/>\n\n=== Return to WWF/E (2002) ===\nOn the January 24, 2002 episode of ''[[WWE SmackDown|SmackDown!]]'', WWF co-owner [[Vince McMahon]] stated that his company had a \"cancer\", and that he would inject the WWF with a \"lethal dose of poison\", so he would no longer have to share ownership of the WWF with Ric Flair. He then revealed the \"poison\" to be the nWo, who would help McMahon destroy his own company, before it could be ruined by anyone else.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/results/smackdown/020124.html|title=SmackDown! \u2013 January 24, 2002|publisher=Online World of Wrestling|accessdate=December 9, 2018}}</ref> Six years after defecting from the promotion, Hall returned to the WWF on February 17 at the [[No Way Out (2002)|No Way Out]] pay-per-view, and was reunited with Kevin Nash and Hollywood Hogan in a [[New World Order (professional wrestling)#World Wrestling Federation/Entertainment (2002)|repackaged nWo]]. Later on in the night, the nWo attacked [[Stone Cold Steve Austin]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/results/wwe/wweppv/nowayout/nowayout02/|title=No Way Out 2002 Results|publisher=Online World of Wrestling|accessdate=December 9, 2018}}</ref> On the March 4 episode of ''Raw'', Hall wrestled his first WWF match since May 1996, defeating [[Spike Dudley]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wrestleview.com/results/raw/63.shtml?_gl=1*dlatoa*_ga*YW1wLUstX2VZbGpKeW1CV19OMEM3bFIxV2NPVGtrUTQtNHJSQjRsb2hIYWx4aUt1VG5MRXNta2dDZE12UU9aTVNwY08.|title=WWF Raw Results \u2013 March 4, 2002|first=Paul|last=Nemer|date=March 4, 2002|accessdate=December 9, 2018|work=WrestleView}}</ref>\n\nAt [[WrestleMania X8]], Hall lost to Austin, his first loss at a WrestleMania. Later in the night, after Hollywood Hogan had lost to the Rock, Hogan proceeded to shake the Rock's hand out of respect, thus turning his back on the nWo. Hall and Nash then attempted to attack Hogan and Rock, but were promptly dispatched by the duo.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wrestleview.com/messages1/1355.shtml|title=Full WWF WrestleMania X8 Results|work=WrestleView|date=March 18, 2002|first=Kevin|last=Romano|accessdate=December 9, 2018}}</ref> Hall and Nash later recruited X-Pac into the nWo on the following episode of ''SmackDown!''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/results/smackdown/020321.html|title=SmackDown! results \u2013 March 21, 2002|accessdate=January 24, 2008|publisher=Online World of Wrestling}}</ref> On the March 25 episode of ''Raw'', Hall was [[WWE Draft|drafted]] to the [[Raw (WWE brand)|Raw brand]] with the rest of the nWo, as a result of the [[2002 WWF draft lottery|WWF draft lottery]].<ref>{{cite web|date=March 25, 2002|url=http://www.pwwew.net/wwfdraft.htm|title=WWF Draft2002|work=pWwew \u2013 Everything Wrestling|accessdate=August 26, 2008}}</ref> Hall faced [[John Layfield|Bradshaw]] in a match at [[Backlash (2002)|Backlash]], which he won with help from X-Pac.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/backlash/history/backlash2002/results/|title=Backlash 2002 official results|publisher=WWE|accessdate=August 26, 2008}}</ref> On the next night on ''Raw'', Hall and X-Pac took on Austin and [[Big Show]]. Late in the match Big Show [[chokeslam]]med Austin and joined the nWo.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wrestleview.com/results/raw/70.shtml?_gl=1*1w5by67*_ga*YW1wLU9rSzVYbXJ6YnFuWGNSVkYwWUtJTTRIZGNHeWlzdUJBODdLZEtZOTBpNUZRekJVRk9QSlZaY3AtVmRhUEVqbUg.|title=Full WWF RAW Results \u2013 April 22, 2002|work=WrestleView|first=Paul|last=Nemer|date=April 22, 2002|accessdate=December 9, 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn May 5, on a flight back from England to the United States, retroactively dubbed \"the plane ride from hell\", Hall became incredibly intoxicated and unresponsive. Hall's last appearance was in a six-man tag match with Big Show and X-Pac against Austin, Bradshaw and Ric Flair on the May 6 episode of ''Raw'', which ended in a [[Professional wrestling#No contest|no contest]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/results/raw/020506.html|title=RAW \u2013 May 6, 2002|publisher=Online World of Wrestling|accessdate=December 9, 2018}}</ref> Hall was released from the promotion the following day due to ongoing issues stemming from his substance abuse.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://slam.canoe.com/SlamWrestlingArchive2001/may12_baines-sun.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170724103546/http://slam.canoe.com/SlamWrestlingArchive2001/may12_baines-sun.html|title=Hall, Henning and F are out|work=Slam! Sports|publisher=[[Canoe.com|Canadian Online Explorer]]|first=Tim|last=Baines|date=May 8, 2002|archivedate=July 24, 2017|accessdate=February 24, 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Total Nonstop Action Wrestling (2002, 2004\u20132005, 2007, 2010) ===\nHall worked for [[Total Nonstop Action Wrestling]] (TNA) briefly in 2002, appearing on their first pay-per-view event. on the July 31 NWATNA PPV, Hall lost to Jeff Jarrett in a [[Professional wrestling match types#Container-based variations|Stretcher match]]. on the September 18 NWATNA PPV, Hall and Syxx-Pac competed in the Tag Team Gauntlet for the Gold Match but did not win. on the September 25 NWATNA PPV, Hall and Syxx-Pac defeated [[Elix Skipper]] and [[Brian Lawler]]. on October 23 NWATNA PPV, Hall defeated [[Jeff Jarrett]]. on October 30 NWATNA PPV, Hall got a shot at the [[NWA World Heavyweight Championship]] but lost to [[Ron Killings]]. Hall would leave NWATNA after his match with Killings.\n\nIn late 2004, Hall returned to TNA, along with Kevin Nash, as TNA prepared for their first monthly pay-per-view, [[Victory Road (2004)|Victory Road]]. Hall joined Nash and Jeff Jarrett in the stable The Kings of Wrestling. on the November 26 episode of Impact, Hall defeated [[A.J. Styles]]. at [[Turning Point (2004 wrestling)|Turning Point]], The Kings of Wrestling lost to [[Randy Savage]], [[Jeff Hardy]], and [[A.J. Styles]]. on the December 24 episode of Impact, Hall interrupted a \"In The Pit with Piper\" and confronted [[H\u00e9ctor Garza]] which led to a match a week later on the December 31 episode of Impact where Hall won the match. Hall lost to Hardy at [[Final Resolution (2005)|Final Resolution]] on January 16, 2005.\n\nOn the November 1, 2007 episode of ''[[TNA Impact!|Impact!]]'', Kevin Nash \"predicted\" Hall would be Sting's mystery partner at [[Genesis (2007)|Genesis]]. The next week, Hall made his return, rebuffing the romantic advances of [[Kurt Angle]]'s wife, [[Karen Jarrett|Karen]], then battling Kurt in his dressing room. He stated he was in TNA solely to confront Nash. Hall asked Nash why he was not there to help him in his troubled past, and Nash responded that it was a result of his own nonstop partying and risk of losing his family. Hall then claimed that all was forgiven and the two embraced in the ring. He also revealed that he was not Sting's mystery partner. on the November 15 episode of ''[[TNA Impact!|Impact!]]'',The reunited Outsiders and [[Samoa Joe]] began a feud with [[The Angle Alliance]]. on the November 29 episode of Impact, Hall and Nash came out to the stage and clapped for Samoa Joe after his match. They were scheduled to compete together at [[Turning Point (2007 wrestling)|Turning Point]], but Hall no-showed.\n\nAt [[Turning Point (2008 wrestling)|Turning Point (2008)]], Hall and the [[Insane Clown Posse]] (ICP) were seen in attendance. This was later revealed to have been scripted to occur, as TNA had asked ICP to attend the event, but were unaware of Hall being their guest.\n\nOn the January 4, 2010 three-hour [[TNA Impact!'s move to Monday nights|Monday night live episode of ''Impact!'']], Hall and [[Sean Waltman]] returned to TNA. That same night, Hulk Hogan made his TNA debut. Hall, Nash and Waltman quickly reformed their alliance, but Hogan kept himself out of the group, claiming \"times have changed\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/TV_Reports_9/article_37861.shtml|title=KELLER'S TNA IMPACT LIVE REPORT 1/4: Jeff Hardy, NWO reunion, Hulk Hogan, TNA Knockout Title match, more surprises \u2013 ongoing coverage|last=Keller|first=Wade|date=January 4, 2010|work=PWTorch|accessdate=January 5, 2010}}</ref> The following week, the revived alliance was named \"[[The Band (professional wrestling)|The Band]]\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/TV_Reports_9/article_38126.shtml|title=WILKENFELD'S TNA IMPACT REPORT 1/14: Ongoing \"virtual time\" coverage of Spike TV broadcast|last=Wilkenfeld|first=Daniel|date=January 14, 2010|accessdate=January 17, 2010|work=PWTorch}}</ref>\n\nHall was scheduled to team with Nash at [[Genesis (2010)|Genesis]] in a match against [[Beer Money, Inc.]], but was replaced by Waltman (as Syxx-Pac). In the end, Hall inadvertently cost his stablemates the match.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/PPV_Reports_5/article_38198.shtml|title=CALDWELL'S TNA GENESIS PPV REPORT 1/17: Ongoing \"virtual time\" coverage of A.J. Styles vs. Kurt Angle, Hulk Hogan's TNA PPV debut|last=Caldwell|first=James|date=January 17, 2010|work=PWTorch|accessdate=January 18, 2010}}</ref> On the next episode of ''Impact!'', Hogan, displeased with the actions of The Band, had security remove Hall and Waltman from the arena, since they were not under contract with TNA.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/TV_Reports_9/article_38325.shtml|title=WILKENFELD'S TNA IMPACT REPORT 1/21: Ongoing \"virtual time\" coverage of Spike TV broadcast|last=Wilkenfeld|first=Daniel|date=January 21, 2010|accessdate=January 29, 2010|work=PWTorch}}</ref> Despite this, Hall and Syxx-Pac continued returning to ''Impact!'' to assault various wrestlers. On the February 4 episode, they turned on Nash and beat him down.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/TV_Reports_9/article_38756.shtml|title=WILKENFELD'S TNA IMPACT REPORT 2/4: Ongoing \"virtual time\" coverage of Spike TV broadcast|date=February 4, 2010|accessdate=February 5, 2010|last=Wilkenfeld|first=Daniel|publisher=PWTorch}}</ref> on the February 11 episode of ''Impact!'' Hall and Waltman attacked Kurt Angle until Hulk Hogan made the save. on the February 18 episode of ''Impact!'' Hall and Waltman had a brawl with Kevin Nash and Eric Young. on the February 25 episode of ''Impact!'' Hall and Waltman had a brawl with Kevin Nash and Eric Young in the parking lot. on the March 15 episode of ''Impact!'' Hall defeated Nash in a 5-Min $25,000 challenge after interference from Waltman. At [[Destination X (2010)|Destination X]], Hall and Syxx-Pac faced Nash and [[Eric Young (wrestler)|Eric Young]] in a tag team match, with The Band's TNA future on the line. In the end, Nash turned on Young and helped The Band win, earning them contracts with TNA.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/PPV_Reports_5/article_40000.shtml|title=CALDWELL'S TNA DESTINATION X PPV REPORT 3/21: Ongoing \"virtual time\" coverage of A.J. Styles vs. Abyss, Ultimate X, Anderson vs. Angle|last=Caldwell|first=James|date= March 21, 2010|work=PWTorch|accessdate=March 22, 2010}}</ref>\n\nOn the March 29 episode of ''Impact!'', The Band lost a six-man tag team steel cage match to Eric Young, [[Rob Van Dam]] and Jeff Hardy.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://wrestleview.com/viewnews.php?id=1269919705|title=Impact Results \u2013 3/29/10|last=Martin|first=Adam|date= March 29, 2010|work=WrestleView|accessdate=March 30, 2010}}</ref> on the April 5 episode of ''Impact!'', The Band interfered in a match and attacked both Team 3D and [[The Motor City Machine Guns]]. on the April 12 episode of ''Impact!'', The Band (Hall, Nash, Waltman) defeated Team 3-D and [[Jesse Neal]] in a Street Fight. At [[Lockdown (2010)|Lockdown]], Hall and Nash lost to [[Dudley Boyz|Team 3D]] in a \"St. Louis Street Fight\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/PPV_Reports_5/article_40725.shtml|title=Caldwell's TNA Lockdown Results 4/18: Ongoing \"virtual time\" coverage of PPV \u2013 Styles vs. The Pope, Team Hogan vs. Team Flair, Angle vs. Anderson|first=James|last=Caldwell|date=April 18, 2010|accessdate=April 18, 2010|publisher=Pro Wrestling Torch}}</ref> On the May 3 ''Impact!'', Eric Young turned on Team 3D and joined The Band.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/wwerawreport/article_41070.shtml|title=TNA Impact Results 5/3: Keller's ongoing \"virtual time\" coverage of live show from Orlando|first=Wade|last=Keller|date=May 3, 2010|accessdate=May 4, 2010|publisher=Pro Wrestling Torch}}</ref> On May 4, at the taping of the May 13 episode of ''Impact!'', Hall teamed with Nash, cashed in his \"[[Professional wrestling match types#Feast or Fired|Feast or Fired]]\" contract and defeated [[Matt Morgan (wrestler)|Matt Morgan]] to win the [[TNA World Tag Team Championship]].<ref name=Impact05132010>{{cite web|url=http://wrestleview.com/viewnews.php?id=1273024520|title=SPOILERS: TNA Impact for next Thursday|last=Gerweck|first=Steve|date= May 4, 2010|work=WrestleView|accessdate=May 5, 2010}}</ref> Nash later declared Young one third of the champions, citing the \"Freebird Rule\".<ref name=Sacrifice2010>{{cite web|url=http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/tnappvs/article_41360.shtml|title=Caldwell's TNA Sacrifice results 5/16: Ongoing \"virtual time\" coverage of PPV \u2013 RVD vs. Styles, Jeff Hardy vs. Mr. Anderson|date=May 16, 2010|accessdate=May 16, 2010|last=Caldwell|first=James|publisher=Pro Wrestling Torch}}</ref><ref name=Impact061010>{{cite web|url=http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/tnaimpact/article_41877.shtml|title=Wilkenfeld's TNA Impact report 6/10: Ongoing \"virtual time\" coverage of Spike TV broadcast|last=Wilkenfeld|first=Daniel|date= June 10, 2010|work=Pro Wrestling Torch|accessdate=June 11, 2010}}</ref> At [[Sacrifice (2010)]], Hall and Nash defeated [[Ink Inc.]] ([[Jesse Neal]] and [[Shannon Moore]]) to retain the titles. on the June 10 episode of ''Impact!'', the Band defeated Matt Morgan (by himself) to retain their titles and this was Hall's final appearance in TNA.\n\nOn the June 14 ''Impact!'' taping, The Band was stripped of the Tag Team Championship, due to Hall's real-life legal problems.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://wrestleview.com/viewnews.php?id=1276582066|title=Spoilers: TNA Impact TV tapings for June 17|last=Martin|first=Adam|date=June 15, 2010|work=WrestleView|accessdate=June 15, 2010}}</ref> The following day, it was announced Hall had been released from TNA after 8 years of working part-time for the company.<ref name=Release061510>{{cite web|url=http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/TNA_News_1/article_41973.shtml|title=TNA News: Scott Hall reportedly fired by TNA; SPOILERS on TNA tag title situation|last=Caldwell|first=James|date= June 15, 2010|work=Pro Wrestling Torch|accessdate=June 15, 2010}}</ref>\n\n=== Return to WWC (2007) ===\nOn July 13, Hall made his return to wrestling for the [[World Wrestling Council]] (WWC) as Razor Ramon (though wearing [[New World Order (professional wrestling)|WolfPac]] themed attire). He wrestled the main event of a [[WWC Anniversary#2007|WWC Anniversary]] tour show at the [[Jos\u00e9 Miguel Agrelot Coliseum]] in San Juan, against [[Carly Col\u00f3n|Carlito]]. He lost after [[Germ\u00e1n Figueroa|Apollo]] interfered on Carlito's behalf.\n\nThe next night, Hall won his second World Championship, the [[WWC Universal Heavyweight Championship]], by defeating Carlito and champion Apollo in a Three-Way Dance main event.<ref name=Uni>{{cite web|url=http://www.wrestling-titles.com/us/pr/wwc/wwc-h.html|title=WWC Universal Heavyweight Title history|publisher=Wrestling-titles.com|accessdate=March 5, 2009}}</ref> On August 4 and September 23, Hall successfully defended the title against [[Eddie Col\u00f3n]]. On October 27, managed by Rico Casanova, he retained the title at WWC's ''Halloween Wrestling Xtravaganza'', defeating [[Orlando Col\u00f3n|Orlando \"Fireblaze\" Colon]].\n\n=== Juggalo Championship Wrestling (2007\u20132009) ===\n{{main|Juggalo World Order}}\nHall made his [[Juggalo Championship Wrestling]] (JCW) debut on August 12, 2007, at ''[[Bloodymania (2007)|Bloodymania]]'', losing to [[JCW Heavyweight Championship|JCW Heavyweight Champion]] [[Steve Robinson (wrestler)|Corporal Robinson]].<ref name=\"JCW SLAM TV, Volume 2\">{{cite AV media|date=October 30, 2007|title=JCW SLAM TV, Volume 2|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt1194584/|medium=DVD|publisher=Psychopathic Video|location=Royal Oak, Michigan|isbn=|accessdate=June 6, 2008}}</ref> In this match, Hall took his first ever [[Bump (professional wrestling)|bump]] on [[thumbtacks]].\n\nOn October 6, 2007, at ''Evansville Invasion'', Corporal Robinson, Hall, and [[Violent J]] formed the Juggalo World Order (JWO) stable.<ref name=\"JCW Slam TV - Hallowicked\">{{cite episode|title=Slam TV: Hallowicked 2007!|url=http://video.google.com/videoplay?docid=-3177937582334783638&hl=en|series=SlamTV!|credits=Creator and Producer: [[Insane Clown Posse]]|location=Detroit, Michigan|airdate=November 17, 2007}}</ref> At the 2007 ''Hallowicked After Party'', on October 31, [[Shaggy 2 Dope]] was introduced as a member of the group. After the main event, [[special guest referee]] [[Kazushige Nosawa|Nosawa]] ripped off his referee shirt to reveal that he, too, was a member of the JWO.<ref name=\"JCW Slam TV - Hallowicked\"/> At ''[[Bloodymania II]]'', Hall teamed with Kevin Nash, who proclaimed himself a member of the group. At the 2008 ''Hallowicked After Party'', the JWO inducted its newest member, [[2 Tuff Tony]].\n\nOn November 9, the JWO \"invaded\" Total Nonstop Action Wrestling's [[Turning Point (2008 wrestling)|Turning Point]] PPV, by purchasing front row tickets to the event. They promote their faction by flashing their JWO jerseys, before being removed from the building.<ref name=\"PWTorch November 9\">{{cite web|url=http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/TNA_News_1/article_27798.shtml|last=Caldwell|first=James|title=Scott Hall appears on camera with ICP at tonight's TNA PPV|accessdate=November 10, 2008|publisher=ProWrestlingTorch|date=November 9, 2008}}</ref><ref name=\"The Main Event November 11\">{{cite episode|title=The Main Event |url=http://wfuckoffradio.com/wfko.php/shows/15 |series=JCW Television |credits=Presenters: Violent J, 2 Tuff Tony, and Corporal Robinson |station=WFKO |airdate=November 11, 2008 |minutes=48:18 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100328093423/http://www.wfuckoffradio.com/wfko.php/shows/15 |archivedate=March 28, 2010 }}</ref> The group expressed interest in \"invading\" WWE's 2009 [[Royal Rumble (2009)|Royal Rumble]], but were unable, due to filming commitments for [[Big Money Rustlas]] in Los Angeles.<ref name=\"The Main Event November 18\">{{cite episode|series=JCW Television |title=The Main Event |url=http://wfuckoffradio.com/wfko.php/shows/15 |credits=Presenters: Violent J, 2 Tuff Tony, and Corporal Robinson |station=WFKO |airdate=November 18, 2008 |minutes=1:40:00 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100328093423/http://www.wfuckoffradio.com/wfko.php/shows/15 |archivedate=March 28, 2010 }}</ref> They have also shown interest in \"invading\" [[Ring of Honor]] and [[Ultimate Fighting Championship]].<ref name=\"The Main Event November 4\">{{cite episode|title=The Main Event |url=http://wfuckoffradio.com/wfko.php/shows/15 |series=JCW Television |credits=Presenters: Violent J, 2 Tuff Tony, and Corporal Robinson |station=WFKO |airdate=November 4, 2008 |minutes=1:12:04 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100328093423/http://www.wfuckoffradio.com/wfko.php/shows/15 |archivedate=March 28, 2010 }}</ref>\n\n=== Independent circuit (2010\u2013present) ===\nOn May 3, 2010, Hall appeared in Continental Championship Wrestling. He and Syxx-Pac escorted [[Richard Young (wrestler)|Ricky Ortiz]] to the ring for his match with Navy Seal (which Ortiz won). On January 14, 2011, Hall managed Ortiz at a Vintage Pro Wrestling show with Ortiz, Hall made an impact costing Kennedy Kendrick the match but when Ortiz continued beating on Kendrick it was reversed.\n\nOn January 8, 2011, Hall appeared at I Believe in Wrestling in Orlando, talking about his health before bringing out Ortiz for his match with \"Hotshot\" Mike Reed. Hall along with Nash and Waltman made an appearance at the 2011 Gathering of the Juggalos. On July 14, 2012, Hall appeared at Belleview Pro Wrestling, accompanying his son, Cody, to the ring for his match against Josh Hess.\n\nOn May 13, 2015, [[Global Force Wrestling (2014\u20132017)|Global Force Wrestling]] (GFW) announced Hall as part of their roster.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.globalforcewrestling.com/roster/|title=Global Force Wrestling Roster|date=May 15, 2015|accessdate=May 15, 2015|work=Global Force Wrestling}}</ref> However, on May 18, 2015, Hall was released from his contract with GFW.\n\nOn January 30, 2016, Hall took part of [[World Association of Wrestling]] television tapings, which took place in the Epic Studios at Norwich, England. It was aired on [[Mustard TV]] on September 10, 2016.<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.mustardtv.co.uk/episode/waw-2/ |title = About Mustard TV}}</ref>\n\n=== Second return to WWE (2014\u2013present) ===\nOn March 24, 2014, Razor Ramon was announced as the seventh and final inductee into that year's class of the [[WWE Hall of Fame]]. He was inducted in [[New Orleans]] on April 5, the night before [[WrestleMania XXX]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/videos/2014-wwe-hall-of-fame-inductee-razor-ramon-raw-march-24-2014-26214743|title=2014 WWE Hall of Fame Inductee: Razor Ramon: Raw, March 24, 2014|work=WWE}}</ref> [[Shawn Michaels]], [[Triple H]], [[Sean Waltman|X-Pac]] and [[Kevin Nash]] joined Hall onstage after his speech, reuniting [[The Kliq]]. WWE promotional material for the event referred to him solely as Razor Ramon, without footage or mention of his work under his real name. At WrestleMania XXX, Hall, as Razor Ramon, appeared onstage with the other Hall of Fame inductees. Hall appeared on the August 11, 2014 episode of ''Raw'' for the first time since 2002 to reunite the nWo with Nash and [[Hulk Hogan]] to celebrate Hogan's birthday.\n\n{{quote|Hard work pays off. Dreams come true. Bad times don't last, but bad guys do.|author=excerpt from Hall's [[WWE Hall of Fame]] induction speech, April 2014}}\n\n[[File:NWo WM31.jpg|thumb|The three original members of [[New World Order (professional wrestling)|the nWo]] making their way to the ring at [[WrestleMania 31]] in 2015]]\nOn the January 19, 2015 episode of ''Raw'', Hall appeared with X-Pac and Nash to reunite the nWo, and along with [[The Acolytes Protection Agency|the APA]] and [[The New Age Outlaws]] they beat down [[The Ascension (professional wrestling)|The Ascension]], who had been insulting legends from past weeks. At [[WrestleMania 31]], Hall, along with Nash and Hogan, reunited as the nWo to help [[Sting (wrestler)|Sting]] in his match against Triple H, who had [[D-Generation X]] helping on his behalf.\n\nIn 2016, Razor Ramon was backstage at [[WrestleMania 32]] celebrating with the new [[WWE Intercontinental Championship|Intercontinental Champion]] [[Zack Ryder]]. The following night on ''Raw'', he asked [[The Miz]] to give Ryder a rematch for the Intercontinental Championship.\n\nThe [[WWE]] revealed that Scott Hall would make an appearance on [[Raw 25 Years]] that took place on January 22, 2018. Under the Razor Ramon gimmick, Hall returned in a segment featuring D-Generation X, The Balor Club, and The Revival. Hall also returned to WWE for the RAW Reunion show on July 22, 2019.\n\nOn December 9, 2019, it was announced that Hall would be inducted into the WWE Hall of Fame a second time (this time under his real name instead of as Razor Ramon), as a member of the [[New World Order (professional wrestling)|New World Order]], together with fellow former nWo stablemates [[Hulk Hogan]], [[Kevin Nash]], and [[Sean Waltman]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.espn.com/wwe/story/_/id/28256144/wwe-honor-nwo-hall-fame-induction|title=WWE to honor nWo with Hall of Fame induction|date=December 9, 2019|website=ESPN.com|language=en|access-date=December 9, 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nHall married Dana Lee Burgio in 1990. They divorced in 1998 due to Hall's drug use.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/Other_News_4/article_54405.shtml|title=Hall News: Full recap of ESPN's Scott Hall documentary, quotes from Hall, McMahon, Bischoff, Hogan, Nash, Waltman, indy promoter, more (w/Analysis of the story)|date=October 19, 2011|accessdate=March 30, 2012|last=Caldwell|first=James|work=Pro Wrestling Torch}}</ref> They remarried in 1999 and divorced again in 2001. He has a son ([[Cody Hall|Cody Taylor]], born 1991)<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.rfvideo.com/shootwiththeoutsiders.aspx|title=The Outsiders Shoot Interview|website=RF Video Inc. - Wrestling Merchandise, Wrestling DVDs, Shoot Interviews, ECW}}</ref> and a daughter (Cassidy Lee, born March 27, 1995).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/SCOTTHALLNWO/status/449218833505476608|date=March 27, 2014|accessdate=March 29, 2014|title=19 years ago today was one of the happiest days of my life...Happy Birthday to Cassidy Lee Hall. All my love, Daddy}}</ref> Hall married his second wife Jessica Hart, in 2006. The marriage lasted for only a year when they divorced in 2007.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thesportster.com/wrestling/15-things-you-didnt-know-about-the-relationships-of-the-nwo-wolfpack/amp/|title=15 Things You Didn't Know About The Relationships of the nWo Wolfpack|date=July 12, 2017|website=TheSportster}}</ref>\n\n=== Health ===\nHall's problems with drugs were made public in the late 1990s and were incorporated into a controversial [[World Championship Wrestling|WCW]] storyline. While the storyline was playing out, Hall was legitimately arrested for keying a limousine while intoxicated outside of a night club in [[Orlando, Florida]], causing $2,000 in damages.<ref name=1998limoarrest>{{cite book|last1=Reynolds|first1=R.D.|last2=Alvarez|first2=Bryan|title=The Death of WCW: WrestleCrap and Figure Four Weekly Present . . .|edition=Paperback|date=November 2004|publisher=[[ECW Press]]|isbn=1-55022-661-4|page=155|chapter=1998: Monumentum is Money|quote=Scott Hall was arrested again the following week for allegedly causing $2,000 dollars in damage by keying a limo outside the Diamond Mine strip club during a drunken fit...}}</ref>\n\nAfter his release from TNA in 2010, Hall checked into rehab paid for by [[WWE]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/Other_News_4/article_43306.shtml|title=Other News: Scott Hall health update \u2013 confirmed to be in WWE-sponsored rehab on October 20th 2010 it has confirmed that hall has been released from rehab|date=August 23, 2010|accessdate=August 23, 2010|last=Caldwell|first=James|work=Pro Wrestling Torch}}</ref> Hall checked out of the rehab facility in early October 2010.<ref>[http://www.prowrestling.net/artman/publish/miscnews/article10014447.shtml Prowrestling.net]. Prowrestling.net (October 5, 2010). Retrieved on October 11, 2011.</ref> Weeks after he checked into rehab, Hall had both a [[Defibrillation|defibrillator]] and a [[Artificial cardiac pacemaker|pacemaker]] implanted in his chest.<ref>[http://www.yardbarker.com/wwe/articles/wwe_scott_hall_talks_helping_a_former_wwe_star_going_into_rehab_and_more/4054649 (WWE) Scott Hall Talks Helping a Former WWE Star, Going Into Rehab and More]. Yardbarker.com (January 28, 2011). Retrieved on October 11, 2011.</ref> He was hospitalized twice in 2010 for double pneumonia (affecting both lungs).<ref>[http://rajah.com/base/node/22485 WWE Wrestling News, Rumors, Results & Spoilers|Rajah.com Scott Hall Reportedly Hospitalized Following Drug Overdose]. Rajah.com (April 7, 2011). Retrieved on November 29, 2013.</ref> During this time, Hall started having seizures and was soon diagnosed with [[epilepsy]], resulting in him requiring to take eleven different medications on a daily basis to treat his heart and seizure problems.<ref name=scottesix />\n\nOn April 6, 2011, Hall was reportedly taken to the hospital due to a seizure.<ref name=scottesix /> Hall's [[Public relations|representative]], Geena Anac, said Hall was in the hospital that night to be treated for [[Hypotension|extremely low blood pressure]], and that Hall visits his doctor on a regular basis while recovering from double pneumonia, for [[blood test|blood work]] and [[General medical examination|checkups]].<ref>[http://mi2n.com/press.php3?press_nb=140808 Former WWE Wrestler Scott Hall's Rep Denies Rumors Regarding Drug Over Dose]. Mi2N.com. Retrieved on October 11, 2011.</ref> Three days later, [[TMZ.com|TMZ]] reported Hall had been taken to a hospital, treated for cardiac issues and remained in the hospital for three days. According to medical reports, Hall was being treated after overdosing on both [[opiate]]s and [[benzodiazepine]]s.<ref name=scottesix />\n\nLongtime friend Kevin Nash claims Hall's substance abuse stems from [[posttraumatic stress disorder]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://weblogs.baltimoresun.com/sports/wrestling/blog/2011/04/kevin_nash_scott_hall_is_in_bad_shape.html|title=Kevin Nash: Scott Hall is in bad shape|date=April 21, 2011|last=Eck|first=Kevin|accessdate=April 23, 2011|publisher=Baltimore Sun}}</ref> On October 20, 2011 ESPN's ''[[E:60]]'' featured a documentary detailing Hall's experience with drugs and alcohol. It included interviews with several of Hall's family members (including his ex-wife and his son, Cody), as well as several prominent figures and close friends from the wrestling industry (including Hulk Hogan, Kevin Nash, Sean Waltman, Eric Bischoff, and [[Stephanie McMahon]]).<ref name=scottesix>[http://espn.go.com/espn/e60/story/_/id/7112089/wwe-pro-wrestler-scott-hall-confront-substance-abuse-health-issues-e60 WWE, pro wrestler Scott Hall confront substance abuse, health issues \u2013 E:60 \u2013 ESPN]. Espn.go.com (October 19, 2011). Retrieved on November 29, 2013.</ref>\n\nIn early 2013, former professional wrestler [[Diamond Dallas Page]] invited Hall into his home in order for Hall to stay sober and \"rebuild his life from the ground up... physically, mentally, professionally, and spiritually.\" Page also initiated a fundraising drive, which raised nearly $110,000 ($30,000 over their $80,000 goal) to pay for hip replacement surgery and dental work for Hall.<ref>[http://www.indiegogo.com/projects/we-can-rebuild-him Indiegogo fundraiser for Hall]. Indiegogo.com. Retrieved on November 29, 2013.</ref>\n\n=== Legal issues ===\nIn 1983, Hall was charged with [[second degree murder]] after shooting a man with his own gun (after wrestling it away from him) in an altercation outside of a nightclub in [[Orlando, Florida]]. According to Hall, this was done in self-defense. The charges were dropped due to lack of evidence. In a 2011 interview for ESPN, Hall admitted killing the man and said he is unable to forget the incident.<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=iA9Upk0j2tE 149]. Youtube.com. Retrieved on November 29, 2013.</ref>\n\nIn 1998, Hall was also arrested for groping a 56-year-old woman outside a hotel in [[Baton Rouge, Louisiana]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.postandcourier.com/article/20120415/PC20/120419546&slId=1|title=Scott Hall past the point of no return?|date=April 15, 2012|accessdate=March 17, 2013|last=Mooneyham|first=Mike|work=The Post and Courier}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ddtdigest.com/updates/1998084m.htm|title=WCW Monday Nitro Report|date=August 24, 1998|accessdate=March 17, 2013|work=DDT Digest}}</ref>\n\nOn October 10, 2008, Hall was arrested during a [[Roast (comedy)|roast]] of [[The Iron Sheik]], held at a [[Crowne Plaza]] hotel in New Jersey. A comedian, Jimmy Graham, had joked, \"After The Sheik and [[Hacksaw Jim Duggan]] got caught snorting [[Cocaine|coke]] in the parking lot, his career fell faster than [[Owen Hart]].\" An enraged Hall charged at Graham and knocked down a podium, then grabbed the microphone from him and yelled about how the joke was disrespectful to Hart.<ref>[http://www.prowrestling.com/article/news/10571 Scott Hall arrested for attack] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081012164040/http://www.prowrestling.com/article/news/10571 |date=October 12, 2008 }} Retrieved on October 11, 2008</ref> Graham described the incident on his MySpace page, claiming Hall was drunk at the time of the attack.<ref>[http://www.prowrestling.com/article/news/10578 Graham explains joke] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081013164143/http://www.prowrestling.com/article/news/10578 |date=October 13, 2008 }} Retrieved on October 12, 2008</ref>\n\nHall was arrested on May 14, 2010 and charged with disorderly conduct and resisting a police officer. Police were called to the Hitching Post Bar in [[Chuluota, Florida]] after Hall (who had been \"drinking heavily\", according to the police report), \"became aggressive\". When they arrived, they found Hall yelling and cursing at amateur wrestling personalities and bar staff. Hall was told he was not allowed to return to the establishment. In his police statement, Hall described himself as an unemployed professional wrestler, despite having a job with TNA Wrestling (who would release him a month later).<ref name=Release061510/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.orlandosentinel.com/news/crime/os-scott-hall-bar-incident-20100521,0,2124800.story|title=Scott Hall arrested: Wrestler charged with disorderly intoxication, resisting at Seminole County bar|date=May 22, 2010|accessdate=June 1, 2010|last=Colarossi|first=Anthony|work=Orlando Sentinel}}</ref>\n\nOn April 6, 2012, Hall was arrested in [[Chuluota, Florida]] at around 9:31&nbsp;pm, by deputies of the [[Seminole County, Florida|Seminole County]] Sheriff's office. The arrest was later reported to be for a [[domestic violence|domestic disturbance]] involving his girlfriend, Lisa Howell. Hall allegedly choked Howell while he was drunk. He was taken to a hospital in Seminole County to be medically cleared prior to being taken to a [[drunk tank]].<ref name=\"sescoops arrest\">{{cite web|url=http://www.sescoops.com/scott-hall-arrested-for-domestic-battery-drank-for-days/|title=Scott Hall Arrested For Choking Girlfriend, Drunk \"For Days\"|last=Pena|first=Daniel|date=April 10, 2012|publisher=SEScoops.com|accessdate=April 26, 2012}}</ref> Hall denied the choking allegations.<ref name=\"sescoops deny\">{{cite web|url=http://www.sescoops.com/scott-hall-denies-choking-his-girlfriend-in-drunken-rage/|title=Scott Hall Denies Choking His Girlfriend in Drunken Rage|last=561|first=Mr.|date=April 11, 2012|publisher=SEScoops.com|accessdate=April 26, 2012}}</ref> The prosecutor dropped the charges, citing insufficient evidence.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://slam.canoe.com/Slam/Wrestling/2012/05/04/19716651-wenn-story.html |title= Charges dropped against Scott Hall |website=[[Canoe.ca|Canadian Online Explorer]] |publisher=SLAM! Wrestling |accessdate=April 9, 2016}}</ref>\n\n== Other media ==\nDuring Hall's fourth reign as [[WWE Intercontinental Championship|WWF Intercontinental Champion]], he appeared [[Kayfabe|in character]] as Razor Ramon on ''[[The Jerry Springer Show]]''. As part of his appearance, Hall handed the Intercontinental Championship belt, T-shirts, chain necklaces, and tickets to [[WrestleMania XII]] to two preteens that had gotten ceremonially\u2014but not legally\u2014married on an episode of the show two years prior. One of the preteens had [[HIV/AIDS|AIDS]], while the other was a wrestling fan who liked Ramon.<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=7E2MsItKMJ0 Razor Ramon on Jerry Springer]. YouTube (September 28, 2009). Retrieved on November 29, 2013.</ref> However, Hall ultimately did not compete at WrestleMania XII due to his suspension.<ref name=\"1996bio\"/>\n\nOn August 24, 2009, Hall began hosting a show on [[YouTube]] called ''Last Call with Scott Hall''. Guests have included [[Sid Eudy|Sid Vicious]], [[Kevin Nash]], [[Richard Young (wrestler)|Ricky Ortiz]], [[Larry Zbyszko]], and [[Sean Waltman]].<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/user/scotthalltv Scott Hall TV]. YouTube. Retrieved on November 29, 2013.</ref>\n\nOn August 20, 2013, Hall appeared on [[HBO]]'s ''[[Real Sports with Bryant Gumbel]]'', along with [[Diamond Dallas Page]] and [[Jake Roberts]] to talk about how he and Roberts have been recuperating since moving in with Page.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.caulifloweralleyclub.org/2013/09/27/hbo-real-sports-presents-dallas-page-scott-hall-and-jake-roberts-segment/|title=HBO \"Real Sports\" presents: Dallas Page, Scott Hall, and Jake Roberts segment|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151019050151/http://www.caulifloweralleyclub.org/2013/09/27/hbo-real-sports-presents-dallas-page-scott-hall-and-jake-roberts-segment/|archivedate=October 19, 2015}}</ref>\n\nRamon has appeared in the video games ''[[WWF Raw (1994 video game)|WWF Raw]]'', ''[[WWF Royal Rumble (1993 video games)|WWF Royal Rumble]]'', ''[[WWF WrestleMania: The Arcade Game]]'', ''[[WWE WrestleMania X8]]'' (as Scott Hall), ''[[WWE 2K14]]'', ''[[WWE 2K16]]'', ''[[WWE 2K17]]'', ''[[WWE 2K18]]'', ''[[WWE 2K19]]'' and ''[[WWE 2K20]]''. In the fourth-to-latter, Hall's nWo and Outsiders attires are available as [[downloadable content]], and in the third-to-latter, Hall is once again DLC, but only in his Outsiders attire.\n\n===Filmography===\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"float: centre; margin-centre: 0; margin-centre: 1em;\"\n!Year\n!Title\n!Role\n!Notes\n|-\n|1995\n|''[[The Jerry Springer Show]]''\n|Razor Ramon\n|1 episode\n|-\n|2011\n|''E:60''\n|Himself\n|Documentary; 1 episode\n|-\n|2010\n|''[[Big Money Rustlas]]''\n|Sign guy\n|\n|-\n|2013\n|''[[Real Sports with Bryant Gumbel]]''\n|Himself\n|1 episode\n|-\n|2015\n|''[[Larry King Show]]''\n|Himself/Guest\n|1 episode\n|-\n|2016\n|''[[Table for 3]]''\n|Himself\n|1 episode\n|-\n|2019\n|''Traveling the Stars: Action Bronson and Friends Watch Ancient Aliens''\n|Himself\n|1 episode\n|}\n\n== Championships and accomplishments ==\n[[File:Razor Ramon IC Champ.jpg|right|thumb|Hall held the [[WWE Intercontinental Championship|WWF Intercontinental Championship]] four times, a former record for the championship]]\n[[File:Scott Hall Hall of Fame (cropped).jpg|thumb|Hall was inducted into the [[WWE Hall of Fame]] in 2014]]\n* '''[[American Wrestling Association]]'''\n** [[AWA World Tag Team Championship]] ([[List of AWA World Tag Team Champions|1 time]]) \u2013 with [[Curt Hennig]]<ref name=\"awatag\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wrestling-titles.com/awa/awa-t.html|title=AWA World Tag Team Title history|publisher=Wrestling-titles.com|accessdate=March 5, 2009}}</ref>\n* '''[[DDT Pro-Wrestling]]'''\n** [[Ironman Heavymetalweight Championship]] ([[Ironman Heavymetalweight Championship#Title history|1 time]])<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wrestling-titles.com/japan/ddt/ironman-hm.html|title=Ironman Heavymetalweight Title|accessdate=August 12, 2016|publisher=Wrestling-Titles.com}}</ref>\n* '''''[[Pro Wrestling Illustrated]]'''''\n** [[List of Pro Wrestling Illustrated awards#Match of the Year|Match of the Year]] (1994)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.100megsfree4.com/wiawrestling/pages/pwi/pwimoty.htm |accessdate=June 23, 2008 |title=Pro Wrestling Illustrated Award Winners Match of the Year |publisher=Wrestling Information Archive |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080616063308/http://www.100megsfree4.com/wiawrestling/pages/pwi/pwimoty.htm |archivedate=June 16, 2008 }}</ref> {{small|vs. [[Shawn Michaels]] in a [[ladder match]] at [[WrestleMania X]]}}\n** [[List of Pro Wrestling Illustrated awards#Most Improved Wrestler of the Year|Most Improved Wrestler of the Year]] (1992)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.100megsfree4.com/wiawrestling/pages/pwi/pwiimp.htm |accessdate=June 23, 2008 |title=Pro Wrestling Illustrated Award Winners Most Improved Wrestler of the Year |publisher=Wrestling Information Archive |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110921094752/http://www.100megsfree4.com/wiawrestling/pages/pwi/pwiimp.htm |archivedate=September 21, 2011 }}</ref>\n** [[List of Pro Wrestling Illustrated awards#Tag Team of the Year|Tag Team of the Year]] (1997)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.100megsfree4.com/wiawrestling/pages/pwi/pwittoty.htm |accessdate=June 23, 2008 |title=Pro Wrestling Illustrated Award Winners Tag Team of the Year |publisher=Wrestling Information Archive |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110813033722/http://100megsfree4.com/wiawrestling/pages/pwi/pwittoty.htm |archivedate=August 13, 2011 }}</ref> {{small|with [[Kevin Nash]]}}\n** Ranked No. 7 of the top 500 singles wrestlers in the ''[[Pro Wrestling Illustrated#PWI 500|PWI 500]]'' in 1994<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.100megsfree4.com/wiawrestling/pages/pwi/pwi50094.htm |accessdate=July 1, 2008 |title=Pro Wrestling Illustrated Top 500 \u2013 1994 |publisher=Wrestling Information Archive |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110522005445/http://www.100megsfree4.com/wiawrestling/pages/pwi/pwi50094.htm |archivedate=May 22, 2011 }}</ref>\n** Ranked No. 72 of the top 500 singles wrestlers of the ''PWI Years'' in 2003<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.100megsfree4.com/wiawrestling/pages/pwi/pwi500yr.htm|title=Pro Wrestling Illustrated's Top 500 Wrestlers of the PWI Years|accessdate=March 14, 2009|publisher=Wrestling Information Archive|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090227054535/http://www.100megsfree4.com/wiawrestling/pages/pwi/pwi500yr.htm|archivedate=February 27, 2009}}</ref>\n** Ranked No. 40 and No. 98 of the top 100 tag teams of the ''PWI Years'' with Kevin Nash and Curt Hennig, respectively, in 2003<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.100megsfree4.com/wiawrestling/pages/pwi/pwi100tg.htm |accessdate=June 23, 2008 |title=Pro Wrestling Illustrated's Top 100 Tag Teams of the PWI Years |publisher=Wrestling Information Archive |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090325080845/http://www.100megsfree4.com/wiawrestling/pages/pwi/pwi100tg.htm |archivedate=March 25, 2009 }}</ref>\n* '''[[United States Wrestling Association]]'''\n** [[USWA Unified World Heavyweight Championship]] ([[USWA Unified World Heavyweight Championship#Title history|1 time]])<ref name=\"uswa\">[http://www.wrestling-titles.com/us/tn/uswa/uswa-uh.html Unified World Heavyweight Title (USWA)]. Wrestling-titles.com. Retrieved on November 29, 2013.</ref>\n* '''[[World Championship Wrestling]]'''\n** [[WCW World Television Championship]] ([[List of WCW World Television Champions|1 time]])<ref name=\"tvtitle\">[http://www.wrestling-titles.com/wcw/wcw-tv.html NWA/WCW World Television Title]. Wrestling-titles.com. Retrieved on November 29, 2013.</ref>\n** [[WWE United States Championship|WCW United States Heavyweight Championship]] ([[List of WWE United States Champions|2 times]])<ref>[http://www.wwe.com/classics/titlehistory/unitedstates/30445411132 19990221 \u2013 Scott Hall]. WWE.com. Retrieved on November 29, 2013.</ref><ref>[http://www.wwe.com/classics/titlehistory/unitedstates/304454112121 19991108 \u2013 Scott Hall]. WWE.com. Retrieved on November 29, 2013.</ref>\n** [[WCW World Tag Team Championship]] ([[List of WCW World Tag Team Champions|7 times]]) \u2013 with Kevin Nash (6) and [[Big Show|The Giant]] (1)<ref name=\"wcwtag\"/>\n** [[World War 3 (1997)]]<ref name=\"1997worldwar3\"/>\n* '''[[Total Nonstop Action Wrestling]]'''\n** [[TNA World Tag Team Championship]] ([[List of TNA World Tag Team Champions|1 time]]) \u2013 with Kevin Nash and [[Eric Young (wrestler)|Eric Young]]{{Efn|Hall defended the championship with either Nash or Young under the [[Freebird Rule]].}}\n* '''[[World Wrestling Council]]'''\n** [[WWC Caribbean Heavyweight Championship]] ([[WWC Caribbean Heavyweight Championship#Title history|1 time]])<ref name=\"caribbeantitle\">[http://www.wrestling-titles.com/us/pr/wwc/carib-h.html Caribbean Heavyweight Title]. Wrestling-titles.com. Retrieved on November 29, 2013.</ref>\n** [[WWC Universal Heavyweight Championship]] ([[WWC Universal Heavyweight Championship#Title history|1 time]])<ref name=Uni/>\n* '''[[WWE|World Wrestling Federation/WWE]]'''\n** [[WWE Intercontinental Championship|WWF Intercontinental Championship]] ([[List of WWE Intercontinental Champions|4 times]])<ref>[http://www.wwe.com/classics/titlehistory/intercontinental/322472 Intercontinental Championship \u2013 Razor Ramon September 27, 1993 \u2013 April 13, 1994]. WWE.com. Retrieved on November 29, 2013.</ref><ref>[http://www.wwe.com/classics/titlehistory/intercontinental/322480 Intercontinental Championship \u2013 Razor Ramon August 29, 1994 \u2013 January 22, 1995]. WWE.com. Retrieved on November 29, 2013.</ref><ref>[http://www.wwe.com/classics/titlehistory/intercontinental/322492 Intercontinental Championship \u2013 Razor Ramon May 19, 1995 \u2013 May 22, 1995]. WWE.com. Retrieved on November 29, 2013.</ref><ref>[http://www.wwe.com/classics/titlehistory/intercontinental/322508 Intercontinental Championship \u2013 Razor Ramon October 22, 1995 \u2013 January 21, 1996]. WWE.com. Retrieved on November 29, 2013.</ref>\n** [[WWE Hall of Fame]] (2 times)\n***[[WWE Hall of Fame (2014)|Class of 2014]] \u2013 individually<ref name=\"WWE\"/>\n*** [[WWE Hall of Fame (2020)|Class of 2020]] \u2013 as a member of the [[New World Order (professional wrestling)|New World Order]]<ref>{{cite news |last1=Johnson |first1=Mike |title=2020 WWE HALL OF FAME CLASS HEADLINERS ANNOUNCED {{!}} PWInsider.com |url=https://www.pwinsider.com/article/132054/2020-wwe-hall-of-fame-class-headliners-announced.html?p=1 |accessdate=December 10, 2019 |work=www.pwinsider.com |date=December 9, 2019}}</ref>\n** [[Slammy Award]] (2 times)\n*** Most Spectacular Match ([[Slammy Award#1994 Slammy Awards|1994]]) {{small|vs. Shawn Michaels in a ladder match at WrestleMania X}}<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.prowrestlinghistory.com/supercards/usa/wwf/slammy.html#94|title=The Slammy Awards|website=www.prowrestlinghistory.com}}</ref>\n*** Match of the Year ([[1996 Slammy Awards|1996]]) {{small|vs. Shawn Michaels at [[SummerSlam (1995)|SummerSlam]]}}<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.prowrestlinghistory.com/supercards/usa/wwf/slammy.html#96|title=The Slammy Awards|website=www.prowrestlinghistory.com}}</ref>\n* '''''[[Wrestling Observer Newsletter]]'''''\n** [[List of Wrestling Observer Newsletter awards#Match of the Year|Match of the Year]] (1994) {{small|vs. Shawn Michaels in a ladder match at WrestleMania X}}<ref name=\"won\">{{cite journal|last=Meltzer|first=Dave|authorlink=Dave Meltzer|date=January 26, 2011|title=Biggest issue of the year: The 2011 Wrestling Observer Newsletter Awards Issue|periodical=[[Wrestling Observer Newsletter]]|location=Campbell, CA|pages=1\u201340|issn=1083-9593}}</ref>\n** [[List of Wrestling Observer Newsletter awards#Best Gimmick|Best Gimmick]] (1996) {{small|as a member of New World Order}}<ref name=\"won\"/>\n** [[List of Wrestling Observer Newsletter awards#Most Disgusting Promotional Tactic|Most Disgusting Promotional Tactic]] (1998) {{small|WCW exploiting his alcoholism in a gimmick}}<ref name=\"won\"/>\n\n== Notes ==\n{{notelist}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category}}\n* {{WWE superstar|name=Razor Ramon}}\n* {{Professional wrestling profiles}}\n* {{IMDb name}}\n*[http://wrestlingexaminer.com/scott-hall-say-hello-to-the-bad-guy/ Scott Hall Article]\n\n{{Navboxes|\n|list1=\n{{New World Order}}\n{{TNA World Tag Team Championship}}\n{{WCW World Television Championship}}\n{{WWC Universal Heavyweight Championship}}\n{{WWE Intercontinental Championship}}\n{{WWE United States Championship}}\n{{WCW World Tag Team Championship}}\n{{WWE Hall of Fame}}\n}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hall, Scott}}\n[[Category:1958 births]]\n[[Category:American male professional wrestlers]]\n[[Category:Bridgeport Bluefish guest managers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Military brats]]\n[[Category:NWA/WCW World Television Champions]]\n[[Category:NWA/WCW/WWE United States Heavyweight Champions]]\n[[Category:People from St. Mary's County, Maryland]]\n[[Category:Professional wrestlers from Florida]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Seminole County, Florida]]\n[[Category:The Kliq members]]\n[[Category:The New World Order (professional wrestling) members]]\n[[Category:USWA Unified World Heavyweight Champions]]\n[[Category:WWE Hall of Fame inductees]]\n[[Category:WWF/WWE Intercontinental Champions]]\n", "name_user": "Fylindfotberserk", "label": "safe", "comment": "date formats perMOS:DATEFORMATbyscript", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Scott_Hall"}
{"title_page": "Disgusted of Tunbridge Wells", "text_new": "{{Good article}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2017}}\n\nThe phrase '''\"Disgusted of Tunbridge Wells\"''' is a [[placeholder name|generic name]] used in the [[United Kingdom]] for a person, usually with strongly conservative political views, who writes [[Letter to the editor|letters to newspapers]] or the [[BBC]] in a tone of [[moral outrage]]. ''Disgusted'' is the [[pseudonym]] of the supposed letter writer, who is a resident of the stereotypically [[middle class|middle-class]] town of [[Royal Tunbridge Wells]], [[Kent]], in the [[South East England|south-east of England]].<ref name=\"BBC Disgusted\">{{cite news | title=Tunbridge Wells: The spiritual home of Middle England | date=13 April 1999 | publisher=BBC | url =http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/special_report/1999/02/99/e-cyclopedia/318036.stm | work=BBC e-cyclopedia | accessdate=22 August 2008}}</ref> The term may have originated with either the 1944 BBC radio programme ''[[Much-Binding-in-the-Marsh]]'', a regular writer to ''[[The Times]]'' or an editor of the letters page of a local newspaper, the ''Tunbridge Wells Advertiser''.<ref name=\"wallop\">{{cite news|last1=Wallop|first1=Harry|title=I remain, Sir, disgusted after all these years&nbsp;... |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/comment/letters/10539468/I-remain-Sir-disgusted-after-all-these-years....html|accessdate=31 January 2017|work=The Telegraph|date=27 December 2013|language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn later times, the term has continued to be used to describe conservative letter writers who complain to newspapers about a subject that they morally or personally disagree with.<ref>{{cite book | first =Kevin | last =Duncan  | title =So What?: The Definitive Guide to the Only Business Questions that Matter  | publisher = John Wiley & Sons | edition =   | year = 2008 | isbn = 1-84112-814-7 | page = 45}}</ref> It is often used in relation to news stories regarding Royal Tunbridge Wells. Some residents of the town have criticised the term as obsolete, but several continue to embrace it.\n\n==Origins==\n[[File:Tunbridge Wells; the Pantiles from the Chalybeate Springs Wellcome L0005676.jpg|thumb|200px|alt=Pedestrian street with trees and 19th-century houses and shops|Royal Tunbridge Wells]]\nA \"stuffy, reactionary image\"<ref name=\"BBC Disgusted\"/>  was associated with the town of [[Tunbridge Wells]] by the novelist [[E. M. Forster]] in his 1908 book ''[[A Room with a View]]'', in which the character Charlotte Bartlett says, \"I am used to Tunbridge Wells, where we are all hopelessly behind the times\".<ref name=\"BBC Disgusted\"/> Tunbridge Wells was later granted a [[royal charter]] by [[King Edward VII]] in 1909 and renamed \"Royal Tunbridge Wells\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.msn.com/en-gb/travel/news/10-british-locations-fit-for-a-queen/ss-BBwJw3F#image=4 |title=10 British locations fit for a Queen |publisher=MSN |date=6 January 2017 |accessdate=5 February 2017 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170206022326/https://www.msn.com/en-gb/travel/news/10-british-locations-fit-for-a-queen/ss-BBwJw3F#image=4 |archivedate=6 February 2017 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nThe [[BBC radio]] show ''Much-Binding-in-the-Marsh'', first broadcast in 1944, is sometimes stated in newspaper reports to have popularised the term ''Disgusted of Tunbridge Wells'' for correspondence to newspapers.<ref name=\"times-answered\">{{cite news |title=Did 'Disgusted of Tunbridge Wells' ever really write to newspapers? |url=http://find.galegroup.com/ttda/infomark.do?&source=gale&prodId=TTDA&userGroupName=kccl&tabID=T003&docPage=article&searchType=BasicSearchForm&docId=IF502445958&type=multipage&contentSet=LTO&version=1.0 |work=The Times |department=Questions Answered |location=London |page=31 |date=22 July 2002 |access-date=8 October 2017 |url-access=subscription |via=[[The Times#Online presence|''The Times'' Digital Archive]]}}</ref> There were also suggestions that the use of ''Disgusted of Tunbridge Wells'' came from one regular contributor of letters to ''[[The Times]]'' in the early 20th century, who would use a particular style of writing to oppose people and organisations who came to his attention. Despite being described as the \"quintessential Englishman\" because of his writing style and having his letters regularly published, his identity was never known because he would only identify himself as \"Disgusted of Tunbridge Wells\".<ref name=tea>{{cite book | first =Stuart | last =Maconie  | title =Adventures on the High Teas: In Search of Middle England  | publisher = Random House | edition =   | year = 2010 | isbn = 0-09-192651-3 | pages = 63\u201385}}</ref> However, some reports have popularly rumoured that this person was a retired colonel who served in the [[British Indian Army]] during the [[British Raj]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Kimball |first=Roger |url=https://www.newcriterion.com/articles.cfm/Saintly-institutions--Notes-on-a-common-prejudice-1145 |title=Saintly institutions? Notes on a common prejudice by Roger Kimball |publisher=The New Criterion |date= |accessdate=5 February 2017}}</ref> In 2014, the ''[[Kent and Sussex Courier]]'' claimed that the originator of ''Disgusted of Tunbridge Wells'' was the retired British Army colonel George Thomas Howe, who had developed a skill in writing letters about [[apartheid]] during five years in the [[Union of South Africa]].<ref name=kl /> Reportedly, his letters were popular reading and helped to sell newspapers that published them.<ref name=kl>{{cite web |first=Phoebe |last=Alexander |url=https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-36933267.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180529203341/https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-36933267.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=29 May 2018 |title=Meet a genuine Disgusted of Tunbridge Wells |newspaper=Kent and Sussex Courier |url-access=subscription |via=[[HighBeam Research]] |date=4 July 2014 |accessdate=29 May 2018 }}</ref>\n\nAccording to the Royal Tunbridge Wells historian and former newspaper editor Frank Chapman, the phrase has a different origin, starting in the 1950s with the staff of the former ''Tunbridge Wells Advertiser''. During the paper's final months of publication,<ref name=\"wallop\" /> the editor Nigel Chapman, alarmed at a lack of letters from readers, insisted his staff write a few to fill space. One signed his simply \"Disgusted, Tunbridge Wells\",<ref name=\"wallop\" /><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/insideout/southeast/series8/week5.shtml |title=Disgusted of Tunbridge Wells |date=3 October 2005 |work=Inside Out |publisher=[[BBC One]]|accessdate=15 February 2011}}</ref> and this was then adopted in all future staff letters until the newspaper ceased publication in 1954.<ref name=\"wallop\" /> The term ''Disgusted of Tunbridge Wells'' was later used to stereotype Royal Tunbridge Wells as a town of retired [[British Army]] colonels who would write such letters to newspapers.<ref>{{cite news |last=Clark |first=Ross |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/property/new-homes/3304601/Tunbridge-Wells-is-disgusted.html |title=Tunbridge Wells is disgusted |newspaper=The Daily Telegraph |date=17 July 2002 |accessdate=29 May 2018 }}</ref>\n\nExamples of letters of this type sent to the ''Advertiser'' may be found which pre-date these origins, such as:<ref name=\"wallop\" />\n\n{{quote|SIR \u2013 Being present at the unveiling of the plaque on Thursday last week on [[the Pantiles]], I was surprised when the National Anthem was played to see that in a place like Tunbridge Wells, which is noted for its loyalty and calls itself \"Royal\", there should be people who refused to remove their hats. Are such people Communists? If they are, Tunbridge Wells should be no place for such as they. We can do without them.|author=Imperialist|source=Letters to the editor, ''Tunbridge Wells Advertiser'', June 14, 1929 |width=50%}}\n\nLetters written with a tone of incensed moral outrage have become commonly described as \"Disgusted of Tunbridge Wells\" letters, even though the writer may not be from Royal Tunbridge Wells.<ref name=tea /><ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.rugbyworld.com/countries/england-countries/worth-selling-naming-rights-twickenham-55378 |title=Is it worth selling the naming rights to Twickenham? |magazine=Rugby World |date=1 April 2016 |accessdate=5 February 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/lifestyle/janet-street-porter-from-parsons-green-punk-to-disgusted-of-tunbridge-wells-6794787.html |title=Janet Street-Porter: from Parsons Green punk to Disgusted of Tunbridge Wells |newspaper=Evening Standard|date=22 October 2009 |accessdate=14 March 2017}}</ref> For example, the actor [[Michael Caine]] once said: \"I don't want to sound like Disgusted of Tunbridge Wells, but I do think there should be some sort of national service for young men\".<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/film/6529529/Michael-Caine-interview.html |title=Michael Caine interview |newspaper=The Telegraph |date=9 November 2009 |accessdate=14 March 2017}}</ref> People writing them have been claimed by commentators to be readers of the ''[[Daily Mail]]'', despite the original letters not originating in that publication.<ref>{{cite book |first=Elaine |last=Aston |title=Feminist Views on the English Stage: Women Playwrights, 1990\u20132000 |publisher=Cambridge University Press |page=77 |isbn=1-139-44153-1 |date=2003}}</ref>\n\n==Later use==\nThe magazine ''[[Private Eye]]'' made regular use of the ''Disgusted of Tunbridge Wells'' pseudonym to satirise the stereotypical conservative [[Middle England]]er, and it became a [[running joke]] for several years.<ref>{{cite book|title=Tickling the English|first=Dara|last=\u00d3 Briain|authorlink=Dara \u00d3 Briain|p=[https://archive.org/details/isbn_9780141046662/page/188 188]|publisher=Penguin Books|year=2010|isbn=978-0-14-104666-2|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/isbn_9780141046662/page/188}}</ref> In 1978, [[BBC Radio 4]] called its new listener feedback programme ''Disgusted, Tunbridge Wells'', though it was renamed ''[[Feedback (radio series)|Feedback]]'' in 1979.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/magazine-15619543 | work=BBC News | title=Disgust: How did the word change so completely? | date=15 November 2011}}</ref> This was following Radio 4 broadcasting the ''[[Take It From Here]]'' radio series in 1954 where \"Disgusted of Tunbridge Wells\" was prominently featured.<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b0131zxv |title=Take It From Here, From 08/04/1954 |publisher=BBC Radio 4 Extra |date=20 March 1954 |accessdate=13 March 2017}}</ref> In politics, the people behind \"Disgusted of Tunbridge Wells\" letters have strong conservative views and are commonly viewed to support the [[Conservative Party (United Kingdom)|Conservative Party]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/142410039/ |title=Tories Bear Brunt Of Conservative Town's 'Disgust' |work=St. Louis Post-Dispatch |via=Newspapers.com |date=6 May 1995 |accessdate=8 February 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |first=Andrew |last=Rawnsley |url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2006/dec/03/comment.politics3 |title=David Cameron still has a huge mountain to climb |newspaper=The Guardian |date=3 December 2006 |accessdate=14 March 2017}}</ref> However, most [[UK Independence Party]] (UKIP) members in the party's early days were viewed by commentators as being \"'Disgusted of Tunbridge Wells' pensioners\", of whom the UKIP leader [[Nigel Farage]] stated in 2013 \"... the people in it [UKIP] and who voted for it were in the main 'Disgusted of Tunbridge Wells'. I mean, you look down the membership list in 1994, anyone below a half colonel was a nobody...\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/92b415d4-b409-11e2-ace9-00144feabdc0 |title=Nigel Farage strikes right note with disgruntled working class |work=Financial Times |date= |accessdate=8 February 2017}}{{Subscription required|date=February 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |first=Decca |last=Aitkenhead |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2013/jan/07/nigel-farage-party-eccentrics-ukip |title=Nigel Farage: I'd rather have a party of eccentrics than bland, ghastly people |newspaper=The Guardian |date=7 January 2013 |accessdate=3 June 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn 1980, the [[BBC Radio 2]] broadcaster [[Terry Wogan]] chaired an \"It's Your BBC\" meeting at Royal Tunbridge Wells' [[Assembly Hall Theatre, Tunbridge Wells|Assembly Hall Theatre]]. A report in ''The Times'' suggested the BBC had staged the meeting in the town in the hope that \"Disgusted\" would reveal himself.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://find.galegroup.com/ttda/infomark.do?&source=gale&prodId=TTDA&userGroupName=kccl&tabID=T003&docPage=article&searchType=BasicSearchForm&docId=CS270501560&type=multipage&contentSet=LTO&version=1.0|first=Kenneth|last=Gosling|title=BBC's quest for 'Disgusted' of Tunbridge Wells|newspaper=The Times|date=24 May 1980|p=16|accessdate=10 March 2017|url-access=subscription }}</ref>\n\nIn 2006, the author and magistrate [[Connie St Louis]] singled out the \"disgusted of Tunbridge Wells\" stereotype as a powerful British middle-class movement, saying \"they are part of the group with the same concerns, so they have a sense of belonging\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://find.galegroup.com/ttda/infomark.do?&source=gale&prodId=TTDA&userGroupName=kccl&tabID=T003&docPage=article&searchType=BasicSearchForm&docId=IF502799495&type=multipage&contentSet=LTO&version=1.0|first=Lucy|last=Alexander|title=Why Britain has no black middle class|newspaper=The Times|date=9 January 2006|accessdate=10 March 2017|url-access=subscription }}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, [[Nigel Cawthorne]] published ''Outraged of Tunbridge Wells'', a compilation of letters to the ''Tunbridge Wells Advertiser'' that were viewed as being in the style of \"Disgusted of Tunbridge Wells\" from the [[British Library]] archives. Critical review of the book has stated that the \"Disgusted of Tunbridge Wells\" style displayed an art of letter writing that has continued despite other things in the world changing.<ref>{{cite web|first=Joshua |last=Neicho |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/books/reviews/outraged-of-tunbridge-wells-edited-by-nigel-cawthorne-review-8989432.html |title=Outraged of Tunbridge Wells, Edited by Nigel Cawthorne \u2013 Review |work=The Independent |date=8 December 2013 |accessdate=5 February 2017}}</ref>\n\nResidents of Royal Tunbridge Wells have also expressed displeasure in a manner similar to the \"Disgusted of Tunbridge Wells\" stereotype in relation to the [[Waitrose]] supermarket chain refusing to open a store in the town while neighbouring \"downmarket\" towns of [[Tonbridge]] and [[Crowborough]] both did have one.<ref>{{cite web|author=Billy Kenber |url=http://www.thetimes.co.uk/tto/business/industries/retailing/article4050715.ece |title=Tunbridge Wells is disgusted at the lack of Waitrose |work=The Times  |date=2014-04-01 |accessdate=2017-02-17}} {{Subscription required|date=February 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, during the [[United Kingdom referendum on the British membership in the European Union]], ''[[The New York Times]]'' used Royal Tunbridge Wells as its base for reporting on the referendum. The town was chosen because it was seen as the \"quintessentially English town\" due to the ''Disgusted of Tunbridge Wells'' phrase. Although most Americans would not fully understand the reference, the town was nonetheless considered a symbol of middle England.<ref name=tott>{{cite web|author= |url=https://www.timesoftunbridgewells.co.uk/american-referendum-coverage-focuses-on-tunbridge-wells/ |title=American Referendum coverage focuses on Tunbridge Wells |work=Times of Tunbridge Wells |date= |accessdate=5 February 2017}}</ref> The town is a Conservative stronghold<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.itv.com/news/meridian/referendum/?page=15|title=How will Tunbridge Wells vote in EU Referendum?|publisher=itv.com|accessdate=10 March 2017}}</ref> and was the only council area in [[Kent]] to vote by a majority for Remain during [[Brexit]].<ref name=tott/>\n\n==Criticism==\nIn 2009, some residents of Royal Tunbridge Wells called the tag \"inappropriate\" and \"stereotypical\", and asked the town to drop association with it in favour of ''Delighted of Tunbridge Wells''.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.thisiskent.co.uk/news/disgusted-DELIGHTED/article-1351326-detail/article.html |title=We're not disgusted, we're DELIGHTED |date=18 September 2009 |website=This is Kent |accessdate=15 February 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110217100714/http://www.thisiskent.co.uk/news/disgusted-DELIGHTED/article-1351326-detail/article.html |archivedate=17 February 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> However, there was opposition to this campaign by other residents, some of whom wrote to newspapers in the \"Disgusted of Tunbridge Wells\" style arguing they preferred ''Disgusted of Tunbridge Wells''.<ref>{{cite web|last=Gerard |first=Jasper|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/6281016/The-rise-and-fall-of-Tunbridge-Wells.html |title=The rise and fall of Tunbridge Wells |work=The Telegraph |date= |accessdate=5 February 2017}}</ref> Local merchants at the town's information centre pointed out that tourists were buying twice as many goods bearing ''Disgusted of Tunbridge Wells'' than with ''Delighted of Tunbridge Wells''.<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/howaboutthat/6206646/Disgusted-of-Tunbridge-Wells-fight-back.html |title='Disgusted of Tunbridge Wells' fight back |work=The Telegraph |date=19 September 2009 |accessdate=5 February 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Wutb\u00fcrger ==\nThe German term Wutb\u00fcrger (or wutbuerger) first appeared in the German press in 2010 and roughly translates to \"angry or enraged citizen\" (''Wut'' meaning \"rage\" and ''B\u00fcrger'' meaning \u201ccitizen\")<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/Wutb%C3%BCrger|title=Wutb\u00fcrger - Wiktionary|website=en.wiktionary.org|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref>. In particular, the essay \"Der Wutb\u00fcrger\" in [[Der Spiegel]] (11 October 2010) made the term popular. It roughly denotes a \"citizen that protests heavily in public out of disappointment about certain political decisions\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.duden.de/rechtschreibung/Wutbuerger|title=Duden {{!}} Wutb\u00fcrger {{!}} Rechtschreibung, Bedeutung, Definition, Herkunft|website=www.duden.de|language=de|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref> The term Wutb\u00fcrger also became the German [[Word of the year (Germany)|word of the year]] in 2010. Manfred Klenner from the University of Zurich points out that it is fear rather than rage that is the prevalent emotion among Wutb\u00fcrgers on Facebook.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Klenner|first=Manfred|last2=Recupero|first2=Diego Reforgiato|last3=Dragoni|first3=Mauro|last4=Buscaldi|first4=Davide|last5=Mehwish|first5=Alam|last6=Cambria|first6=Erik|date=2018-06-04|title=What Does it Mean to be a Wutb\u00fcrger? A First Exploration|url=http://ceur-ws.org/Vol-2111/|journal=Klenner, Manfred  (2018). What Does it Mean to be a Wutb\u00fcrger? A First Exploration.  In: Proceedings of 4th Workshop on Sentic Computing, Sentiment Analysis, Opinion Mining, and Emotion Detection (EMSASW 2018), Heraklion, 4 June 2018 - 4 June 2018.|location=Heraklion|publisher=s.n.|doi=info:doi/10.5167/uzh-159171}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Edith Clampton]], a pseudonymous comedic letter-writer to the ''Bangkok Post''\n* ''[[Will it play in Peoria?]]''\n* [[Sir Bufton Tufton]], a recurring character in the UK satirical magazine ''Private Eye''\n* ''[[Monty Python's Flying Circus]]'', which featured numerous segments satirizing angry letters to the BBC\n* [[Keith Flett]], a noted writer of letters to British newspapers\n* [[Gammon (insult)]], directed at jingoistic supporters of Brexit\n* [[Down with this sort of thing]]\n* [[Placeholder name]]\n* [[Multiple-use name]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20150418222059/http://disgustedoftunbridgewells.co.uk/about.html Disgusted of Tunbridge Wells] (local website)\n\n{{Royal Tunbridge Wells}}\n\n[[Category:Royal Tunbridge Wells]]\n[[Category:Conservatism in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:English phrases]]\n[[Category:English culture]]\n[[Category:Letter writers]]\n[[Category:Stereotypes of the middle class]]\n[[Category:Class-related slurs]]\n[[Category:Anonymity pseudonyms]]\n", "text_old": "{{Good article}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2017}}\n\nThe phrase '''\"Disgusted of Tunbridge Wells\"''' is a [[placeholder name|generic name]] used in the [[United Kingdom]] for a person, usually with strongly conservative political views, who writes [[Letter to the editor|letters to newspapers]] or the [[BBC]] in a tone of [[moral outrage]]. ''Disgusted'' is the [[pseudonym]] of the supposed letter writer, who is a resident of the stereotypically [[middle class|middle-class]] town of [[Royal Tunbridge Wells]], [[Kent]], in the [[South East England|south-east of England]].<ref name=\"BBC Disgusted\">{{cite news | title=Tunbridge Wells: The spiritual home of Middle England | date=13 April 1999 | publisher=BBC | url =http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/special_report/1999/02/99/e-cyclopedia/318036.stm | work=BBC e-cyclopedia | accessdate=22 August 2008}}</ref> The term may have originated with either the 1944 BBC radio programme ''[[Much-Binding-in-the-Marsh]]'', a regular writer to ''[[The Times]]'' or an editor of the letters page of a local newspaper, the ''Tunbridge Wells Advertiser''.<ref name=\"wallop\">{{cite news|last1=Wallop|first1=Harry|title=I remain, Sir, disgusted after all these years&nbsp;... |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/comment/letters/10539468/I-remain-Sir-disgusted-after-all-these-years....html|accessdate=31 January 2017|work=The Telegraph|date=27 December 2013|language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn later times, the term has continued to be used to describe conservative letter writers who complain to newspapers about a subject that they morally or personally disagree with.<ref>{{cite book | first =Kevin | last =Duncan  | title =So What?: The Definitive Guide to the Only Business Questions that Matter  | publisher = John Wiley & Sons | edition =   | year = 2008 | isbn = 1-84112-814-7 | page = 45}}</ref> It is often used in relation to news stories regarding Royal Tunbridge Wells. Some residents of the town have criticised the term as obsolete, but several continue to embrace it.\n\n==Origins==\n[[File:Tunbridge Wells; the Pantiles from the Chalybeate Springs Wellcome L0005676.jpg|thumb|200px|alt=Pedestrian street with trees and 19th-century houses and shops|Royal Tunbridge Wells]]\nA \"stuffy, reactionary image\"<ref name=\"BBC Disgusted\"/>  was associated with the town of [[Tunbridge Wells]] by the novelist [[E. M. Forster]] in his 1908 book ''[[A Room with a View]]'', in which the character Charlotte Bartlett says, \"I am used to Tunbridge Wells, where we are all hopelessly behind the times\".<ref name=\"BBC Disgusted\"/> Tunbridge Wells was later granted a [[royal charter]] by [[King Edward VII]] in 1909 and renamed \"Royal Tunbridge Wells\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.msn.com/en-gb/travel/news/10-british-locations-fit-for-a-queen/ss-BBwJw3F#image=4 |title=10 British locations fit for a Queen |publisher=MSN |date=6 January 2017 |accessdate=5 February 2017 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170206022326/https://www.msn.com/en-gb/travel/news/10-british-locations-fit-for-a-queen/ss-BBwJw3F#image=4 |archivedate=6 February 2017 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nThe [[BBC radio]] show ''Much-Binding-in-the-Marsh'', first broadcast in 1944, is sometimes stated in newspaper reports to have popularised the term ''Disgusted of Tunbridge Wells'' for correspondence to newspapers.<ref name=\"times-answered\">{{cite news |title=Did 'Disgusted of Tunbridge Wells' ever really write to newspapers? |url=http://find.galegroup.com/ttda/infomark.do?&source=gale&prodId=TTDA&userGroupName=kccl&tabID=T003&docPage=article&searchType=BasicSearchForm&docId=IF502445958&type=multipage&contentSet=LTO&version=1.0 |work=The Times |department=Questions Answered |location=London |page=31 |date=22 July 2002 |access-date=8 October 2017 |url-access=subscription |via=[[The Times#Online presence|''The Times'' Digital Archive]]}}</ref> There were also suggestions that the use of ''Disgusted of Tunbridge Wells'' came from one regular contributor of letters to ''[[The Times]]'' in the early 20th century, who would use a particular style of writing to oppose people and organisations who came to his attention. Despite being described as the \"quintessential Englishman\" because of his writing style and having his letters regularly published, his identity was never known because he would only identify himself as \"Disgusted of Tunbridge Wells\".<ref name=tea>{{cite book | first =Stuart | last =Maconie  | title =Adventures on the High Teas: In Search of Middle England  | publisher = Random House | edition =   | year = 2010 | isbn = 0-09-192651-3 | pages = 63\u201385}}</ref> However, some reports have popularly rumoured that this person was a retired colonel who served in the [[British Indian Army]] during the [[British Raj]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Kimball |first=Roger |url=https://www.newcriterion.com/articles.cfm/Saintly-institutions--Notes-on-a-common-prejudice-1145 |title=Saintly institutions? Notes on a common prejudice by Roger Kimball |publisher=The New Criterion |date= |accessdate=5 February 2017}}</ref> In 2014, the ''[[Kent and Sussex Courier]]'' claimed that the originator of ''Disgusted of Tunbridge Wells'' was the retired British Army colonel George Thomas Howe, who had developed a skill in writing letters about [[apartheid]] during five years in the [[Union of South Africa]].<ref name=kl /> Reportedly, his letters were popular reading and helped to sell newspapers that published them.<ref name=kl>{{cite web |first=Phoebe |last=Alexander |url=https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-36933267.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180529203341/https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-36933267.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=29 May 2018 |title=Meet a genuine Disgusted of Tunbridge Wells |newspaper=Kent and Sussex Courier |url-access=subscription |via=[[HighBeam Research]] |date=4 July 2014 |accessdate=29 May 2018 }}</ref>\n\nAccording to the Royal Tunbridge Wells historian and former newspaper editor Frank Chapman, the phrase has a different origin, starting in the 1950s with the staff of the former ''Tunbridge Wells Advertiser''. During the paper's final months of publication,<ref name=\"wallop\" /> the editor Nigel Chapman, alarmed at a lack of letters from readers, insisted his staff write a few to fill space. One signed his simply \"Disgusted, Tunbridge Wells\",<ref name=\"wallop\" /><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/insideout/southeast/series8/week5.shtml |title=Disgusted of Tunbridge Wells |date=3 October 2005 |work=Inside Out |publisher=[[BBC One]]|accessdate=15 February 2011}}</ref> and this was then adopted in all future staff letters until the newspaper ceased publication in 1954.<ref name=\"wallop\" /> The term ''Disgusted of Tunbridge Wells'' was later used to stereotype Royal Tunbridge Wells as a town of retired [[British Army]] colonels who would write such letters to newspapers.<ref>{{cite news |last=Clark |first=Ross |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/property/new-homes/3304601/Tunbridge-Wells-is-disgusted.html |title=Tunbridge Wells is disgusted |newspaper=The Daily Telegraph |date=17 July 2002 |accessdate=29 May 2018 }}</ref>\n\nExamples of letters of this type sent to the ''Advertiser'' may be found which pre-date these origins, such as:<ref name=\"wallop\" />\n\n{{quote|SIR \u2013 Being present at the unveiling of the plaque on Thursday last week on [[the Pantiles]], I was surprised when the National Anthem was played to see that in a place like Tunbridge Wells, which is noted for its loyalty and calls itself \"Royal\", there should be people who refused to remove their hats. Are such people Communists? If they are, Tunbridge Wells should be no place for such as they. We can do without them.|author=Imperialist|source=Letters to the editor, ''Tunbridge Wells Advertiser'', June 14, 1929 |width=50%}}\n\nLetters written with a tone of incensed moral outrage have become commonly described as \"Disgusted of Tunbridge Wells\" letters, even though the writer may not be from Royal Tunbridge Wells.<ref name=tea /><ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.rugbyworld.com/countries/england-countries/worth-selling-naming-rights-twickenham-55378 |title=Is it worth selling the naming rights to Twickenham? |magazine=Rugby World |date=1 April 2016 |accessdate=5 February 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/lifestyle/janet-street-porter-from-parsons-green-punk-to-disgusted-of-tunbridge-wells-6794787.html |title=Janet Street-Porter: from Parsons Green punk to Disgusted of Tunbridge Wells |newspaper=Evening Standard|date=22 October 2009 |accessdate=14 March 2017}}</ref> For example, the actor [[Michael Caine]] once said: \"I don't want to sound like Disgusted of Tunbridge Wells, but I do think there should be some sort of national service for young men\".<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/film/6529529/Michael-Caine-interview.html |title=Michael Caine interview |newspaper=The Telegraph |date=9 November 2009 |accessdate=14 March 2017}}</ref> People writing them have been claimed by commentators to be readers of the ''[[Daily Mail]]'', despite the original letters not originating in that publication.<ref>{{cite book |first=Elaine |last=Aston |title=Feminist Views on the English Stage: Women Playwrights, 1990\u20132000 |publisher=Cambridge University Press |page=77 |isbn=1-139-44153-1 |date=2003}}</ref>\n\n==Later use==\nThe magazine ''[[Private Eye]]'' made regular use of the ''Disgusted of Tunbridge Wells'' pseudonym to satirise the stereotypical conservative [[Middle England]]er, and it became a [[running joke]] for several years.<ref>{{cite book|title=Tickling the English|first=Dara|last=\u00d3 Briain|authorlink=Dara \u00d3 Briain|p=[https://archive.org/details/isbn_9780141046662/page/188 188]|publisher=Penguin Books|year=2010|isbn=978-0-14-104666-2|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/isbn_9780141046662/page/188}}</ref> In 1978, [[BBC Radio 4]] called its new listener feedback programme ''Disgusted, Tunbridge Wells'', though it was renamed ''[[Feedback (radio series)|Feedback]]'' in 1979.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/magazine-15619543 | work=BBC News | title=Disgust: How did the word change so completely? | date=15 November 2011}}</ref> This was following Radio 4 broadcasting the ''[[Take It From Here]]'' radio series in 1954 where \"Disgusted of Tunbridge Wells\" was prominently featured.<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b0131zxv |title=Take It From Here, From 08/04/1954 |publisher=BBC Radio 4 Extra |date=20 March 1954 |accessdate=13 March 2017}}</ref> In politics, the people behind \"Disgusted of Tunbridge Wells\" letters have strong conservative views and are commonly viewed to support the [[Conservative Party (United Kingdom)|Conservative Party]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/142410039/ |title=Tories Bear Brunt Of Conservative Town's 'Disgust' |work=St. Louis Post-Dispatch |via=Newspapers.com |date=6 May 1995 |accessdate=8 February 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |first=Andrew |last=Rawnsley |url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2006/dec/03/comment.politics3 |title=David Cameron still has a huge mountain to climb |newspaper=The Guardian |date=3 December 2006 |accessdate=14 March 2017}}</ref> However, most [[UK Independence Party]] (UKIP) members in the party's early days were viewed by commentators as being \"'Disgusted of Tunbridge Wells' pensioners\", of which the UKIP leader [[Nigel Farage]] stated in 2013 \"... the people in it [UKIP] and who voted for it were in the main 'Disgusted of Tunbridge Wells'. I mean, you look down the membership list in 1994, anyone below a half colonel was a nobody...\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/92b415d4-b409-11e2-ace9-00144feabdc0 |title=Nigel Farage strikes right note with disgruntled working class |work=Financial Times |date= |accessdate=8 February 2017}}{{Subscription required|date=February 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |first=Decca |last=Aitkenhead |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2013/jan/07/nigel-farage-party-eccentrics-ukip |title=Nigel Farage: I'd rather have a party of eccentrics than bland, ghastly people |newspaper=The Guardian |date=7 January 2013 |accessdate=3 June 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn 1980, the [[BBC Radio 2]] broadcaster [[Terry Wogan]] chaired an \"It's Your BBC\" meeting at Royal Tunbridge Wells' [[Assembly Hall Theatre, Tunbridge Wells|Assembly Hall Theatre]]. A report in ''The Times'' suggested the BBC had staged the meeting in the town in the hope that \"Disgusted\" would reveal himself.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://find.galegroup.com/ttda/infomark.do?&source=gale&prodId=TTDA&userGroupName=kccl&tabID=T003&docPage=article&searchType=BasicSearchForm&docId=CS270501560&type=multipage&contentSet=LTO&version=1.0|first=Kenneth|last=Gosling|title=BBC's quest for 'Disgusted' of Tunbridge Wells|newspaper=The Times|date=24 May 1980|p=16|accessdate=10 March 2017|url-access=subscription }}</ref>\n\nIn 2006, the author and magistrate [[Connie St Louis]] singled out the \"disgusted of Tunbridge Wells\" stereotype as a powerful British middle-class movement, saying \"they are part of the group with the same concerns, so they have a sense of belonging\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://find.galegroup.com/ttda/infomark.do?&source=gale&prodId=TTDA&userGroupName=kccl&tabID=T003&docPage=article&searchType=BasicSearchForm&docId=IF502799495&type=multipage&contentSet=LTO&version=1.0|first=Lucy|last=Alexander|title=Why Britain has no black middle class|newspaper=The Times|date=9 January 2006|accessdate=10 March 2017|url-access=subscription }}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, [[Nigel Cawthorne]] published ''Outraged of Tunbridge Wells'', a compilation of letters to the ''Tunbridge Wells Advertiser'' that were viewed as being in the style of \"Disgusted of Tunbridge Wells\" from the [[British Library]] archives. Critical review of the book has stated that the \"Disgusted of Tunbridge Wells\" style displayed an art of letter writing that has continued despite other things in the world changing.<ref>{{cite web|first=Joshua |last=Neicho |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/books/reviews/outraged-of-tunbridge-wells-edited-by-nigel-cawthorne-review-8989432.html |title=Outraged of Tunbridge Wells, Edited by Nigel Cawthorne \u2013 Review |work=The Independent |date=8 December 2013 |accessdate=5 February 2017}}</ref>\n\nResidents of Royal Tunbridge Wells have also expressed displeasure in a manner similar to the \"Disgusted of Tunbridge Wells\" stereotype in relation to the [[Waitrose]] supermarket chain refusing to open a store in the town while neighbouring \"downmarket\" towns of [[Tonbridge]] and [[Crowborough]] both did have one.<ref>{{cite web|author=Billy Kenber |url=http://www.thetimes.co.uk/tto/business/industries/retailing/article4050715.ece |title=Tunbridge Wells is disgusted at the lack of Waitrose |work=The Times  |date=2014-04-01 |accessdate=2017-02-17}} {{Subscription required|date=February 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, during the [[United Kingdom referendum on the British membership in the European Union]], ''[[The New York Times]]'' used Royal Tunbridge Wells as its base for reporting on the referendum. The town was chosen because it was seen as the \"quintessentially English town\" due to the ''Disgusted of Tunbridge Wells'' phrase. Although most Americans would not fully understand the reference, the town was nonetheless considered a symbol of middle England.<ref name=tott>{{cite web|author= |url=https://www.timesoftunbridgewells.co.uk/american-referendum-coverage-focuses-on-tunbridge-wells/ |title=American Referendum coverage focuses on Tunbridge Wells |work=Times of Tunbridge Wells |date= |accessdate=5 February 2017}}</ref> The town is a Conservative stronghold<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.itv.com/news/meridian/referendum/?page=15|title=How will Tunbridge Wells vote in EU Referendum?|publisher=itv.com|accessdate=10 March 2017}}</ref> and was the only council area in [[Kent]] to vote by a majority for Remain during [[Brexit]].<ref name=tott/>\n\n==Criticism==\nIn 2009, some residents of Royal Tunbridge Wells called the tag \"inappropriate\" and \"stereotypical\", and asked the town to drop association with it in favour of ''Delighted of Tunbridge Wells''.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.thisiskent.co.uk/news/disgusted-DELIGHTED/article-1351326-detail/article.html |title=We're not disgusted, we're DELIGHTED |date=18 September 2009 |website=This is Kent |accessdate=15 February 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110217100714/http://www.thisiskent.co.uk/news/disgusted-DELIGHTED/article-1351326-detail/article.html |archivedate=17 February 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> However, there was opposition to this campaign by other residents, some of whom wrote to newspapers in the \"Disgusted of Tunbridge Wells\" style arguing they preferred ''Disgusted of Tunbridge Wells''.<ref>{{cite web|last=Gerard |first=Jasper|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/6281016/The-rise-and-fall-of-Tunbridge-Wells.html |title=The rise and fall of Tunbridge Wells |work=The Telegraph |date= |accessdate=5 February 2017}}</ref> Local merchants at the town's information centre pointed out that tourists were buying twice as many goods bearing ''Disgusted of Tunbridge Wells'' than with ''Delighted of Tunbridge Wells''.<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/howaboutthat/6206646/Disgusted-of-Tunbridge-Wells-fight-back.html |title='Disgusted of Tunbridge Wells' fight back |work=The Telegraph |date=19 September 2009 |accessdate=5 February 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Wutb\u00fcrger ==\nThe German term Wutb\u00fcrger (or wutbuerger) first appeared in the German press in 2010 and roughly translates to \"angry or enraged citizen\" (''Wut'' meaning \"rage\" and ''B\u00fcrger'' meaning \u201ccitizen\")<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/Wutb%C3%BCrger|title=Wutb\u00fcrger - Wiktionary|website=en.wiktionary.org|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref>. In particular, the essay \"Der Wutb\u00fcrger\" in [[Der Spiegel]] (11 October 2010) made the term popular. It roughly denotes a \"citizen that protests heavily in public out of disappointment about certain political decisions\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.duden.de/rechtschreibung/Wutbuerger|title=Duden {{!}} Wutb\u00fcrger {{!}} Rechtschreibung, Bedeutung, Definition, Herkunft|website=www.duden.de|language=de|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref> The term Wutb\u00fcrger also became the German [[Word of the year (Germany)|word of the year]] in 2010. Manfred Klenner from the University of Zurich points out that it is fear rather than rage that is the prevalent emotion among Wutb\u00fcrgers on Facebook.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Klenner|first=Manfred|last2=Recupero|first2=Diego Reforgiato|last3=Dragoni|first3=Mauro|last4=Buscaldi|first4=Davide|last5=Mehwish|first5=Alam|last6=Cambria|first6=Erik|date=2018-06-04|title=What Does it Mean to be a Wutb\u00fcrger? A First Exploration|url=http://ceur-ws.org/Vol-2111/|journal=Klenner, Manfred  (2018). What Does it Mean to be a Wutb\u00fcrger? A First Exploration.  In: Proceedings of 4th Workshop on Sentic Computing, Sentiment Analysis, Opinion Mining, and Emotion Detection (EMSASW 2018), Heraklion, 4 June 2018 - 4 June 2018.|location=Heraklion|publisher=s.n.|doi=info:doi/10.5167/uzh-159171}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Edith Clampton]], a pseudonymous comedic letter-writer to the ''Bangkok Post''\n* ''[[Will it play in Peoria?]]''\n* [[Sir Bufton Tufton]], a recurring character in the UK satirical magazine ''Private Eye''\n* ''[[Monty Python's Flying Circus]]'', which featured numerous segments satirizing angry letters to the BBC\n* [[Keith Flett]], a noted writer of letters to British newspapers\n* [[Gammon (insult)]], directed at jingoistic supporters of Brexit\n* [[Down with this sort of thing]]\n* [[Placeholder name]]\n* [[Multiple-use name]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20150418222059/http://disgustedoftunbridgewells.co.uk/about.html Disgusted of Tunbridge Wells] (local website)\n\n{{Royal Tunbridge Wells}}\n\n[[Category:Royal Tunbridge Wells]]\n[[Category:Conservatism in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:English phrases]]\n[[Category:English culture]]\n[[Category:Letter writers]]\n[[Category:Stereotypes of the middle class]]\n[[Category:Class-related slurs]]\n[[Category:Anonymity pseudonyms]]\n", "name_user": "Ehrenkater", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eLater use", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Disgusted_of_Tunbridge_Wells"}
{"title_page": "Kato (The Green Hornet)", "text_new": "{{DISPLAYTITLE:Kato (''The Green Hornet'')}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2012}}\n{{superherobox\n|image = Kato (The Green Hornet character).jpg\n|converted = y\n|caption = Art by Aaron Campbell\n|character_name =Kato\n|debut = American [[old-time radio]], 1936\n|creators =[[Fran Striker]]\n|alter_ego =\n|Base of operations =\n|alliances =\n|partners=[[The Green Hornet]]\n|aliases=\n|powers=Master [[martial artist]]<br>[[Automotive engineering]] expert\n|}}\n'''Kato''' (\u52a0\u85e4) is a fictional character from ''[[The Green Hornet]]'' series. This character has appeared with the Green Hornet in film, television, book and comic book versions. Kato was the Hornet's assistant and has been played by a number of actors. On radio, Kato was initially played by [[Raymond Hayashi]], then [[Roland Parker (actor)|Roland Parker]] who had the role for most of the run, and in the later years Mickey Tolan and Paul Carnegie.<ref>[[Jim Harmon|Harmon, Jim]], ''Radio Mystery and Adventure and Its Appearances in Film, Television and Other Media'', [[McFarland & Company|McFarland & Company, Inc.]], 1992.</ref> [[Keye Luke]] took the role in the movie serials, and in the [[The Green Hornet (TV series)|television series]] he was portrayed by [[Bruce Lee]]. [[Jay Chou]]  played Kato in the 2011 [[The Green Hornet (2011 film)|Green Hornet film]].\n\n==Character history==\nKato was [[Britt Reid]]'s valet, who doubled as The Green Hornet's [[mask]]ed driver and partner to help him in his vigilante adventures, disguised as the activities of a racketeer and his chauffeur/[[bodyguard]]/enforcer. According to the storyline, years before the events depicted in the series, Britt Reid had saved Kato's life while traveling in the Far East. Depending on the version of the story, this prompted Kato to become Reid's assistant or friend.  In the anthology The Green Hornet Chronicles from [[Moonstone Books]], author [[Richard Dean Starr]]'s story \"Nothing Gold Can Stay: An Origin Story of Kato\" explores the character's background and how he ends up living in America, suggesting that Kato met Britt Reid on a later trip back to his homeland while in search of his mother.\n\n===Radio program and nationality===\n[[George W. Trendle]], the owner of radio station WXYZ in Michigan first created and produced \"The Green Hornet\" show in 1936, with the scripts being written by [[Fran Striker]]. The show became so popular it ran for nearly two decades and spun off at least two films. This was Trendle and Striker's second big radio hit; their first was \"The [[Lone Ranger]].\" \n\nIn the 1936 premiere of the radio program, Kato was presented as being Japanese. By 1939, the [[Second Sino-Japanese War|invasion of China]] by the [[Empire of Japan]] made this bad for public relations, and from that year until 1945 \"Britt Reid's Japanese valet\" in the show's opening was then simply identified by the announcer as his \"faithful valet.\" {{citation needed|date=January 2011}} The first of [[Universal Studios|Universal]]'s two movie serials, produced in 1939 but not released to theaters until early 1940, referred in passing to Kato being \"a [[Koreans|Korean]]\".  By 1941, Kato had begun to be referred to as [[Filipino people|Filipino]].<ref>radio episode \"Walkout for Profit\" ''The Green Hornet Collection'', Volume 2, Tape 1, Side B, Wireless, 1995 (original airdate: June 21, 1941, [[Blue Network]])).</ref>  A long-standing, but false, urban legend maintained that the switch from one to the other occurred immediately after the 1941 bombing of [[Pearl Harbor]]. In serials, Kato was played by Chinese-born [[Americans|American]] actor [[Keye Luke]].<ref>{{cite news|title= Float Like a Franchise, Sting Like a ...  |work= [[The New York Times]]|date=2011-01-07|url= https://www.nytimes.com/2011/01/09/movies/09hornet.html?_r=1&hpw|accessdate=2011-01-10|first=Franz|last=Lidz}}</ref> In the 2011 film, Kato (played by [[Jay Chou]]) tells Britt Reid that he was born in the Chinese city of [[Shanghai]]; Reid replies by saying that he \"love[s] Japan\".\n\n\n\n===Television series===\n{{Main|The Green Hornet (TV series)}}\nThe televised series of \"[[The Green Hornet]]\" was created and produced by William Dozier, the owner of Greenway Productions, for ABC. It ran from 1966 to 1967 and was then cancelled after that one season. Van Williams played the Green Hornet and [[Bruce Lee]] played [[Kato]]. Dozier was also the creator of the more popular \"[[Batman]]\" television series. Even though he had the Green Hornet and Kato appear on \"[[Batman]]\" three times, they never acquired a large audience.\n\n[[File:Kato (Bruce Lee).png|thumb|left|upright|Kato, as portrayed by [[Bruce Lee]] in the television series]]\nIt was due in part to [[Bruce Lee]]'s portrayal of this character, that the Green Hornet became more well known, and that the martial arts became more popular in the United States in the 1960s.<ref>{{Cite news|title= Getting 'The Green Hornet' off the ground|work=Los Angeles Times|date=July 23, 2010|url= http://articles.latimes.com/2010/jul/23/entertainment/la-et-green-hornet-20100723/3|accessdate=September 13, 2010|first=Geoff|last=Boucher}}</ref> Indeed, Lee refused to follow the American director's expectation of fisticuff fights and insisted he be allowed to use his martial arts skills. <ref>\"Bruce Lee Steals the Show in 'The Green Hornet'\" American Heritage Center Blog https://ahcwyo.org/2020/03/16/bruce-lee-steals-the-show-in-the-green-hornet/</ref> They became so popular with the audience that Van Williams, who played the Green Hornet, asked to be taught some moves. In a crossover episode of ''[[Batman (TV series)|Batman]]'' from the same time and companies, Kato had a battle with [[Dick Grayson|Robin]] that ended in a draw (the same thing happened simultaneously with their senior partners). This was in part because Lee refused to participate in a fight that showed Asian-style martial arts being defeated; the original script had the Green Hornet and Kato being beaten by Batman and Robin. The popular impression Lee made at the time is demonstrated by one of the TV series tie-in coloring books produced by Watkins & Strathmore. It is titled ''Kato's Revenge Featuring the Green Hornet''.<ref>Bonnet, Jean Pierre, \"The Buzz Word\" (letter to the editor), ''The Green Hornet'', Vol. 2, # 18, February 1993, [[NOW Comics]].</ref> ''The Green Hornet'''s success in Hong Kong, where it was popularly known as ''The Kato Show'', led to Lee starring in the [[Bruce Lee filmography|feature film]]s that would make him a pop culture icon. This show launched [[Bruce Lee]]'s adult television and film career. \n\nIn the TV series Kato (portrayed by [[Bruce Lee]]) is not at all a mechanic but a professional servant, a highly skilled driver, and a master of the art of war. In all other versions of the story he is also a mechanic, with the creations of both the special automobile, the Black Beauty, and the Hornet's trademark sleeping gas and the gun that delivered it attributed to him. In the television series he also became an expert in martial arts, which was implied in the first film serial with his use of a tranquilizing [[Knifehand strike|\"chop\"]] to the back of a thug's neck.\n\n\n===Comic book adaptations===\nAll ''Green Hornet'' comic book adaptations have included Kato. These were produced by [[Helnit]] (later [[Holyoke Publishing|Holyoke]]), [[Harvey Comics|Harvey]], [[Dell Comics|Dell]] and, tied into the television version, [[Gold Key Comics|Gold Key]]. Beginning in [[1989 in comics|1989]] one, published by [[NOW Comics]], established a continuity between the different versions of the story. In this comic, the TV/Bruce Lee version of Kato was the son of the Kato from the radio stories, and had the given name Hayashi as an homage to the character's first radio actor.<ref>[[Will Murray (writer)|Murray, Will]], \"Where Hornets Swarm,\" ''[[Comics Scene (magazine)|Comics Scene]]'', No. 9, October 1989, [[Starlog|Starlog Communications International, Inc.]], p.42.</ref>\n\nThe comic also established a new Kato, a much younger half-sister of the television-based character, Mishi. This female Kato also insisted on being treated as the Hornet's full partner rather than a sidekick. However, the Green Hornet, Inc., soon withdrew approval and this character was replaced with the 1960s version after Vol. 1, #10.<ref>Piron, Diane, \"The Buzz Word\" (letter column), ''The Green Hornet'', Vol. 1, No. 13, November 1990.</ref> Her removal was explained by having the Kato family company, Nippon Today, needing her automotive designing services at its Zurich, Switzerland facility. Mishi would return in Volume 2, appearing sporadically in the new costumed identity of the Crimson Wasp, on a vendetta against the criminal, Johnny Dollar. She eventually revealed (in ''The Green Hornet'' Vol. 2, #s 12 & 13, August & September 1992) that he had been an embezzling executive at the Swiss plant, whose actions she unwittingly began to expose. Consequently, he had murdered her fianc\u00e9 and his daughter in an attack that also caused the unknowingly pregnant Mishi, the main target, to miscarry.\n\nIn the No. 34, July 1994 issue of that run, she appeared in her \"Hornet's partner\" guise one additional time, as the masked Paul Reid attended a gangland meeting; the rules stated that each \"boss\" was allowed two \"boys.\" During this period, Hayashi became romantically involved with District Attorney Diana Reid, daughter of the original Hornet, who even thought for a while that she had conceived his child. In the final issue, Diana discussed their wedding plans with Mishi. In the last two issues, yet another Kato, a nephew to both of these named Kono, was brought in to allow the aging Hayashi to retire from crime-fighting, but the publisher's ceasing of operations prevented much of him being seen. The Bruce Lee-based Kato was also featured in two of his own spin-off miniseries, written by [[Mike Baron]]. The first had him defending a Chinese temple, where he had studied [[kung fu]], from the Communist government, while in the second he took the job of bodyguarding a heroin-addicted rock star. A third solo adventure, also by Baron, was announced and promoted first as another miniseries, then as a graphic novel (now subtitled \"Dragons in Eden\"), but was left unpublished when NOW folded. The line featured one other version of the character.\n\nThe three-issue mini-series ''The Green Hornet: Dark Tomorrow'' (June&ndash;August 1993) was set approximately one hundred years in the future, and had an Asian-American Green Hornet, real name Clayton Reid, who had been corrupted by power and truly became the crime boss he was supposed to only pretend to be, fighting a Caucasian Kato. Beyond the reversal of ethnicities, the latter added the claim that he and the future Hornet were cousins, and the art's depiction of this Hornet's unnamed paternal grandparents resembles Paul Reid and Mishi Kato. Although the future Kato is not further identified here, a later \"Reid/Kato Family Trees\" feature (in ''The Green Hornet'', Vol. 2, # 26, October 1993) gave him the first name Luke.\n\nThis comic book incarnation gave a degree of official status to a long-standing error about the character, that in his ''masked'' identity he is known as Kato. The name was restricted to his private persona in the original radio series, the two movie serials, and most of the television version (there were two slips in this last medium, one on the ''[[Batman (TV series)|Batman]]'' appearance, the other in the last filmed episode of the ''Hornet'' series itself, \"Invasion from Outer Space, Part 2\"; this story is well out of sync with the rest of the run, and the writer, director, and even the line producer are people with no other credits on the program). But the NOW comic version made a big point of having the masked assistants called Kato, with the woman at one early point telling the equally new Hornet during their first adventure, \"While I'm in this funky get-up, call me Kato. It's part of the tradition.\"<ref>''The Green Hornet'', Vol. 1, No. 7, May 1990, [[NOW Comics]], p. 7.</ref>\n\nIn the [[Kevin Smith]]'s 2010 revamp of the continuity, Kato is depicted, in modern times, as the elderly but still physically fit valet of the late Britt Reid, killed by a yakuza mobster going by the ''Black Hornet '' sobriquet. The elder Kato, in this version a Japanese forced to act Filipino to avoid the suspicions and the racist charges against his people during WWII, retires his identity along with Britt Reid, and both men decide to devote themselves to their families, respectively raising their offspring Britt Reid Jr. and Mulan Kato.\n\nAfter Britt Reid's death, Kato returns in America with Mulan, now the second Kato, to act out the ''Secret Testament'' of Britt Reid Sr., who wished, in the event of his death, Kato to destroy every Green Hornet paraphernalia still in his possession and whisk Britt Reid Jr. to Japan, for his safety. However both offspring refuse Reid's and Kato's will: Mulan Kato, now clad in a close variation of her father's original outfit, storms off to confront the Yakuza, and Britt Reid Jr. manages to steal one of the Green Hornet costumes to help her, despite having little training on his own.<ref>''Green Hornet'' No. 3 (2010)</ref>\n\nAs the new Kato, Mulan is a strong, physically fit, silent warrior woman, able to perform amazing feats with uncanny strength and precision.<ref>''Green Hornet'' No. 2 (2010)</ref>  Despite having been shown, in her late teens, as a peppy, lively, cheery ''social butterfly'',<ref>''Kato'' No. 1 (2010)</ref> the adult Mulan Kato is a darker, brooding character who never speaks (despite physically able to do so, Mulan prefers speaking as little as she can to prevent the much talkative Britt Reid Jr., and seemingly everyone else, from talking back<ref>''Kato'' No. 5 (2010)</ref>) and shows little, if no interest at all, for any form of socialization, a thing that seems to distress the second Green Hornet, every bit the suave socialite his father was.\n\nIn addition, the limited series ''Green Hornet: Parallel Lives'' by writer Jai Nitz, will serve as a prequel to the [[The Green Hornet (2011 film)|2011 Green Hornet film]], exploring the backstory for the film's version of Kato.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.comicbookresources.com/?page=article&id=26322 |title=Nitz Separates \"Green Hornet: Parallel Lives\" |date=May 20, 2010|first=Steve|last=Sunu|work=Comic Book Resources |accessdate=December 25, 2010}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, an eight-issue miniseries called ''Masks'' brought together famous heroes from the pulp era. It starred [[The Shadow]], the Green Hornet and Kato, [[The Spider]] and [[Zorro]], and was written by [[Chris Roberson (author)|Chris Roberson]] with art by [[Alex Ross]] and [[Dennis Calero]].<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.comicvine.com/masks/4050-54311/ |title=Masks |first= |last= |work=Comic Vine |year=2013 |accessdate=6 November 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Films===\nIn 1975, the Taiwanese actor [[Bruce Li]] played Kato in ''Bruce Lee Against Supermen''.<ref>{{Google books|Co5XDwAAQBAJ|Spinegrinder: The Movies Most Critics Won't Write about|page=|keywords=bruce+li+kato+supermen|text=|plainurl=}}</ref>\n\nA 1994 Hong Kong film, ''Qing feng xia'', starred [[Kar Lok Chin]] as a Kato-like masked hero called the Green Hornet (in English subtitles).<ref>{{cite news|title= Channeling Kato: Jay Chou dons the iconic mask in GREEN HORNET|first=Gene|last=Ching|work=[[Kung Fu Magazine]]|url = http://www.kungfumagazine.com/ezine/article.php?article=942|accessdate=January 22, 2011}}</ref> In one scene, he is reminded of his predecessors, one of whom is represented by a picture of Bruce Lee in his TV Kato costume.{{Citation needed|date=June 2010}}.\n\n===Portrayed in ''Dragon: The Bruce Lee Story''===\nThe 1993 American semi-fictionalized film biography ''[[Dragon: The Bruce Lee Story]],'' in which [[Jason Scott Lee]] (no relation) portrayed Bruce Lee, featured scenes involving the filming of the TV series ''[[The Green Hornet (TV series)|The Green Hornet]].''<ref>{{cite web | title= Green Hornet Pays Homage to His Kato | work=Los Angeles Times | first=Jane | last=Galbraith | date=May 16, 1993 | url=http://articles.latimes.com/1993-05-16/entertainment/ca-35788_1_green-hornet | accessdate=2011-01-10}}</ref> [[Van Williams]], who starred in that TV series, appeared in the film as the show's director.<ref name= Galbraith>{{cite news|title= A Look inside Hollywood and the movies : Cameo Corner : Green Hornet Pays Homage to His Kato| work= [[Los Angeles Times]] |date=May 16, 1993|url= http://articles.latimes.com/1993-05-16/entertainment/ca-35788_1_green-hornet|accessdate=December 7, 2010| first= Jane|last=Galbraith| archivedate= December 20, 2016| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20161220193339/http://articles.latimes.com/1993-05-16/entertainment/ca-35788_1_green-hornet| url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Feature films===\n{{Main|Black Mask (film)}}\n''Black Mask'' is a [[Hong Kong films of 1996|1996]] [[Cinema of Hong Kong|Hong Kong]] [[Hong Kong action cinema|action film]] starring [[Jet Li]]. \nThe film is an adaptation of the [[List of manhua#1990s|1992]] [[manhua]] ''Black Mask'' by [[Li Chi-Tak]].  In the film, in homage to ''[[The Green Hornet]]'', Black Mask wears a domino mask and chauffeur's cap in the same style as Kato from the series. The Black Mask is even compared to Kato in one scene. In 2002, it was followed by a sequel, ''[[Black Mask 2: City of Masks]]'' starring [[Andy On]].\n\n{{Main|Legend of the Fist: The Return of Chen Zhen}}\nIn the film Legend of the Fist: The Return of Chen Zhen, released late September 2010 in Asia and early 2011 in the United States, there is a large feature of the Green Hornet. The subplot consist of the main character [[Chen Zhen (character)|Chen Zhen]] (played by [[Donnie Yen]]) dressing up as a mask vigilante (based on the Green Hornet's sidekick Kato) to stop Japanese assassinations and to protect the people.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://screenanarchy.com/2010/06/donnie-yen-has-a-question-for-the-makers-of-the-green-hornet-why-did-you-bother.html |title=Donnie Yen Has A Question For The Makers Of THE GREEN HORNET: Why Did You Bother? |first=Todd |last=Brown |work=Screen Anarchy|date=29 June 2010}}</ref>\n\nThe director has mentioned that since Bruce Lee played both Chen Zhen (in the 1972 film Fist of Fury) and Kato (in the 1960s television series The Green Hornet) before, the film was a tribute and dedication to Lee.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.asianewsnet.net/home/news.php?id=14481&sec=24 |title=Bruce Lee tribute |work=The Straits Times |author=Yip Wai Yee |date=September 22, 2010|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110119093459/http://www.asianewsnet.net/home/news.php?sec=24&id=14481|archivedate=January 19, 2011}}</ref>\n\n{{Main|The Green Hornet (2011 film)}}\nOn June 4, 2008 Sony Pictures announced plans for a feature film of the superhero. Released on January 14, 2011,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=greenhornet.htm |title=The Green Hornet |website=Box Office Mojo}}</ref> the film starred [[Seth Rogen]], who took on writing duties along with ''[[Superbad (film)|Superbad]]'' co-writer [[Evan Goldberg]]. [[Stephen Chow]] had originally signed to play Kato,<ref>{{cite news| title='The Green Hornet': Asian comedy star Stephen Chow to play Kato and direct |first=Nicole |last=Sperling |date=19 September 2008 |work=Entertainment Weekly |url=http://ew.com/article/2008/09/19/stephen-chow-to/}}</ref> but then dropped out.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.slashfilm.com/2009/07/11/kato-casting-call-kicks-chow-to-the-curb/ |title=Kato Casting Call Kicks Chow To The Curb? |date=July 11, 2009 |first=Brendon |last=Connelly |work=Slash Film |accessdate=December 25, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100525203428/http://www.slashfilm.com/2009/07/11/kato-casting-call-kicks-chow-to-the-curb/ |archive-date=May 25, 2010 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Taiwanese actor [[Jay Chou]] replaced Chow as Kato for the film.<ref>{{cite news | last = Wallace | first = Lewis | title = ''Green Hornet'' Gets Its Kato: Asian Pop Star Jay Chou | url = https://www.wired.com/underwire/2009/08/green-hornet-gets-its-kato-asian-pop-star-jay-chou/ | work=[[Wired (magazine)|Wired]] | date = August 7, 2009 | accessdate = November 2, 2010}}</ref> In this version, Kato is an orphan who ran away from the orphanage, and was originally employed by Britt Reid's father James as a car mechanic (also making his coffee with a specially-designed machine he had created for the purpose), joining Britt on the steps that lead to him becoming the Green Hornet as Britt concluded that they had both been wasting their potential. Kato's martial art skills in this version of the series are so exceptional that he claims that time literally slows down for him when he gets an adrenaline rush in a dangerous situation, as well as his traditional role as mechanic and driver. Although he and Britt have a temporary falling-out when they argue over their respective importance to the \"Green Hornet\" concept- Kato acting as the actual action man of the Hornet while Britt is the public face as Kato is too fast for any cameras to see him- they patch up their differences in time to destroy the gang of crime lord Chudnofsky.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.comics.org/search.lasso?type=title&query=Kato+of+the+Green+Hornet&sort=chrono&Submit=Search ''Kato of the Green Hornet''] at the [[Grand Comics Database]]\n* \"[http://www.snopes.com/radiotv/radio/kato.asp Turning Japanese].\" ''[[Snopes]]''. February 1, 2011.\n\n{{The Green Hornet}}\n{{Batman (TV series)}}\n{{GoldenAge}}\n\n[[Category:Green Hornet]]\n[[Category:Comic book sidekicks]]\n[[Category:Radio characters introduced in 1936]]\n[[Category:Fictional Japanese people]]\n[[Category:Chinese superheroes]]\n[[Category:Fictional Jeet Kune Do practitioners]]\n[[Category:Fictional bodyguards]]\n[[Category:Fictional chauffeurs]]\n[[Category:Fictional software engineers]]\n[[Category:Fictional hackers]]\n[[Category:Fictional henchmen]]\n[[Category:Fictional inventors]]\n[[Category:Fictional mechanics]]\n[[Category:Fictional orphans]]\n[[Category:Fictional scientists]]\n[[Category:Fictional vigilantes]]\n[[Category:Fictional valets]]\n[[Category:Film sidekicks]]\n[[Category:Radio sidekicks]]\n[[Category:Television sidekicks]]\n[[Category:Dell Comics characters]]\n", "text_old": "{{DISPLAYTITLE:Kato (''The Green Hornet'')}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2012}}\n{{superherobox\n|image = Kato (The Green Hornet character).jpg\n|converted = y\n|caption = Art by Aaron Campbell\n|character_name =Kato\n|debut = American [[old-time radio]], 1936\n|creators =[[Fran Striker]]\n|alter_ego =\n|Base of operations =\n|alliances =\n|partners=[[The Green Hornet]]\n|aliases=\n|powers=Master [[martial artist]]<br>[[Automotive engineering]] expert\n|}}\n'''Kato''' (\u52a0\u85e4) is a fictional character from ''[[The Green Hornet]]'' series. This character has also appeared with the Green Hornet in film, television, book and comic book versions. Kato was the Hornet's assistant and has been played by a number of actors. On radio, Kato was initially played by [[Raymond Hayashi]], then [[Roland Parker (actor)|Roland Parker]] who had the role for most of the run, and in the later years Mickey Tolan and Paul Carnegie.<ref>[[Jim Harmon|Harmon, Jim]], ''Radio Mystery and Adventure and Its Appearances in Film, Television and Other Media'', [[McFarland & Company|McFarland & Company, Inc.]], 1992.</ref> [[Keye Luke]] took the role in the movie serials, and in the [[The Green Hornet (TV series)|television series]] he was portrayed by [[Bruce Lee]]. [[Jay Chou]]  played Kato in the 2011 [[The Green Hornet (2011 film)|Green Hornet film]].\n\n==Character history==\nKato was [[Britt Reid]]'s valet, who doubled as The Green Hornet's [[mask]]ed driver and partner to help him in his vigilante adventures, disguised as the activities of a racketeer and his chauffeur/[[bodyguard]]/enforcer. According to the storyline, years before the events depicted in the series, Britt Reid had saved Kato's life while traveling in the Far East. Depending on the version of the story, this prompted Kato to become Reid's assistant or friend.  In the anthology The Green Hornet Chronicles from [[Moonstone Books]], author [[Richard Dean Starr]]'s story \"Nothing Gold Can Stay: An Origin Story of Kato\" explores the character's background and how he ends up living in America, suggesting that Kato met Britt Reid on a later trip back to his homeland while in search of his mother.\n\n===Radio program and nationality===\n[[George W. Trendle]], the owner of radio station WXYZ in Michigan first created and produced \"The Green Hornet\" show in 1936, with the scripts being written by [[Fran Striker]]. The show became so popular it ran for nearly two decades and spun off at least two films. This was Trendle and Striker's second big radio hit; their first was \"The [[Lone Ranger]].\" \n\nIn the 1936 premiere of the radio program, Kato was presented as being Japanese. By 1939, the [[Second Sino-Japanese War|invasion of China]] by the [[Empire of Japan]] made this bad for public relations, and from that year until 1945 \"Britt Reid's Japanese valet\" in the show's opening was then simply identified by the announcer as his \"faithful valet.\" {{citation needed|date=January 2011}} The first of [[Universal Studios|Universal]]'s two movie serials, produced in 1939 but not released to theaters until early 1940, referred in passing to Kato being \"a [[Koreans|Korean]]\".  By 1941, Kato had begun to be referred to as [[Filipino people|Filipino]].<ref>radio episode \"Walkout for Profit\" ''The Green Hornet Collection'', Volume 2, Tape 1, Side B, Wireless, 1995 (original airdate: June 21, 1941, [[Blue Network]])).</ref>  A long-standing, but false, urban legend maintained that the switch from one to the other occurred immediately after the 1941 bombing of [[Pearl Harbor]]. In serials, Kato was played by Chinese-born [[Americans|American]] actor [[Keye Luke]].<ref>{{cite news|title= Float Like a Franchise, Sting Like a ...  |work= [[The New York Times]]|date=2011-01-07|url= https://www.nytimes.com/2011/01/09/movies/09hornet.html?_r=1&hpw|accessdate=2011-01-10|first=Franz|last=Lidz}}</ref> In the 2011 film, Kato (played by [[Jay Chou]]) tells Britt Reid that he was born in the Chinese city of [[Shanghai]]; Reid replies by saying that he \"love[s] Japan\".\n\n\n\n===Television series===\n{{Main|The Green Hornet (TV series)}}\nThe televised series of \"[[The Green Hornet]]\" was created and produced by William Dozier, the owner of Greenway Productions, for ABC. It ran from 1966 to 1967 and was then cancelled after that one season. Van Williams played the Green Hornet and [[Bruce Lee]] played [[Kato]]. Dozier was also the creator of the more popular \"[[Batman]]\" television series. Even though he had the Green Hornet and Kato appear on \"[[Batman]]\" three times, they never acquired a large audience.\n\n[[File:Kato (Bruce Lee).png|thumb|left|upright|Kato, as portrayed by [[Bruce Lee]] in the television series]]\nIt was due in part to [[Bruce Lee]]'s portrayal of this character, that the Green Hornet became more well known, and that the martial arts became more popular in the United States in the 1960s.<ref>{{Cite news|title= Getting 'The Green Hornet' off the ground|work=Los Angeles Times|date=July 23, 2010|url= http://articles.latimes.com/2010/jul/23/entertainment/la-et-green-hornet-20100723/3|accessdate=September 13, 2010|first=Geoff|last=Boucher}}</ref> Indeed, Lee refused to follow the American director's expectation of fisticuff fights and insisted he be allowed to use his martial arts skills. <ref>\"Bruce Lee Steals the Show in 'The Green Hornet'\" American Heritage Center Blog https://ahcwyo.org/2020/03/16/bruce-lee-steals-the-show-in-the-green-hornet/</ref> They became so popular with the audience that Van Williams, who played the Green Hornet, asked to be taught some moves. In a crossover episode of ''[[Batman (TV series)|Batman]]'' from the same time and companies, Kato had a battle with [[Dick Grayson|Robin]] that ended in a draw (the same thing happened simultaneously with their senior partners). This was in part because Lee refused to participate in a fight that showed Asian-style martial arts being defeated; the original script had the Green Hornet and Kato being beaten by Batman and Robin. The popular impression Lee made at the time is demonstrated by one of the TV series tie-in coloring books produced by Watkins & Strathmore. It is titled ''Kato's Revenge Featuring the Green Hornet''.<ref>Bonnet, Jean Pierre, \"The Buzz Word\" (letter to the editor), ''The Green Hornet'', Vol. 2, # 18, February 1993, [[NOW Comics]].</ref> ''The Green Hornet'''s success in Hong Kong, where it was popularly known as ''The Kato Show'', led to Lee starring in the [[Bruce Lee filmography|feature film]]s that would make him a pop culture icon. This show launched [[Bruce Lee]]'s adult television and film career. \n\nIn the TV series Kato (portrayed by [[Bruce Lee]]) is not at all a mechanic but a professional servant, a highly skilled driver, and a master of the art of war. In all other versions of the story he is also a mechanic, with the creations of both the special automobile, the Black Beauty, and the Hornet's trademark sleeping gas and the gun that delivered it attributed to him. In the television series he also became an expert in martial arts, which was implied in the first film serial with his use of a tranquilizing [[Knifehand strike|\"chop\"]] to the back of a thug's neck.\n\n\n===Comic book adaptations===\nAll ''Green Hornet'' comic book adaptations have included Kato. These were produced by [[Helnit]] (later [[Holyoke Publishing|Holyoke]]), [[Harvey Comics|Harvey]], [[Dell Comics|Dell]] and, tied into the television version, [[Gold Key Comics|Gold Key]]. Beginning in [[1989 in comics|1989]] one, published by [[NOW Comics]], established a continuity between the different versions of the story. In this comic, the TV/Bruce Lee version of Kato was the son of the Kato from the radio stories, and had the given name Hayashi as an homage to the character's first radio actor.<ref>[[Will Murray (writer)|Murray, Will]], \"Where Hornets Swarm,\" ''[[Comics Scene (magazine)|Comics Scene]]'', No. 9, October 1989, [[Starlog|Starlog Communications International, Inc.]], p.42.</ref>\n\nThe comic also established a new Kato, a much younger half-sister of the television-based character, Mishi. This female Kato also insisted on being treated as the Hornet's full partner rather than a sidekick. However, the Green Hornet, Inc., soon withdrew approval and this character was replaced with the 1960s version after Vol. 1, #10.<ref>Piron, Diane, \"The Buzz Word\" (letter column), ''The Green Hornet'', Vol. 1, No. 13, November 1990.</ref> Her removal was explained by having the Kato family company, Nippon Today, needing her automotive designing services at its Zurich, Switzerland facility. Mishi would return in Volume 2, appearing sporadically in the new costumed identity of the Crimson Wasp, on a vendetta against the criminal, Johnny Dollar. She eventually revealed (in ''The Green Hornet'' Vol. 2, #s 12 & 13, August & September 1992) that he had been an embezzling executive at the Swiss plant, whose actions she unwittingly began to expose. Consequently, he had murdered her fianc\u00e9 and his daughter in an attack that also caused the unknowingly pregnant Mishi, the main target, to miscarry.\n\nIn the No. 34, July 1994 issue of that run, she appeared in her \"Hornet's partner\" guise one additional time, as the masked Paul Reid attended a gangland meeting; the rules stated that each \"boss\" was allowed two \"boys.\" During this period, Hayashi became romantically involved with District Attorney Diana Reid, daughter of the original Hornet, who even thought for a while that she had conceived his child. In the final issue, Diana discussed their wedding plans with Mishi. In the last two issues, yet another Kato, a nephew to both of these named Kono, was brought in to allow the aging Hayashi to retire from crime-fighting, but the publisher's ceasing of operations prevented much of him being seen. The Bruce Lee-based Kato was also featured in two of his own spin-off miniseries, written by [[Mike Baron]]. The first had him defending a Chinese temple, where he had studied [[kung fu]], from the Communist government, while in the second he took the job of bodyguarding a heroin-addicted rock star. A third solo adventure, also by Baron, was announced and promoted first as another miniseries, then as a graphic novel (now subtitled \"Dragons in Eden\"), but was left unpublished when NOW folded. The line featured one other version of the character.\n\nThe three-issue mini-series ''The Green Hornet: Dark Tomorrow'' (June&ndash;August 1993) was set approximately one hundred years in the future, and had an Asian-American Green Hornet, real name Clayton Reid, who had been corrupted by power and truly became the crime boss he was supposed to only pretend to be, fighting a Caucasian Kato. Beyond the reversal of ethnicities, the latter added the claim that he and the future Hornet were cousins, and the art's depiction of this Hornet's unnamed paternal grandparents resembles Paul Reid and Mishi Kato. Although the future Kato is not further identified here, a later \"Reid/Kato Family Trees\" feature (in ''The Green Hornet'', Vol. 2, # 26, October 1993) gave him the first name Luke.\n\nThis comic book incarnation gave a degree of official status to a long-standing error about the character, that in his ''masked'' identity he is known as Kato. The name was restricted to his private persona in the original radio series, the two movie serials, and most of the television version (there were two slips in this last medium, one on the ''[[Batman (TV series)|Batman]]'' appearance, the other in the last filmed episode of the ''Hornet'' series itself, \"Invasion from Outer Space, Part 2\"; this story is well out of sync with the rest of the run, and the writer, director, and even the line producer are people with no other credits on the program). But the NOW comic version made a big point of having the masked assistants called Kato, with the woman at one early point telling the equally new Hornet during their first adventure, \"While I'm in this funky get-up, call me Kato. It's part of the tradition.\"<ref>''The Green Hornet'', Vol. 1, No. 7, May 1990, [[NOW Comics]], p. 7.</ref>\n\nIn the [[Kevin Smith]]'s 2010 revamp of the continuity, Kato is depicted, in modern times, as the elderly but still physically fit valet of the late Britt Reid, killed by a yakuza mobster going by the ''Black Hornet '' sobriquet. The elder Kato, in this version a Japanese forced to act Filipino to avoid the suspicions and the racist charges against his people during WWII, retires his identity along with Britt Reid, and both men decide to devote themselves to their families, respectively raising their offspring Britt Reid Jr. and Mulan Kato.\n\nAfter Britt Reid's death, Kato returns in America with Mulan, now the second Kato, to act out the ''Secret Testament'' of Britt Reid Sr., who wished, in the event of his death, Kato to destroy every Green Hornet paraphernalia still in his possession and whisk Britt Reid Jr. to Japan, for his safety. However both offspring refuse Reid's and Kato's will: Mulan Kato, now clad in a close variation of her father's original outfit, storms off to confront the Yakuza, and Britt Reid Jr. manages to steal one of the Green Hornet costumes to help her, despite having little training on his own.<ref>''Green Hornet'' No. 3 (2010)</ref>\n\nAs the new Kato, Mulan is a strong, physically fit, silent warrior woman, able to perform amazing feats with uncanny strength and precision.<ref>''Green Hornet'' No. 2 (2010)</ref>  Despite having been shown, in her late teens, as a peppy, lively, cheery ''social butterfly'',<ref>''Kato'' No. 1 (2010)</ref> the adult Mulan Kato is a darker, brooding character who never speaks (despite physically able to do so, Mulan prefers speaking as little as she can to prevent the much talkative Britt Reid Jr., and seemingly everyone else, from talking back<ref>''Kato'' No. 5 (2010)</ref>) and shows little, if no interest at all, for any form of socialization, a thing that seems to distress the second Green Hornet, every bit the suave socialite his father was.\n\nIn addition, the limited series ''Green Hornet: Parallel Lives'' by writer Jai Nitz, will serve as a prequel to the [[The Green Hornet (2011 film)|2011 Green Hornet film]], exploring the backstory for the film's version of Kato.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.comicbookresources.com/?page=article&id=26322 |title=Nitz Separates \"Green Hornet: Parallel Lives\" |date=May 20, 2010|first=Steve|last=Sunu|work=Comic Book Resources |accessdate=December 25, 2010}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, an eight-issue miniseries called ''Masks'' brought together famous heroes from the pulp era. It starred [[The Shadow]], the Green Hornet and Kato, [[The Spider]] and [[Zorro]], and was written by [[Chris Roberson (author)|Chris Roberson]] with art by [[Alex Ross]] and [[Dennis Calero]].<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.comicvine.com/masks/4050-54311/ |title=Masks |first= |last= |work=Comic Vine |year=2013 |accessdate=6 November 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Films===\nIn 1975, the Taiwanese actor [[Bruce Li]] played Kato in ''Bruce Lee Against Supermen''.<ref>{{Google books|Co5XDwAAQBAJ|Spinegrinder: The Movies Most Critics Won't Write about|page=|keywords=bruce+li+kato+supermen|text=|plainurl=}}</ref>\n\nA 1994 Hong Kong film, ''Qing feng xia'', starred [[Kar Lok Chin]] as a Kato-like masked hero called the Green Hornet (in English subtitles).<ref>{{cite news|title= Channeling Kato: Jay Chou dons the iconic mask in GREEN HORNET|first=Gene|last=Ching|work=[[Kung Fu Magazine]]|url = http://www.kungfumagazine.com/ezine/article.php?article=942|accessdate=January 22, 2011}}</ref> In one scene, he is reminded of his predecessors, one of whom is represented by a picture of Bruce Lee in his TV Kato costume.{{Citation needed|date=June 2010}}.\n\n===Portrayed in ''Dragon: The Bruce Lee Story''===\nThe 1993 American semi-fictionalized film biography ''[[Dragon: The Bruce Lee Story]],'' in which [[Jason Scott Lee]] (no relation) portrayed Bruce Lee, featured scenes involving the filming of the TV series ''[[The Green Hornet (TV series)|The Green Hornet]].''<ref>{{cite web | title= Green Hornet Pays Homage to His Kato | work=Los Angeles Times | first=Jane | last=Galbraith | date=May 16, 1993 | url=http://articles.latimes.com/1993-05-16/entertainment/ca-35788_1_green-hornet | accessdate=2011-01-10}}</ref> [[Van Williams]], who starred in that TV series, appeared in the film as the show's director.<ref name= Galbraith>{{cite news|title= A Look inside Hollywood and the movies : Cameo Corner : Green Hornet Pays Homage to His Kato| work= [[Los Angeles Times]] |date=May 16, 1993|url= http://articles.latimes.com/1993-05-16/entertainment/ca-35788_1_green-hornet|accessdate=December 7, 2010| first= Jane|last=Galbraith| archivedate= December 20, 2016| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20161220193339/http://articles.latimes.com/1993-05-16/entertainment/ca-35788_1_green-hornet| url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Feature films===\n{{Main|Black Mask (film)}}\n''Black Mask'' is a [[Hong Kong films of 1996|1996]] [[Cinema of Hong Kong|Hong Kong]] [[Hong Kong action cinema|action film]] starring [[Jet Li]]. \nThe film is an adaptation of the [[List of manhua#1990s|1992]] [[manhua]] ''Black Mask'' by [[Li Chi-Tak]].  In the film, in homage to ''[[The Green Hornet]]'', Black Mask wears a domino mask and chauffeur's cap in the same style as Kato from the series. The Black Mask is even compared to Kato in one scene. In 2002, it was followed by a sequel, ''[[Black Mask 2: City of Masks]]'' starring [[Andy On]].\n\n{{Main|Legend of the Fist: The Return of Chen Zhen}}\nIn the film Legend of the Fist: The Return of Chen Zhen, released late September 2010 in Asia and early 2011 in the United States, there is a large feature of the Green Hornet. The subplot consist of the main character [[Chen Zhen (character)|Chen Zhen]] (played by [[Donnie Yen]]) dressing up as a mask vigilante (based on the Green Hornet's sidekick Kato) to stop Japanese assassinations and to protect the people.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://screenanarchy.com/2010/06/donnie-yen-has-a-question-for-the-makers-of-the-green-hornet-why-did-you-bother.html |title=Donnie Yen Has A Question For The Makers Of THE GREEN HORNET: Why Did You Bother? |first=Todd |last=Brown |work=Screen Anarchy|date=29 June 2010}}</ref>\n\nThe director has mentioned that since Bruce Lee played both Chen Zhen (in the 1972 film Fist of Fury) and Kato (in the 1960s television series The Green Hornet) before, the film was a tribute and dedication to Lee.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.asianewsnet.net/home/news.php?id=14481&sec=24 |title=Bruce Lee tribute |work=The Straits Times |author=Yip Wai Yee |date=September 22, 2010|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110119093459/http://www.asianewsnet.net/home/news.php?sec=24&id=14481|archivedate=January 19, 2011}}</ref>\n\n{{Main|The Green Hornet (2011 film)}}\nOn June 4, 2008 Sony Pictures announced plans for a feature film of the superhero. Released on January 14, 2011,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=greenhornet.htm |title=The Green Hornet |website=Box Office Mojo}}</ref> the film starred [[Seth Rogen]], who took on writing duties along with ''[[Superbad (film)|Superbad]]'' co-writer [[Evan Goldberg]]. [[Stephen Chow]] had originally signed to play Kato,<ref>{{cite news| title='The Green Hornet': Asian comedy star Stephen Chow to play Kato and direct |first=Nicole |last=Sperling |date=19 September 2008 |work=Entertainment Weekly |url=http://ew.com/article/2008/09/19/stephen-chow-to/}}</ref> but then dropped out.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.slashfilm.com/2009/07/11/kato-casting-call-kicks-chow-to-the-curb/ |title=Kato Casting Call Kicks Chow To The Curb? |date=July 11, 2009 |first=Brendon |last=Connelly |work=Slash Film |accessdate=December 25, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100525203428/http://www.slashfilm.com/2009/07/11/kato-casting-call-kicks-chow-to-the-curb/ |archive-date=May 25, 2010 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Taiwanese actor [[Jay Chou]] replaced Chow as Kato for the film.<ref>{{cite news | last = Wallace | first = Lewis | title = ''Green Hornet'' Gets Its Kato: Asian Pop Star Jay Chou | url = https://www.wired.com/underwire/2009/08/green-hornet-gets-its-kato-asian-pop-star-jay-chou/ | work=[[Wired (magazine)|Wired]] | date = August 7, 2009 | accessdate = November 2, 2010}}</ref> In this version, Kato is an orphan who ran away from the orphanage, and was originally employed by Britt Reid's father James as a car mechanic (also making his coffee with a specially-designed machine he had created for the purpose), joining Britt on the steps that lead to him becoming the Green Hornet as Britt concluded that they had both been wasting their potential. Kato's martial art skills in this version of the series are so exceptional that he claims that time literally slows down for him when he gets an adrenaline rush in a dangerous situation, as well as his traditional role as mechanic and driver. Although he and Britt have a temporary falling-out when they argue over their respective importance to the \"Green Hornet\" concept- Kato acting as the actual action man of the Hornet while Britt is the public face as Kato is too fast for any cameras to see him- they patch up their differences in time to destroy the gang of crime lord Chudnofsky.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.comics.org/search.lasso?type=title&query=Kato+of+the+Green+Hornet&sort=chrono&Submit=Search ''Kato of the Green Hornet''] at the [[Grand Comics Database]]\n* \"[http://www.snopes.com/radiotv/radio/kato.asp Turning Japanese].\" ''[[Snopes]]''. February 1, 2011.\n\n{{The Green Hornet}}\n{{Batman (TV series)}}\n{{GoldenAge}}\n\n[[Category:Green Hornet]]\n[[Category:Comic book sidekicks]]\n[[Category:Radio characters introduced in 1936]]\n[[Category:Fictional Japanese people]]\n[[Category:Chinese superheroes]]\n[[Category:Fictional Jeet Kune Do practitioners]]\n[[Category:Fictional bodyguards]]\n[[Category:Fictional chauffeurs]]\n[[Category:Fictional software engineers]]\n[[Category:Fictional hackers]]\n[[Category:Fictional henchmen]]\n[[Category:Fictional inventors]]\n[[Category:Fictional mechanics]]\n[[Category:Fictional orphans]]\n[[Category:Fictional scientists]]\n[[Category:Fictional vigilantes]]\n[[Category:Fictional valets]]\n[[Category:Film sidekicks]]\n[[Category:Radio sidekicks]]\n[[Category:Television sidekicks]]\n[[Category:Dell Comics characters]]\n", "name_user": "PaulatAHC", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kato_(The_Green_Hornet)"}
{"title_page": "List of irredentist claims or disputes", "text_new": "{{short description|Wikimedia list article}}\n{{For|proposed mergers of sovereign states|List of proposed state mergers}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2018}}\n{{Multiple issues|\n{{more citations needed|date=May 2007}}\n{{original research|date=April 2011}}\n}}\n{{main|Irredentism}}\nThis is a '''list of irredentist claims or disputes'''. Irredentism is any political or popular movement that seeks to claim or reclaim and occupy a land that the movement's members consider to be a \"lost\" (or \"unredeemed\") territory from their nation's past. Not all [[territorial dispute]]s are irredentist, although they are often couched in irredentist [[propaganda|rhetoric]] to justify and [[legitimacy (political science)|legitimise]] such claims both internationally and within the country. \n\n==Prominent irredentist disputes (by area)==\nProminent irredentist disputes during the past century have included:\n\n=== Europe ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! scope=\"col\" width=\"130\" | State\n! scope=\"col\" width=\"150\" | Claimed area\n! Notes\n|-\n|{{flag|Armenia}}\n|{{flag|Republic of Artsakh}}\n|\n|-\n|{{flag|Austria}}\n|{{flag|South Tyrol}}\n|A desire to unify South Tyrol with Austria is held by nationalist groups in both Austria and South Tyrol, which became part of Italy following Austria's loss in [[World War I|World War One]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/magazine-20633126|title=South Tyrol's identity crisis: Italian, German, Austrian...?|last=Bell|first=Bethany|date=8 December 2012|accessdate=27 April 2016|publisher=BBC News|location=Bolzano, Italy}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nationalia.info/new/9915/south-tyrol-heading-to-unofficial-independence-referendum-in-autumn|title=South Tyrol heading to unofficial independence referendum in autumn|date=3 July 2013|work=nationalia.info|accessdate=27 April 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/education/2014/may/30/south-tyrol-live-in-italy-feel-austrian|title=The South Tyrol identity crisis: to live in Italy, but feel Austrian|last=Marchetti|first=Silvia|date=31 May 2014|accessdate=27 April 2016|publisher=The Guardian}}</ref>\n|-\n|{{flag|Azerbaijan}}\n|''Parts of:''<br />\n{{flag|Iran}}\n|\n|-\n|{{flag|Chechnya}}\n|''Parts of:''\n{{flag|Dagestan}}\n|Internal dispute: [[Chechnya]] (currently part of the Russian Federation) has occasionally laid claims on a region called Akkia (roughly the Auhovskiy rayon, in Russian), part of neighbouring Dagestan (also in Russia.) \n|-\n|{{flag|Georgia}}\n|{{flag|Abkhazia}}<br />{{flag|South Ossetia}}\n|[[Abkhaz\u2013Georgian conflict]]<br />[[Georgian\u2013Ossetian conflict]]\n|-\n|{{flag|Ingushetia}}\n|''Parts of:''\n{{flag|North Ossetia \u2013 Alania}}\n|Internal dispute: Both territories are part of [[Russia]].\n|-\n|{{flag|Ireland}}\n|{{flag|Northern Ireland}}\n| The claim was officially dropped in accordance with the [[Good Friday Agreement]].\n|-\n|{{flag|Portugal}}\n|{{flag|Olivenza}}\n|Currently administered by [[Spain]]. Not actively pursued by Portugal since both countries joined the [[European Union]] in 1986.\n|-\n|{{flag|Serbia}}\n|{{flag|Republika Srpska}}\n| Currently, there is a movement calling for the unification of Republika Srpska with Serbia. The area is currently part of [[Bosnia and Herzegovina]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.refworld.org/docid/5a9fc717a.html|title=Refworld {{!}} Bosnia: Defying court ban, Republika Srpska goes ahead with 'Statehood Day'|last=Refugees|first=United Nations High Commissioner for|website=Refworld|language=en|access-date=2019-03-26}}</ref>\n|-\n|{{flag|Spain}}\n|{{flag|Gibraltar}}\n|[[Status of Gibraltar]]\n|-\n|{{flag|Albania}}\n|{{flag|Kosovo}}\n|\n|}\n[[Russian irredentism]] can be divided into three categories: broad, intermediate, and narrow.\n\n* The broad sense includes all lands that historically made up the [[Russian Empire]] and/or the [[Soviet Union]] at their maximum extents. It may also extend to neighbouring countries or regions that are populated by peoples over which Russia ruled (e.g. [[Iranian Azerbaijan]] in [[Iran]]), or peoples which are closely related to them due to linguistic, ethnic or religious ties. Historically, Russia has pursued all of these avenues; examples include the [[Panslavism]] movement to put all of the [[Balkans]] (where there exists Slavic and [[Eastern Orthodox]] majorities) under Russian hegemony; the [[Moscow, third Rome|Third Rome]] philosophy, which focused on re-claiming the former [[Byzantine Empire]] regions (in particular the warm winter port of [[Constantinople]], today [[Istanbul]]), and in addition establishing a hegemony over [[Greater Armenia (political concept)|Greater Armenia]] and the [[Holy Land]] ([[Lebanon]], [[Palestine (region)|Palestine]] etc.). Simultaneously, there were ambitions to continue expansion into [[Persia]] and even [[India]] (see [[The Great Game]]). The Russian Empire also planned to force [[Qing Dynasty|Qing China]] to cede [[Xinjiang]], [[Manchuria]], [[Mongolia|Outer Mongolia]], and [[Korea]]. While the [[Russo-Japanese War]] ended most of these prospects, the Soviet Union would eventually create a sphere of influence in this area in the form of the [[Mongolian People's Republic]] and the [[Tuvan People's Republic]]. Finally, in [[Russian America]], Russia held claims extending from the [[Aleutian Islands]] to northern [[California]], but these plans were cancelled after Alaska [[Alaska Purchase|was sold to the United States]] in 1867.\n* The intermediate sense includes some or all of the independent countries and/or territories that made up the historical Russian borders. These may include [[Moldova]], [[Ukraine]], eastern [[Poland]], [[Belarus]], the [[Baltic states]], and [[Finland]] in Europe, [[Azerbaijan]], [[Armenia]], and [[Georgia (country)|Georgia]] in the [[Caucasus]], and [[Kazakhstan]], [[Turkmenistan]], [[Tajikistan]], [[Kyrgyzstan]], and [[Uzbekistan]] in [[Central Asia]]. Some narrower definitions include only the pro-Russian breakaway states of [[Abkhazia]] (Georgia), [[South Ossetia]] (Georgia), and [[Transnistria]] (Moldova), as well as [[Kars Oblast]] in Turkey and [[Batum Oblast]] partly in Turkey also ([[Ardahan Province]]) and [[Adjara]] in [[Georgia (country)|Georgia]].\n* The narrow sense of Russian irredentism focuses only on regions that are populated by [[Russians|ethnic Russians]] that are outside the Russian Federation, such as: [[Narva]] in [[Estonia]]; lands around [[Daugavpils]] and [[Riga]] in [[Latvia]]; [[Sloboda Ukraine]], [[Novorossiya]], and [[Crimea]] from Ukraine (the latter of which has ''de facto'' joined the Federation<ref>{{cite journal|first=Vladimir |last=Socor |author-link=Vladimir Socor |url=http://www.jamestown.org/regions/centralasia/single/?tx_ttnews[tt_news]=42144&tx_ttnews[backPid]=53&cHash=377ed0c543440239db55d887478f2c53#.VyAwZ3rbucw |title=Putin's Crimea Speech: A Manifesto of Greater-Russia Irredentism |journal=Eurasia Daily Monitor |volume=11 |issue=56 |date=25 March 2014 |accessdate=27 April 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160427052607/http://www.jamestown.org/programs/edm/single/?tx_ttnews%5Btt_news%5D=42144&cHash=7d7b25bd2616f914691c6f7e3b00c3eb |archivedate=27 April 2016 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|first=Stephen|last=Saideman|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/opinion/why-crimea-is-likely-the-limit-of-greater-russia/article17542819/|title=Why Crimea is likely the limit of Greater Russia|publisher=The Globe and Mail|date=18 March 2014|accessdate=27 April 2016}}</ref>); [[Gagra district]] in Georgia (also claimed by [[Abkhazia]]); and lands between the Russian border and the rivers of [[Ural River|Ural]] and [[Irtysh River|Irtysh]] in [[Kazakhstan]], as well as parts of [[Semirechye]].\n\n====Historical and fringe disputes====\nMany fringe and opposition groups in various countries maintain their own set of territorial claims, which are given below:\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! scope=\"col\" width=\"130\" | State\n! scope=\"col\" width=\"150\" | Claimed area\n! Notes\n|-\n|{{flag|Albania}}\n|[[Kosovo]]\n''Parts of:''<br />\n[[Serbia]]<br />[[Montenegro]]<br />[[North Macedonia]]<br />[[Greece]]\n|Some claim the calls for a [[Greater Albania]] is irredentist.\n|-\n|{{flag|Armenia}}\n| ''Parts of:''<br />\n{{flag|Georgia}}<br />{{flag|Azerbaijan}}<br />{{flag|Turkey}}<br />{{flag|Iran}}\n|\n|-\n|{{flag|Belarus}}\n|''Parts of:''<br />\n{{flag|Poland}}<br />{{flag|Lithuania}}<br />{{flag|Russia}}\n|\n|-\n|{{flag|Bosnia and Herzegovina}}\n|''Parts of:''<br />\n{{flag|Montenegro}}<br />{{flag|Serbia}}\n|\n|-\n|{{flag|Bulgaria}}\n|{{flag|North Macedonia}}\n''Parts of:''<br />\n{{flag|Romania}}<br />{{flag|Serbia}}<br />{{flag|Greece}}<br />{{flag|Turkey}}<br />{{flag|Albania}}\n|\n|-\n|{{flag|Croatia}}\n|''Parts of:''<br />\n{{flag|Bosnia and Herzegovina}}<br />{{flag|Serbia}}<br />{{flag|Montenegro}}\n|\n|-\n|{{flag|Denmark}}\n|{{flagicon image|Flag of Scania.svg}} [[Sk\u00e5neland|Scania]]<br />{{flagicon image|Flag of Schleswig.svg}} [[Duchy of Schleswig|Schleswig]]\n|\n|-\n|{{flag|England}}\n|{{flag|Monmouthshire}}\n|The [[English Democrats Party]] are irredentist in regards to [[Monmouthshire (historic)|Monmouthshire]] (since 1974 part of Wales).<ref name=\"EDPmanifesto\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/shared/bsp/hi/pdfs/EDP_uk_manifesto.pdf|title=Manifesto of the English Democrats: Putting England First|date=2005|accessdate=25 April 2016|publisher=[[bbc.co.uk]]|format=PDF}}</ref>\n|-\n|{{flag|Estonia}}\n| ''Parts of:''<br />\n{{flag|Russia}}\n|\n|-\n|{{flag|Finland}}\n|{{flag|Karelia}}\n|\n|-\n|{{flag|Greece}}\n|{{flag|Cyprus}}\n''Parts of:''<br />\n{{flag|Turkey}}<br />{{flag|Albania}}\n|The [[Megali Idea]] became a political objective of the Greek government in the early 20th century. It envisioned a \"Greater Greece\" covering areas of earlier Greek empires where significant Greek settlements still existed. The idea ended with the devastating defeat of the Greek army in  Asia Minor in 1922 and the following [[population exchange between Greece and Turkey]].<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Finefrock |first1=Michael M. |title=Ataturk, Lloyd George and the Megali Idea: Cause and Consequence of the Greek Plan to Seize Constantinople from the Allies, June-August 1922 |journal=The Journal of Modern History |date=March 1980 |volume=52 |issue=S1 |url=https://www.journals.uchicago.edu/doi/pdfplus/10.1086/242238 |accessdate=26 October 2019 |publisher=The University of Chicago Press Books}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=The Greek Turkish Population Exchange |url=https://cmes.arizona.edu/sites/cmes.arizona.edu/files/3.%20Case%20study%20-%20Greek%20Turkish%20Population%20Exchange_1.pdf |accessdate=26 October 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n|{{flag|Georgia}}\n|''Parts of:''<br />\n{{flag|Turkey}}<br />{{flag|Russia}}<br />{{flag|Azerbaijan}}<br />{{flag|Armenia}}\n|Georgian irredentists claim [[Tao-Klarjeti]] \n|-\n|{{flag|Germany}}\n|{{flag|Austria}}<br />{{flag|Luxembourg}}<br />{{flag|Liechtenstein}}\n\n''Parts of:''<br />\n{{flag|Belgium}}<br />{{flag|Poland}}<br />{{flag|Lithuania}}<br />{{flag|Russia}}<br />{{flag|Denmark}}<br />{{flag|France}}<br />{{flag|Czech Republic}}<br />{{flag|Hungary}}<br />{{flag|Slovakia}}<br />{{flag|Italy}}<br />{{flag|Slovenia}}\n|\n|-\n|{{flag|Hungary}}\n|''Parts of:''<br />\n{{flag|Slovakia}}<br />{{flag|Romania}}<br />{{flag|Serbia}}<br />{{flag|Ukraine}}<br />{{flag|Austria}}\n|\n|-\n|{{flag|Italy}}\n|{{flag|Malta}}<br />\n''Parts of:''<br />{{flag|Albania}}<br />{{flag|Croatia}}<br />{{flag|France}}\n\n|[[Italy|Italian]] claims to [[Istria]] and [[Dalmatia]] after [[World War I]]. \n|-\n|{{flag|North Macedonia}}\n|''Parts of:''<br />\n{{flag|Greece}}<br />{{flag|Bulgaria}}<br />{{flag|Albania}}\n|Irredentists from North Macedonia have expressed land claims to the entire historical region of [[Macedonia (region)|Macedonia]]\n|-\n|{{flag|Norway}}\n|