}}\n|''Parts of:''<br />\n{{flag|Argentina}}\n|\n|-\n|{{flag|Guanacaste}}\n|{{flag|Puntarenas}}\n|\n|-\n|{{flag|Guatemala}}\n|''Parts of:''<br/>\n{{flag|Belize}}\n|Referred to the [[International Court of Justice]] since 2019.\n|-\n|{{flag|Nicaragua}}\n|''Parts of:''<br />\n{{flag|Costa Rica}}<br />{{flag|Colombia}}\n|\n|-\n|{{flag|Venezuela}}\n|''Parts of:''<br />\n{{flag|Guyana}}\n|\n|}\n\n===North America===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! scope=\"col\" width=\"130\" | State\n! scope=\"col\" width=\"150\" | Claimed area\n! Notes\n|-\n\n|-\n|{{flag|Quebec}}\n|{{flag|Labrador}}\n|The Quebec government claims that the territory of [[Labrador]] belongs to the province of [[Quebec]]. [[Labrador]] is part of the province of [[Newfoundland and Labrador]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mef.qc.ca/question_du_labrador.htm|title=La question du Labrador|date=2 May 2001|work=Estrien Movement for French|language=fr|trans-title=The question Labrador|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050426064023/http://www.mef.qc.ca/question_du_labrador.htm|archivedate=26 April 2005|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n|}\n\n===Africa===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! scope=\"col\" width=\"130\" | State\n! scope=\"col\" width=\"150\" | Claimed area\n! Notes\n|-\n|{{flag|Comoros}}\n|{{flag|Mayotte}}\n|\n|-\n|{{flag|Madagascar}}\n|''Parts of:''<br />\n{{flag|France}}\n|\n|-\n|{{flag|Mauritania}}\n|{{flag|Western Sahara}}<br />{{flag|Azawad}}\n\n''Parts of:''<br />\n{{flag|Mali}}<br />{{flag|Niger}}\n|\n|-\n|{{flag|Morocco}}\n|{{flag|Western Sahara}}<br />{{flag|Madeira}}<br />{{flag|Canary Islands}}<br />{{flag|Mauritania}}<br />{{flag|Ceuta}}<br />{{flag|Melilla}}\n\n''Parts of:''<br />\n{{flag|Algeria}}<br />{{flag|Mali}}\n|\n|-\n|{{flag|Puntland}}\n|''Parts of:''<br />\n{{flag|Somaliland}}\n|rowspan=\"2\"|\n|-\n|{{flag|Somaliland}}\n|''Parts of:''<br />\n{{flag|Puntland}}\n|-\n|{{flag|Somalia}}\n|''Parts of:''<br />\n{{flag|Ethiopia}}<br />\n{{flag|Kenya}}\n|\n|}\n\n==See also==\n* [[Ethnic nationalism]]\n* [[Ethnic cleansing]]\n* [[Identity politics]]\n* [[Lebensraum]]\n* [[Revanchism]]\n* [[Status quo ante bellum]]\n* [[Manifest destiny]]\n* [[Historical powers]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Irredentism}}\n{{Secession in Countries}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:List Of Irredentist Claims Or Disputes}}\n[[Category:Irredentism|*]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Wikimedia list article}}\n{{For|proposed mergers of sovereign states|List of proposed state mergers}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2018}}\n{{Multiple issues|\n{{more citations needed|date=May 2007}}\n{{original research|date=April 2011}}\n}}\n{{main|Irredentism}}\nThis is a '''list of irredentist claims or disputes'''. Irredentism is any political or popular movement that seeks to claim or reclaim and occupy a land that the movement's members consider to be a \"lost\" (or \"unredeemed\") territory from their nation's past. Not all [[territorial dispute]]s are irredentist, although they are often couched in irredentist [[propaganda|rhetoric]] to justify and [[legitimacy (political science)|legitimise]] such claims both internationally and within the country. \n\n==Prominent irredentist disputes (by area)==\nProminent irredentist disputes during the past century have included:\n\n=== Europe ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! scope=\"col\" width=\"130\" | State\n! scope=\"col\" width=\"150\" | Claimed area\n! Notes\n|-\n|{{flag|Armenia}}\n|{{flag|Republic of Artsakh}}\n|\n|-\n|{{flag|Austria}}\n|{{flag|South Tyrol}}\n|A desire to unify South Tyrol with Austria is held by nationalist groups in both Austria and South Tyrol, which became part of Italy following Austria's loss in [[World War I|World War One]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/magazine-20633126|title=South Tyrol's identity crisis: Italian, German, Austrian...?|last=Bell|first=Bethany|date=8 December 2012|accessdate=27 April 2016|publisher=BBC News|location=Bolzano, Italy}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nationalia.info/new/9915/south-tyrol-heading-to-unofficial-independence-referendum-in-autumn|title=South Tyrol heading to unofficial independence referendum in autumn|date=3 July 2013|work=nationalia.info|accessdate=27 April 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/education/2014/may/30/south-tyrol-live-in-italy-feel-austrian|title=The South Tyrol identity crisis: to live in Italy, but feel Austrian|last=Marchetti|first=Silvia|date=31 May 2014|accessdate=27 April 2016|publisher=The Guardian}}</ref>\n|-\n|{{flag|Azerbaijan}}\n|''Parts of:''<br />\n{{flag|Iran}}\n|\n|-\n|{{flag|Chechnya}}\n|''Parts of:''\n{{flag|Dagestan}}\n|Internal dispute: [[Chechnya]] (currently part of the Russian Federation) has occasionally laid claims on a region called Akkia (roughly the Auhovskiy rayon, in Russian), part of neighbouring Dagestan (also in Russia.) \n|-\n|{{flag|Georgia}}\n|{{flag|Abkhazia}}<br />{{flag|South Ossetia}}\n|[[Abkhaz\u2013Georgian conflict]]<br />[[Georgian\u2013Ossetian conflict]]\n|-\n|{{flag|Ingushetia}}\n|''Parts of:''\n{{flag|North Ossetia \u2013 Alania}}\n|Internal dispute: Both territories are part of [[Russia]].\n|-\n|{{flag|Ireland}}\n|{{flag|Northern Ireland}}\n| The claim was officially dropped in accordance with the [[Good Friday Agreement]].\n|-\n|{{flag|Portugal}}\n|{{flag|Olivenza}}\n|Currently administered by [[Spain]]. Not actively pursued by Portugal since both countries joined the [[European Union]] in 1986.\n|-\n|{{flag|Serbia}}\n|{{flag|Republika Srpska}}\n| Currently, there is a movement calling for the unification of Republika Srpska with Serbia. The area is currently part of [[Bosnia and Herzegovina]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.refworld.org/docid/5a9fc717a.html|title=Refworld {{!}} Bosnia: Defying court ban, Republika Srpska goes ahead with 'Statehood Day'|last=Refugees|first=United Nations High Commissioner for|website=Refworld|language=en|access-date=2019-03-26}}</ref>\n|-\n|{{flag|Spain}}\n|{{flag|Gibraltar}}\n|[[Status of Gibraltar]]\n|-\n|{{flag|Albania}}\n|{{flag|Kosovo}}\n|\n|}\n[[Russian irredentism]] can be divided into three categories: broad, intermediate, and narrow.\n\n* The broad sense includes all lands that historically made up the [[Russian Empire]] and/or the [[Soviet Union]] at their maximum extents. It may also extend to neighbouring countries or regions that are populated by peoples over which Russia ruled (e.g. [[Iranian Azerbaijan]] in [[Iran]]), or peoples which are closely related to them due to linguistic, ethnic or religious ties. Historically, Russia has pursued all of these avenues; examples include the [[Panslavism]] movement to put all of the [[Balkans]] (where there exists Slavic and [[Eastern Orthodox]] majorities) under Russian hegemony; the [[Moscow, third Rome|Third Rome]] philosophy, which focused on re-claiming the former [[Byzantine Empire]] regions (in particular the warm winter port of [[Constantinople]], today [[Istanbul]]), and in addition establishing a hegemony over [[Greater Armenia (political concept)|Greater Armenia]] and the [[Holy Land]] ([[Lebanon]], [[Palestine (region)|Palestine]] etc.). Simultaneously, there were ambitions to continue expansion into [[Persia]] and even [[India]] (see [[The Great Game]]). The Russian Empire also planned to force [[Qing Dynasty|Qing China]] to cede [[Xinjiang]], [[Manchuria]], [[Mongolia|Outer Mongolia]], and [[Korea]]. While the [[Russo-Japanese War]] ended most of these prospects, the Soviet Union would eventually create a sphere of influence in this area in the form of the [[Mongolian People's Republic]] and the [[Tuvan People's Republic]]. Finally, in [[Russian America]], Russia held claims extending from the [[Aleutian Islands]] to northern [[California]], but these plans were cancelled after Alaska [[Alaska Purchase|was sold to the United States]] in 1867.\n* The intermediate sense includes some or all of the independent countries and/or territories that made up the historical Russian borders. These may include [[Moldova]], [[Ukraine]], eastern [[Poland]], [[Belarus]], the [[Baltic states]], and [[Finland]] in Europe, [[Azerbaijan]], [[Armenia]], and [[Georgia (country)|Georgia]] in the [[Caucasus]], and [[Kazakhstan]], [[Turkmenistan]], [[Tajikistan]], [[Kyrgyzstan]], and [[Uzbekistan]] in [[Central Asia]]. Some narrower definitions include only the pro-Russian breakaway states of [[Abkhazia]] (Georgia), [[South Ossetia]] (Georgia), and [[Transnistria]] (Moldova), as well as [[Kars Oblast]] in Turkey and [[Batum Oblast]] partly in Turkey also ([[Ardahan Province]]) and [[Adjara]] in [[Georgia (country)|Georgia]].\n* The narrow sense of Russian irredentism focuses only on regions that are populated by [[Russians|ethnic Russians]] that are outside the Russian Federation, such as: [[Narva]] in [[Estonia]]; lands around [[Daugavpils]] and [[Riga]] in [[Latvia]]; [[Sloboda Ukraine]], [[Novorossiya]], and [[Crimea]] from Ukraine (the latter of which has ''de facto'' joined the Federation<ref>{{cite journal|first=Vladimir |last=Socor |author-link=Vladimir Socor |url=http://www.jamestown.org/regions/centralasia/single/?tx_ttnews[tt_news]=42144&tx_ttnews[backPid]=53&cHash=377ed0c543440239db55d887478f2c53#.VyAwZ3rbucw |title=Putin's Crimea Speech: A Manifesto of Greater-Russia Irredentism |journal=Eurasia Daily Monitor |volume=11 |issue=56 |date=25 March 2014 |accessdate=27 April 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160427052607/http://www.jamestown.org/programs/edm/single/?tx_ttnews%5Btt_news%5D=42144&cHash=7d7b25bd2616f914691c6f7e3b00c3eb |archivedate=27 April 2016 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|first=Stephen|last=Saideman|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/opinion/why-crimea-is-likely-the-limit-of-greater-russia/article17542819/|title=Why Crimea is likely the limit of Greater Russia|publisher=The Globe and Mail|date=18 March 2014|accessdate=27 April 2016}}</ref>); [[Gagra district]] in Georgia (also claimed by [[Abkhazia]]); and lands between the Russian border and the rivers of [[Ural River|Ural]] and [[Irtysh River|Irtysh]] in [[Kazakhstan]], as well as parts of [[Semirechye]].\n\n====Historical and fringe disputes====\nMany fringe and opposition groups in various countries maintain their own set of territorial claims, which are given below:\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! scope=\"col\" width=\"130\" | State\n! scope=\"col\" width=\"150\" | Claimed area\n! Notes\n|-\n|{{flag|Albania}}\n|[[Kosovo]]\n''Parts of:''<br />\n[[Serbia]]<br />[[Montenegro]]<br />[[North Macedonia]]<br />[[Greece]]\n|Some claim the calls for a [[Greater Albania]] is irredentist.\n|-\n|{{flag|Armenia}}\n| ''Parts of:''<br />\n{{flag|Georgia}}<br />{{flag|Azerbaijan}}<br />{{flag|Turkey}}<br />{{flag|Iran}}\n|\n|-\n|{{flag|Belarus}}\n|''Parts of:''<br />\n{{flag|Poland}}<br />{{flag|Lithuania}}<br />{{flag|Russia}}\n|\n|-\n|{{flag|Bosnia and Herzegovina}}\n|''Parts of:''<br />\n{{flag|Montenegro}}<br />{{flag|Serbia}}\n|\n|-\n|{{flag|Bulgaria}}\n|{{flag|North Macedonia}}\n''Parts of:''<br />\n{{flag|Romania}}<br />{{flag|Serbia}}<br />{{flag|Greece}}<br />{{flag|Turkey}}<br />{{flag|Albania}}\n|\n|-\n|{{flag|Croatia}}\n|''Parts of:''<br />\n{{flag|Bosnia and Herzegovina}}<br />{{flag|Serbia}}<br />{{flag|Montenegro}}\n|\n|-\n|{{flag|Denmark}}\n|{{flagicon image|Flag of Scania.svg}} [[Sk\u00e5neland|Scania]]<br />{{flagicon image|Flag of Schleswig.svg}} [[Duchy of Schleswig|Schleswig]]\n|\n|-\n|{{flag|England}}\n|{{flag|Monmouthshire}}\n|The [[English Democrats Party]] are irredentist in regards to [[Monmouthshire (historic)|Monmouthshire]] (since 1974 part of Wales).<ref name=\"EDPmanifesto\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/shared/bsp/hi/pdfs/EDP_uk_manifesto.pdf|title=Manifesto of the English Democrats: Putting England First|date=2005|accessdate=25 April 2016|publisher=[[bbc.co.uk]]|format=PDF}}</ref>\n|-\n|{{flag|Estonia}}\n| ''Parts of:''<br />\n{{flag|Russia}}\n|\n|-\n|{{flag|Finland}}\n|{{flag|Karelia}}\n|\n|-\n|{{flag|Greece}}\n|{{flag|Cyprus}}\n''Parts of:''<br />\n{{flag|Turkey}}<br />{{flag|Albania}}\n|The [[Megali Idea]] became a political objective of the Greek government in the early 20th century. It envisioned a \"Greater Greece\" covering areas of earlier Greek empires where significant Greek settlements still existed. The idea ended with the devastating defeat of the Greek army in  Asia Minor in 1922 and the following [[population exchange between Greece and Turkey]].<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Finefrock |first1=Michael M. |title=Ataturk, Lloyd George and the Megali Idea: Cause and Consequence of the Greek Plan to Seize Constantinople from the Allies, June-August 1922 |journal=The Journal of Modern History |date=March 1980 |volume=52 |issue=S1 |url=https://www.journals.uchicago.edu/doi/pdfplus/10.1086/242238 |accessdate=26 October 2019 |publisher=The University of Chicago Press Books}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=The Greek Turkish Population Exchange |url=https://cmes.arizona.edu/sites/cmes.arizona.edu/files/3.%20Case%20study%20-%20Greek%20Turkish%20Population%20Exchange_1.pdf |accessdate=26 October 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n|{{flag|Georgia}}\n|''Parts of:''<br />\n{{flag|Turkey}}<br />{{flag|Russia}}<br />{{flag|Azerbaijan}}<br />{{flag|Armenia}}\n|Georgian irredentists claim [[Tao-Klarjeti]] \n|-\n|{{flag|Germany}}\n|{{flag|Austria}}<br />{{flag|Luxembourg}}<br />{{flag|Liechtenstein}}\n\n''Parts of:''<br />\n{{flag|Belgium}}<br />{{flag|Poland}}<br />{{flag|Lithuania}}<br />{{flag|Russia}}<br />{{flag|Denmark}}<br />{{flag|France}}<br />{{flag|Czech Republic}}<br />{{flag|Hungary}}<br />{{flag|Slovakia}}<br />{{flag|Italy}}<br />{{flag|Slovenia}}\n|\n|-\n|{{flag|Hungary}}\n|''Parts of:''<br />\n{{flag|Slovakia}}<br />{{flag|Romania}}<br />{{flag|Serbia}}<br />{{flag|Ukraine}}<br />{{flag|Austria}}\n|\n|-\n|{{flag|Italy}}\n|{{flag|Malta}}<br />\n''Parts of:''<br />{{flag|Albania}}<br />{{flag|Croatia}}<br />{{flag|France}}\n\n|[[Italy|Italian]] claims to [[Istria]] and [[Dalmatia]] after [[World War I]]. \n|-\n|{{flag|North Macedonia}}\n|''Parts of:''<br />\n{{flag|Greece}}<br />{{flag|Bulgaria}}<br />{{flag|Albania}}\n|Irredentists from North Macedonia have expressed land claims to the entire historical region of [[Macedonia (region)|Macedonia]]\n|-\n|{{flag|Norway}}\n|{{flag|Greenland}}<br />{{flag|Faroe Islands}}<br />{{flag|Shetland}}<br />{{flag|Orkney}}\n\n''Parts of:''<br />\n{{flag|Sweden}}\n\n|-\n|{{flag|Poland}}\n|''Parts of:''<br />\n{{flag|Belarus}}<br />{{flag|Ukraine}}<br />{{flag|Lithuania}}<br />{{flag|Czech Republic}}\n|\n|-\n|{{flag|Romania}}\n|{{flag|Moldova}}\n\n''Parts of:''<br />\n{{flag|Bulgaria}}<br />{{flag|Ukraine}}\n|\n|-\n|{{flag|Serbia}}\n|{{flag|Kosovo}}\n\n''Parts of:''<br />\n{{flag|Bosnia and Herzegovina}}<br />{{flag|Croatia}}<br />{{flag|North Macedonia}}<br />{{flag|Montenegro}}\n|\n|-\n|{{flag|Slovenia}}\n|''Parts of:''<br />\n{{flag|Italy}}<br />{{flag|Austria}}<br />{{flag|Croatia}}\n|\n\n|-\n|{{flag|Turkey}}\n|{{flag|Cyprus}}<br />{{flag|Crimea}}\n\n''Parts of:''<br />\n{{flag|Syria}}<br />{{flag|Iraq}}<br />{{flag|Greece}}<br />{{flag|Bulgaria}}<br />{{flag|Armenia}}<br />{{flag|Azerbaijan}}<br />{{flag|Georgia}}<br />{{flag|Iran}}<br />\n|\n\n|-\n|{{flag|Ukraine}}\n|''Parts of:''<br />\n{{flag|Transnistria}}<br />{{flag|Romania}}<br />{{flag|Slovakia}}<br />{{flag|Poland}}<br />{{flag|Belarus}}<br />{{flag|Russia}}\n|\n|}\n*In the 1955 referendum, [[Saarland]], a previous [[Saarland Protectorate|French protectorate territory]], [[1955 Saar Statute referendum|voted]] to reunite with [[Germany]].\n* [[France|French]] claimed [[Alsace-Lorraine]] before [[World War I]], after which the territory was returned to them.\n* [[Bulgaria]], [[Serbia]], [[Greece]] and [[Montenegro]] claimed various European parts of the Ottoman Empire and Albania (both of which the four divided among themselves) before the [[First Balkan War]], where they took these claims to the battlefield, and won.\n\n===Asia===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! scope=\"col\" width=\"130\" | State\n! scope=\"col\" width=\"150\" | Claimed area\n! Notes\n|-\n|{{flag|Afghanistan}}\n|''Parts of:''<br />\n{{flag|Pakistan}}\n|\n|-\n|{{flag|Cambodia}}\n|''Parts of:''<br />\n{{flag|Vietnam}}\n|\n|-\n|{{flag|People's Republic of China}}\n|{{flag|Republic of China}}\n|\n|-\n|{{flag|People's Republic of China}}\n|[[Arunachal Pradesh]]\n({{flag|India}})\n|\n|-\n|{{flag|Democratic People's Republic of Korea}}\n|{{flag|Republic of Korea}}\n|\n|-\n|{{flag|India}}\n|{{flag|Azad Kashmir}}<br />{{flag|Gilgit-Baltistan}}\n\n''Part of -''\n\n''[[Pakistan|Islamic Republic of Pakistan]]''\n\n'''And'''\n\n[[Aksai Chin]]\n\n[[Tibet Autonomous Region]]\n \n\nPart of-<br />{{flag|People's Republic of China}}\n|\n|-\n|{{flag|Japan}}\n|[[Kuril Islands]]<br />\n({{flag|Russia}})\n|\n|-\n|{{flag|Pakistan}}\n|[[Jammu and Kashmir]] \n({{flag|India}})\n|\n|-\n|{{flag|Philippines}}\n|''Parts of:''<br />\n{{flag|Sabah}}<br />\n({{flag|Malaysia}})\n|\n|-\n|{{flag|Republic of China}}\n|{{flag|People's Republic of China}}\n|\n|-\n|{{flag|Republic of China}}\n|{{flag|Tuva}}<br />{{flag|Mongolia}}\n|\n|-\n|{{flag|Republic of Korea}}\n|{{flag|Democratic People's Republic of Korea}}\n|\n|}\n\n====Middle East====\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! scope=\"col\" width=\"130\" | State\n! scope=\"col\" width=\"150\" | Claimed area\n! Notes\n|-\n|{{flag|Iraq}}\n|{{flag|Kuwait}}\n|\n|-\n|{{flag|Iraq}}\n|{{flag|Khuzestan}}<br />\n({{flag|Iran}})\n|\n|-\n|{{flag|Iraqi Kurdistan}}\n|{{flag|Iraq}}\n|\n|-\n|{{flag|Israel}}\n|{{flag|Palestine}}\n|\n|-\n|{{flag|Lebanon}}\n|''Parts of:''<br />\n{{flag|Israel}}\n|\n|-\n|{{flag|Palestine}}\n|{{flag|Israel}}<br />{{flag|Jordan}}\n|\n|-\n|{{flag|Syria}}\n|\n({{flag|Israel}})\n|\n|-\n|{{flag|Syria}}\n|[[Hatay]]\n({{flag|Turkey}})\n|\n|}\n\n===South and Central America===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! scope=\"col\" width=\"130\" | State\n! scope=\"col\" width=\"150\" | Claimed area\n! Notes\n|-\n|{{flag|Argentina}}\n|{{flag|Falkland Islands}} {{flag|South Georgia and the South Sandwich Islands}}<br />\n|[[Argentina]] claims land in the South Atlantic and Antartica, including the [[Falkland Islands]]\n|-\n|{{flag|Bolivia}}\n|''Parts of:''<br />\n{{flag|Chile}}\n|\n|-\n|{{flag|Chile}}\n|''Parts of:''<br />\n{{flag|Argentina}}\n|\n|-\n|{{flag|Guanacaste}}\n|{{flag|Puntarenas}}\n|\n|-\n|{{flag|Guatemala}}\n|''Parts of:''<br/>\n{{flag|Belize}}\n|Referred to the [[International Court of Justice]] since 2019.\n|-\n|{{flag|Nicaragua}}\n|''Parts of:''<br />\n{{flag|Costa Rica}}<br />{{flag|Colombia}}\n|\n|-\n|{{flag|Venezuela}}\n|''Parts of:''<br />\n{{flag|Guyana}}\n|\n|}\n\n===North America===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! scope=\"col\" width=\"130\" | State\n! scope=\"col\" width=\"150\" | Claimed area\n! Notes\n|-\n\n|-\n|{{flag|Quebec}}\n|{{flag|Labrador}}\n|The Quebec government claims that the territory of [[Labrador]] belongs to the province of [[Quebec]]. [[Labrador]] is part of the province of [[Newfoundland and Labrador]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mef.qc.ca/question_du_labrador.htm|title=La question du Labrador|date=2 May 2001|work=Estrien Movement for French|language=fr|trans-title=The question Labrador|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050426064023/http://www.mef.qc.ca/question_du_labrador.htm|archivedate=26 April 2005|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n|}\n\n===Africa===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! scope=\"col\" width=\"130\" | State\n! scope=\"col\" width=\"150\" | Claimed area\n! Notes\n|-\n|{{flag|Comoros}}\n|{{flag|Mayotte}}\n|\n|-\n|{{flag|Madagascar}}\n|''Parts of:''<br />\n{{flag|France}}\n|\n|-\n|{{flag|Mauritania}}\n|{{flag|Western Sahara}}<br />{{flag|Azawad}}\n\n''Parts of:''<br />\n{{flag|Mali}}<br />{{flag|Niger}}\n|\n|-\n|{{flag|Morocco}}\n|{{flag|Western Sahara}}<br />{{flag|Madeira}}<br />{{flag|Canary Islands}}<br />{{flag|Mauritania}}<br />{{flag|Ceuta}}<br />{{flag|Melilla}}\n\n''Parts of:''<br />\n{{flag|Algeria}}<br />{{flag|Mali}}\n|\n|-\n|{{flag|Puntland}}\n|''Parts of:''<br />\n{{flag|Somaliland}}\n|rowspan=\"2\"|\n|-\n|{{flag|Somaliland}}\n|''Parts of:''<br />\n{{flag|Puntland}}\n|-\n|{{flag|Somalia}}\n|''Parts of:''<br />\n{{flag|Ethiopia}}<br />\n{{flag|Kenya}}\n|\n|}\n\n==See also==\n* [[Ethnic nationalism]]\n* [[Ethnic cleansing]]\n* [[Identity politics]]\n* [[Lebensraum]]\n* [[Revanchism]]\n* [[Status quo ante bellum]]\n* [[Manifest destiny]]\n* [[Historical powers]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Irredentism}}\n{{Secession in Countries}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:List Of Irredentist Claims Or Disputes}}\n[[Category:Irredentism|*]]\n", "name_user": "Schicksal345", "label": "safe", "comment": "Sweden has considerd to recover Finland ever since it was lost. Even today fringe nationalist movements want to recover it. There has also been movement within Finland to join Sweden called the \"East swedes movement\".", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_irredentist_claims_or_disputes"}
{"title_page": "The Disappearance (1997 TV series)", "text_new": "{{Infobox television\n| show_name                = The Disappearance\n| image                    = TheDisappearance.webp\n| image_size               = \n| image_alt                = \n| caption                  = Official poster\n| show_name_2              = \n| native_name          = {{Infobox name module|\n| traditional          = \u96b1\u5f62\u602a\u5091\n| simplified           = \u9690\u5f62\u602a\u6770\n| pinyin               = Y\u01d0n X\u00edng Gu\u00e0i Ji\u00e9\n| jyutping             = Jan2 Jing4 Gwaai3 Git6}}\n| genre                    = [[Science fiction]]<br>[[Comedy]]\n| creator                  = \n| based_on                 = \n| developer                = \n| writer                   = Chu King-kei<br>Lau Siu-kwan<br>Lo Mei-wan<br>Au Yuk-han<br>Cheung Chung-chai<br>Ng Lap-kwong<br>[[Au Kin-yee]]\n| director                 = Ng Chung-chai<br>[[Law Wing-cheung]]<br>Wong Kwok-keung<br>Leung Tak-wah\n| creative_director        = \n| presenter                = \n| starring                 = [[Gordon Lam]]<br>[[Mariane Chan]]<br>[[Bowie Lam]]<br>[[Astrid Chan]]<br>[[Edmond Leung]]<br>[[Kenneth Chan Kai-tai|Kenneth Chan]]<br>Emily Kwan<br>Wong Ching<br>Emotion Cheung<br>[[Miriam Yeung]]\n| judges                   = \n| voices                   = \n| narrated                 = \n| theme_music_composer     = James Ting\n| opentheme                = ''Invisible'' (\u900f\u660e) by Edmond Leung\n| endtheme                 = ''Best Friend'' (\u597d\u670b\u53cb) by Edmond Leung\n| composer                 = Mahmood Rumjahn\n| country                  = Hong Kong\n| language                 = [[Cantonese]]\n| num_seasons              = \n| num_episodes             = 20\n| list_episodes            = \n| executive_producer       = \n| producer                 = Yeung Kam-chuen\n| editor                   = \n| location                 = [[Hong Kong]]\n| cinematography           = \n| camera                   = \n| runtime                  = \n| company                  = [[TVB]]\n| distributor              = \n| channel                  = [[TVB Jade]]\n| picture_format           = \n| audio_format             = \n| first_run                =\n| first_aired              = {{Start date|df=y|1997|10|27}}\n| last_aired               = {{End date|df=y|1997|11|21}}\n| preceded_by              = \n| followed_by              = \n| related                  = \n| website                  = https://www.encoretvb.com/cantonese/series/1301-The_Disappearance\n| website_title            = \n| production_website       = \n| production_website_title = \n}}\n\n'''''The Disappearance''''' is a 1997 Hong Kong [[science fiction]] [[comedy]] television series produced by [[TVB]] and starring [[Gordon Lam]] as a magazine journalist who drinks a potion which grants him [[invisibility]], and uses it expose criminals and help others around him. The series aired on [[TVB Jade]] from 27 October to 21 November 1997.\n\n==Plot==\nAu Chi-lap ([[Gordon Lam]]) is an optimistic magazine journalist who lives a simple, yet happy life with his parents and stepsister ([[Miriam Yeung]]). His life changes when he becomes embroiled in a jewelry theft case. Chan Shui-cheng ([[Bowie Lam]]), a fellow townsman of the Au family, arrives in [[Hong Kong]] to live with the Aus. Shui-cheng, who worked as an assistant to a scientist in [[Hunan]], insists the jewelry theft is an invisible person who drank a potion created by the scientist. Shui-cheng investigates this with the help from San Hiu-lam ([[Mariane Chan]]), the Aus' new neighbor who is a well-meaning, ambitious but clumsy beat cop. Chi-lap also joins in as he does not believe Shui-cheng's bizarre claims and thinks the latter is trying to con Hiu-lam. \n\nNot long after, Chi-lap is framed by the chief editor of a rival magazine company, Victor Tsui ([[Kenneth Chan Kai-tai|Kenneth Chan]]) for fabricating false news, which causes his employer to face criminal charges. When Chi-lap finds out that Shui-cheng's claims about invisibility were true, he drinks a bottle of the potion kept by Shui-cheng achieves invisibility in order to gather evidence against Victor and save his magazine company. \n\nLater, Chi-lap also encounters and works with Victor's girlfriend, Wing Cheuk ([[Astrid Chan]]), whom he was a never a fan of. One time when they were on a job to interview a [[Triad (organized crime)|triad]] boss in [[Huidong County, Guangdong]], Chi-lap uses his invisibility to save Wing from an attack from the triads which left her temporary blind, so she did not find out about this secret. The two become friends afterwards and Chi-lap warns Wing about Victor, who is using her to get rich since she is the daughter of a rich tycoon, but she dismisses Chi-lap's claims. By chance, Wing finds out Victor's scheme and breaks up with him, while Chi-lap comforts her during this rough period and their relationship bossoms into a romance. After losing his opportunity to strike fortune, Victor is bent on seeking revenge on Chi-lap for getting in his way.\n\n==Cast==\n===The Au family===\n*Wong Ching as '''Au Wing-kuen''' (\u5340\u6c38\u6b0a), Chi-lap's father who works as a security officer.\n*Mannor Chan as '''Au Lee Siu-foon''' (\u5340\u674e\u7b11\u6b61), Wing-kuen's second wife who is Chi-lap's stepmother and San-san's mother.\n*[[Gordon Lam]] as '''Au Chi-lap''' (\u5340\u5fd7\u7acb), a journalist for \"Chuen Chun Weekly\" (\u50b3\u771f\u9031\u520a) who achieves [[invisibility]] after drinking a potion. He turns invisible once his heart rate goes up and would re-appear visible when Hiu-lam screams.\n*[[Miriam Yeung]] as '''Au San-san''' (\u5340\u73ca\u73ca), Chi-lap's younger stepsister who owns a store with his stepbrother's friend and co-worker, Yat-sing, who she eventually develops a romance with.\n\n===The Cheung family===\n*Cheung Ying-choi as '''Cheung Siu-nin''' (\u8523\u5146\u5e74), chairman of the Cheung's Corporation and Wing's father who abandoned his first wife and Wing's mother Yuk-fun, in the past.\n*Alice Fung as '''Cheuk Yuk-fun''' (\u5353\u7389\u82ac), Siu-nin's ex-wife and Wing's mother who raised her daughter without relying on her ex-husband's wealth.\n*[[Mary Hon]] as '''Wong Man-na''' (\u738b\u66fc\u5a1c), Siu-nin's wife who swayed his husband in abandoning Yuk-fun and is eyeing on her husband's fortune.\n*Maggie Chan as '''Cheung Siu-ling''' (\u8523\u5146\u73b2), Siu-nin's younger sister who was used by Victor.\n*Lee Wai-man as '''Eric Cheung''' (\u8523\u5ead\u8c50), Siu-nin and Man-na's homosexual son who is a doctor. San-san initially had a crush on him and he used her to cover up his homosexuality to avoid shocking his father.\n*[[Astrid Chan]] as '''Wing Cheuk''' (\u5353\u7a4e), Siu-nin and Yuk-fun's daughter who is a fierce journalist who used to work for \"In Weekly\" (IN\u9031\u520a) before moving to \"Chuen Chun Weekly\" and working with Chi-lap. She initially dated Victor before discovering his deceptive side and later dates Chi-lap.\n\n===The San family===\n*Emily Kwan as '''San Hiu-man''' (\u8f9b\u66c9\u6587), Hiu-lam's older sister who is materialistic and only dates rich men. She is a well known novelist, though her recent works have been unsuccessfully.\n*[[Mariane Chan]] as '''San Hiu-lam''' (\u8f9b\u66c9\u5d50), Hiu-man's younger sister who is well-meaning, righteous and ambitious beat cop who later fulfills her dream of being a CID officer. She develops a crush on Chi-lap after spending with him and when he saved her from criminals.\n\n===Chuen Chun Weekly===\n*Wong San as '''Kwong Cheung-leung''' (\u913a\u660c\u826f), owner of \"Chuen Chun Weekly\" and Chi-lap's godfather.\n*Elton Loo as '''Kwong King-chuen''' (\u913a\u666f\u5168),  known as '''King Sir''', Cheung-leung's son and  chief editor of \"Chuen Chun Weekly\".\n*[[Edmond Leung]] as '''Ho Yat-sing''' (\u4f55\u4e00\u6210), Chi-lap's friend and colleague who likes to take his job easy. He operates a store with San-san who eventually becomes his girlfriend.\n*Chiu Hung as '''Master Chow''' (\u5468\u516c), a veteran journalist for \"Chuen Chun Weekly\".\n*Vivian Tsang as '''Mary''', a journalist for \"Chuen Chun Weekly\".\n*Wong Wai-lam as '''Keung''' (\u963f\u5f37), a stuttering journalist for \"Chuen Chun Weekly\".\n*Ng Sze-ling as '''Cat''',  journalist for \"Chuen Chun Weekly\".\n\n===Other cast===\n*[[Bowie Lam]] as '''Chan Shui-cheng''' (\u9673\u6c34\u4e95), an assistant for a scientist from [[Hunan]] who invented to potion to invisibility. He arrives in [[Hong Kong]] and lives in the Au household and develops a crush on Hiu-man, who ridicues his low social status and eccentric behavior.\n*[[Kenneth Chan Kai-tai|Kenneth Chan]] as '''Victor Tsui''' (\u5f90\u529b\u5716), chief editor of \"In Weekly\" who is involved in numerous illegal activities. He initially dated Wing before he found out about her rich family background and cheated on her, but afterwards, schemed to accumulate fortune through Wing but was foiled.\n*Emotion Cheung as '''Sze-ma Tat-wah''' (\u53f8\u99ac\u9054\u83ef), Hiu-lam's superior officer who suspects Chi-lap using his  invisibility to commit crimes. He pursues Hiu-lam after mistakenly believing she had a crush on him, when in reality, she was in love with Chi-lap.\n*[[Eileen Yeow]] as '''Apple''', Chi-lap's ex-girlfriend and first love who left him to become a singer in [[Taiwan]].\n*Wong Wai-tak as '''Ben''', Victor's assistant.\n*Ip Chun-sing as '''Fai''' (\u963f\u8f1d), Tat-wah's subordinate.\n*Mak Ka-lun as Tat-wah's subordinate.\n*Leung Chiu-ho as Tat-wah's subordinate.\n*Tang Yu-chiu as Tat-wah's subordinate.\n*[[Hoi Sang Lee]] as '''Wong Piu''' (\u738b\u5f6a), Man-na's older brother who schemes with his sister to accumulate Siu-nin's fortune.\n*Forrest Chan as '''Brother Tung''' (\u6771\u54e5), a rich tycoon and owner of the \"Star of Bangladesh\" diamond.\n*[[Angela Tong]] as '''Sister Chi''' (\u679d\u59d0), Brother Tung's girlfriend.\n*Ben Wong as the scientist who invented the potion of invisibility and Shui-cheng's former employer.\n*Sit Sung-kei as the first invisible who killed the scientist and took his potion and used it to steal the \"Star of Bangladesh\".\n*Bruce Li as '''Stephen''', a lawyer who pursed Hiu-man but was lustful toward Hiu-lam at the same time.\n*Ling Hon as the manager of the building where the Aus and Sans live in.\n*Cheung Hung-cheung as '''Lam Kwok-fu''' (\u6797\u570b\u5bcc), Apple's abusive boyfriend and is a rich tycoon who colludes with Victor.\n*Vincent Cheung as Lam Kwok-fu's underling.\n*Irene Wong as '''Daisy''', San-san's friend who dated Yat-sing before dumping him for another man.\n*Andy Tai as '''Bob Lee''', Hiu-man's ex-boyfriend who used her to scam money to start a business.\n*Lee Ka-keung as '''David''', Eric's boyfriend.\n*Siu Cheuk-yiu as a thug hired by Wong Piu and Man-na to kidnap Siu-nin.\n*Yau Piu as a thug hired by Wong Piu and Man-na to kidnap Siu-nin.\n*[[Ruco Chan]] as '''Chan Chi-cha''' (\u9673\u5fd7\u9f4a), a security officer for Cheung's Corporation who was bribed by Victor.\n*Chan Min-leung as a security officer for Cheung's Corporation.\n\n==Reception==\nDue to the series' unusual theme different from the typical prime time series during that era, it premiered with rather low ratings. However, by its finale, the series has reached a rating of 30 points.<ref name=hk>{{cite web|url=https://www.hk01.com/%E5%8D%B3%E6%99%82%E5%A8%9B%E6%A8%82/83420/%E6%9E%97%E5%AE%B6%E6%A3%9F%E7%9A%84%E7%B5%82%E6%A5%B5%E7%A5%9E%E5%8A%87-%E9%9A%B1%E5%BD%A2%E6%80%AA%E5%82%91-%E9%A1%8C%E6%9D%90%E5%A4%AA%E6%96%B0%E7%A9%8E%E6%94%B6%E8%A6%96%E6%9B%BE-%E6%8F%92%E6%B0%B4|title=\u6797\u5bb6\u68df\u7684\u7d42\u6975\u795e\u5287\u3000\u300a\u96b1\u5f62\u602a\u5091\u300b\u984c\u6750\u592a\u65b0\u7a4e\u6536\u8996\u66fe\u300c\u63d2\u6c34\u300d}}</ref>\n\nOn [[Douban]], ''The Disappeance'' has a score of 7.5/10 stars.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.douban.com/doubanapp/dispatch?uri=/movie/4034054&|title=\u9690\u5f62\u602a\u6770 (1997)}}</ref>\n\nThe series has been accused of plagerizing the [[Invisible Man (film series)|''Invisible Man'' film series]] and the Japanese television series, ''Toumen Ningen''.<ref name=hk/>\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of TVB series (1997)]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*''[https://programme.mytvsuper.com/tc/116228/%E9%9A%B1%E5%BD%A2%E6%80%AA%E5%82%91 The Disappeance]'' MyTV Super\n\n[[Category:Hong Kong television series]]\n[[Category:TVB dramas]]\n[[Category:Hong Kong comedy television series]]\n[[Category:1990s comic science fiction television series]]\n[[Category:1997 Hong Kong television series debuts]]\n[[Category:1997 Hong Kong television series endings]]\n[[Category:Serial drama television series]]\n[[Category:Cantonese-language television programs]]\n[[Category:Television series about journalists]]\n[[Category:Television shows set in Hong Kong]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox television\n| show_name                = The Disappearance\n| image                    = TheDisappearance.webp\n| image_size               = \n| image_alt                = \n| caption                  = Official poster\n| show_name_2              = \n| native_name          = {{Infobox name module|\n| traditional          = \u96b1\u5f62\u602a\u5091\n| simplified           = \u9690\u5f62\u602a\u6770\n| pinyin               = Y\u01d0n X\u00edng Gu\u00e0i Ji\u00e9\n| jyutping             = Jan2 Jing4 Gwaai3 Git6}}\n| genre                    = [[Science fiction]]<br>[[Comedy]]\n| creator                  = \n| based_on                 = \n| developer                = \n| writer                   = Chu King-kei<br>Lau Siu-kwan<br>Lo Mei-wan<br>Au Yuk-han<br>Cheung Chung-chai<br>Ng Lap-kwong<br>[[Au Kin-yee]]\n| director                 = Ng Chung-chai<br>[[Law Wing-cheung]]<br>Wong Kwok-keung<br>Leung Tak-wah\n| creative_director        = \n| presenter                = \n| starring                 = [[Gordon Lam]]<br>[[Mariane Chan]]<br>[[Bowie Lam]]<br>[[Astrid Chan]]<br>[[Edmond Leung]]<br>[[Kenneth Chan Kai-tai|Kenneth Chan]]<br>Emily Kwan<br>Wong Ching<br>Emotion Cheung<br>[[Miriam Yeung]]\n| judges                   = \n| voices                   = \n| narrated                 = \n| theme_music_composer     = James Ting\n| opentheme                = ''Invisible'' (\u900f\u660e) by Edmond Leung\n| endtheme                 = ''Best Friend'' (\u597d\u670b\u53cb) by Edmond Leung\n| composer                 = Mahmood Rumjahn\n| country                  = Hong Kong\n| language                 = [[Cantonese]]\n| num_seasons              = \n| num_episodes             = 20\n| list_episodes            = \n| executive_producer       = \n| producer                 = Yeung Kam-chuen\n| editor                   = \n| location                 = [[Hong Kong]]\n| cinematography           = \n| camera                   = \n| runtime                  = \n| company                  = [[TVB]]\n| distributor              = \n| channel                  = [[TVB Jade]]\n| picture_format           = \n| audio_format             = \n| first_run                =\n| first_aired              = {{Start date|df=y|1997|10|27}}\n| last_aired               = {{End date|df=y|1997|11|21}}\n| preceded_by              = \n| followed_by              = \n| related                  = \n| website                  = https://www.encoretvb.com/cantonese/series/1301-The_Disappearance\n| website_title            = \n| production_website       = \n| production_website_title = \n}}\n\n'''''The Disappearance''''' is a 1997 Hong Kong [[science fiction]] [[comedy]] television series produced by [[TVB]] and starring [[Gordon Lam]] as a magazine journalist who drinks a potion which grants him [[invisibility]], and uses it expose criminals and help others around him. The series aired on [[TVB Jade]] from 27 October to 21 November 1997.\n\n==Plot==\nAu Chi-lap ([[Gordon Lam]]) is an optimistic magazine journalist who lives a simple, yet happy life with his parents and stepsister ([[Miriam Yeung]]). His life changes when he becomes embroiled in a jewelry theft case. Chan Shui-cheng ([[Bowie Lam]]), a fellow townsman of the Au family, arrives in [[Hong Kong]] to live with the Aus. Shui-cheng, who worked as an assistant to a scientist in [[Hunan]], insists the jewelry theft is an invisible person who drank a potion created by the scientist. Shui-cheng investigates this with the help from San Hiu-lam ([[Mariane Chan]]), the Aus' new neighbor who is a well-meaning, ambitious but clumsy beat cop. Chi-lap also joins in as he does not believe Shui-cheng's bizarre claims and thinks the latter is trying to con Hiu-lam. \n\nNot long after, Chi-lap is framed by the chief editor of a rival magazine company, Victor Tsui ([[Kenneth Chan Kai-tai|Kenneth Chan]]) for fabricating false news, which causes his employer to face criminal charges. When Chi-lap finds out that Shui-cheng's claims about invisibility were true, he drinks a bottle of the potion kept by Shui-cheng achieves invisibility in order to gather evidence against Victor and save his magazine company. \n\nLater, Chi-lap also encounters and works with Victor's girlfriend, Wing Cheuk ([[Astrid Chan]]), whom he was a never a fan of. One time when they were on a job to to interview a [[Triad (organized crime)|triad]] boss in [[Huidong County, Guangdong]], Chi-lap uses his invisibility to save Wing from an attack from the triads which left her temporary blind, so she did not find out about this secret. The two become friends afterwards and Chi-lap warns Wing about Victor, who is using her to get rich since she is the daughter of a rich tycoon, but she dismisses Chi-lap's claims. By chance, Wing finds out Victor's scheme and breaks up with him, while Chi-lap comforts her during this rough period and their relationship bossoms into a romance. After losing his opportunity to strike fortune, Victor is bent on seeking revenge on Chi-lap for getting in his way.\n\n==Cast==\n===The Au family===\n*Wong Ching as '''Au Wing-kuen''' (\u5340\u6c38\u6b0a), Chi-lap's father who works as a security officer.\n*Mannor Chan as '''Au Lee Siu-foon''' (\u5340\u674e\u7b11\u6b61), Wing-kuen's second wife who is Chi-lap's stepmother and San-san's mother.\n*[[Gordon Lam]] as '''Au Chi-lap''' (\u5340\u5fd7\u7acb), a journalist for \"Chuen Chun Weekly\" (\u50b3\u771f\u9031\u520a) who achieves [[invisibility]] after drinking a potion. He turns invisible once his heart rate goes up and would re-appear visible when Hiu-lam screams.\n*[[Miriam Yeung]] as '''Au San-san''' (\u5340\u73ca\u73ca), Chi-lap's younger stepsister who owns a store with his stepbrother's friend and co-worker, Yat-sing, who she eventually develops a romance with.\n\n===The Cheung family===\n*Cheung Ying-choi as '''Cheung Siu-nin''' (\u8523\u5146\u5e74), chairman of the Cheung's Corporation and Wing's father who abandoned his first wife and Wing's mother Yuk-fun, in the past.\n*Alice Fung as '''Cheuk Yuk-fun''' (\u5353\u7389\u82ac), Siu-nin's ex-wife and Wing's mother who raised her daughter without relying on her ex-husband's wealth.\n*[[Mary Hon]] as '''Wong Man-na''' (\u738b\u66fc\u5a1c), Siu-nin's wife who swayed his husband in abandoning Yuk-fun and is eyeing on her husband's fortune.\n*Maggie Chan as '''Cheung Siu-ling''' (\u8523\u5146\u73b2), Siu-nin's younger sister who was used by Victor.\n*Lee Wai-man as '''Eric Cheung''' (\u8523\u5ead\u8c50), Siu-nin and Man-na's homosexual son who is a doctor. San-san initially had a crush on him and he used her to cover up his homosexuality to avoid shocking his father.\n*[[Astrid Chan]] as '''Wing Cheuk''' (\u5353\u7a4e), Siu-nin and Yuk-fun's daughter who is a fierce journalist who used to work for \"In Weekly\" (IN\u9031\u520a) before moving to \"Chuen Chun Weekly\" and working with Chi-lap. She initially dated Victor before discovering his deceptive side and later dates Chi-lap.\n\n===The San family===\n*Emily Kwan as '''San Hiu-man''' (\u8f9b\u66c9\u6587), Hiu-lam's older sister who is materialistic and only dates rich men. She is a well known novelist, though her recent works have been unsuccessfully.\n*[[Mariane Chan]] as '''San Hiu-lam''' (\u8f9b\u66c9\u5d50), Hiu-man's younger sister who is well-meaning, righteous and ambitious beat cop who later fulfills her dream of being a CID officer. She develops a crush on Chi-lap after spending with him and when he saved her from criminals.\n\n===Chuen Chun Weekly===\n*Wong San as '''Kwong Cheung-leung''' (\u913a\u660c\u826f), owner of \"Chuen Chun Weekly\" and Chi-lap's godfather.\n*Elton Loo as '''Kwong King-chuen''' (\u913a\u666f\u5168),  known as '''King Sir''', Cheung-leung's son and  chief editor of \"Chuen Chun Weekly\".\n*[[Edmond Leung]] as '''Ho Yat-sing''' (\u4f55\u4e00\u6210), Chi-lap's friend and colleague who likes to take his job easy. He operates a store with San-san who eventually becomes his girlfriend.\n*Chiu Hung as '''Master Chow''' (\u5468\u516c), a veteran journalist for \"Chuen Chun Weekly\".\n*Vivian Tsang as '''Mary''', a journalist for \"Chuen Chun Weekly\".\n*Wong Wai-lam as '''Keung''' (\u963f\u5f37), a stuttering journalist for \"Chuen Chun Weekly\".\n*Ng Sze-ling as '''Cat''',  journalist for \"Chuen Chun Weekly\".\n\n===Other cast===\n*[[Bowie Lam]] as '''Chan Shui-cheng''' (\u9673\u6c34\u4e95), an assistant for a scientist from [[Hunan]] who invented to potion to invisibility. He arrives in [[Hong Kong]] and lives in the Au household and develops a crush on Hiu-man, who ridicues his low social status and eccentric behavior.\n*[[Kenneth Chan Kai-tai|Kenneth Chan]] as '''Victor Tsui''' (\u5f90\u529b\u5716), chief editor of \"In Weekly\" who is involved in numerous illegal activities. He initially dated Wing before he found out about her rich family background and cheated on her, but afterwards, schemed to accumulate fortune through Wing but was foiled.\n*Emotion Cheung as '''Sze-ma Tat-wah